dom-document-visibilitystate.name: visibilityState
dom-document-visibilitystate.summary: The Document.visibilityState read-only property returns the visibility of the document, that is in which context this element is now visible. It is useful to know if the document is in the background or an invisible tab, or only loaded for pre-rendering.
dom-document-visibilitystate.title: Document: visibilityState property

dom-document-write-dev.name: write
dom-document-write-dev.summary: The document.write() method writes a string of text to a document stream opened by document.open().
dom-document-write-dev.title: document: write() method

dom-document-writeln-dev.name: writeln
dom-document-writeln-dev.summary: Writes a string of text followed by a newline character to a document.

chrome.notes: Only supported for HTMLDocument, not all Document objects.

opera.notes: Only supported for HTMLDocument, not all Document objects.

opera_android.notes: Only supported for HTMLDocument, not all Document objects.

safari.notes: Only supported for HTMLDocument, not all Document objects.

edge_blink.notes: Only supported for HTMLDocument, not all Document objects.

dom-document-writeln-dev.title: document: writeln() method

the-document-object.name: Document
the-document-object.summary: The Document interface represents any web page loaded in the browser and serves as an entry point into the web page's content, which is the DOM tree.
the-document-object.title: Document

the-dragevent-interface.name: DragEvent
the-dragevent-interface.summary: This constructor is used to create a synthetic DragEvent object.
the-dragevent-interface.title: DragEvent: DragEvent() constructor

the-dragevent-interface.name: DragEvent
the-dragevent-interface.summary: The DragEvent interface is a DOM event that represents a drag and drop interaction. The user initiates a drag by placing a pointer device (such as a mouse) on the touch surface and then dragging the pointer to a new location (such as another DOM element). Applications are free to interpret a drag and drop interaction in an application-specific way.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 10, DragEvent is exposed in standards mode but not quirks mode.

the-dragevent-interface.title: DragEvent

dom-dragevent-datatransfer-dev.name: dataTransfer
dom-dragevent-datatransfer-dev.summary: The DragEvent.dataTransfer property holds the drag operation's data (as a DataTransfer object).

ie.notes: The value is always null.

dom-dragevent-datatransfer-dev.title: DragEvent: dataTransfer property

handler-onauxclick.name: auxclick_event
handler-onauxclick.summary: The auxclick event is fired at an Element when a non-primary pointing device button (any mouse button other than the primaryusually leftmostbutton) has been pressed and released both within the same element.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 68, the auxclick event is used to trigger the new tab on middle-click action; previously, this had been done with the click event. Apps can prevent middle-click from opening new tabs (or middle-click to paste, if that feature is enabled) by intercepting auxclick on links, and auxclick event handlers can now open popups without triggering the popup blocker.

handler-onauxclick.title: Element: auxclick event

event-beforematch.name: beforematch_event
event-beforematch.summary: An element receives a beforematch event when it is in the hidden until found state and the browser is about to reveal its content because the user has found the content through the "find in page" feature or through fragment navigation.
event-beforematch.title: Element: beforematch event

handler-onblur.name: blur_event
handler-onblur.summary: The blur event fires when an element has lost focus. The event does not bubble, but the related focusout event that follows does bubble.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

handler-onblur.title: Element: blur event

handler-onblur.name: blur_event
handler-onblur.summary: The blur event fires when an element has lost focus.

notes: Apart from firing the event on window as other browsers do, Firefox also fires the event on the document object. See bug 1228802.
Before Firefox 24, the interface for this event is a plain Event, not FocusEvent.

handler-onblur.title: Window: blur event

handler-onclick.name: click_event
handler-onclick.summary: An element receives a click event when a pointing device button (such as a mouse's primary mouse button) is both pressed and released while the pointer is located inside the element.

firefox.notes: Beginning in Firefox 68, Firefox no longer incorrectly sends a click event for buttons other than the primary mouse button; previously, there were circumstances in which this would occur. One example: middle-clicking a link would send a click to the document's <html> element.

handler-onclick.title: Element: click event

handler-oncopy.name: copy_event
handler-oncopy.summary: The copy event fires when the user initiates a copy action through the browser's user interface.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 9, this event is not supported via addEventListener; however, the event handler is supported since IE 5.5. The event can be listened to via element.oncopy.

handler-oncopy.title: Element: copy event

handler-oncut.name: cut_event
handler-oncut.summary: The cut event is fired when the user has initiated a "cut" action through the browser's user interface.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 9, this event is not supported via addEventListener; however, the event handler is supported since IE 5.5. The event can be listened to via element.oncopy.

handler-oncut.title: Element: cut event

handler-ondblclick.name: dblclick_event
handler-ondblclick.summary: The dblclick event fires when a pointing device button (such as a mouse's primary button) is double-clicked; that is, when it's rapidly clicked twice on a single element within a very short span of time.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 68, dblclick events are only sent for the primary mouse button, per the specification.

handler-ondblclick.title: Element: dblclick event

handler-onfocus.name: focus_event
handler-onfocus.summary: The focus event fires when an element has received focus. The event does not bubble, but the related focusin event that follows does bubble.

firefox.notes: The interface for this event is Event, not FocusEvent.

handler-onfocus.title: Element: focus event

handler-onfocus.name: focus_event
handler-onfocus.summary: The focus event fires when an element has received focus.

notes: Apart from firing the event on window as other browsers do, Firefox also fires the event on the document object. See bug 1228802.
Before Firefox 24, the interface for this event is a plain Event, not FocusEvent.

handler-onfocus.title: Window: focus event

handler-onkeydown.name: keydown_event
handler-onkeydown.summary: The keydown event is fired when a key is pressed.
handler-onkeydown.title: Element: keydown event

handler-onkeyup.name: keyup_event
handler-onkeyup.summary: The keyup event is fired when a key is released.
handler-onkeyup.title: Element: keyup event

handler-onmousedown.name: mousedown_event
handler-onmousedown.summary: The mousedown event is fired at an Element when a pointing device button is pressed while the pointer is inside the element.
handler-onmousedown.title: Element: mousedown event

handler-onmouseenter.name: mouseenter_event
handler-onmouseenter.summary: The mouseenter event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is initially moved so that its hotspot is within the element at which the event was fired.
handler-onmouseenter.title: Element: mouseenter event

handler-onmouseleave.name: mouseleave_event
handler-onmouseleave.summary: The mouseleave event is fired at an Element when the cursor of a pointing device (usually a mouse) is moved out of it.
handler-onmouseleave.title: Element: mouseleave event

handler-onmousemove.name: mousemove_event
handler-onmousemove.summary: The mousemove event is fired at an element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is moved while the cursor's hotspot is inside it.
handler-onmousemove.title: Element: mousemove event

handler-onmouseout.name: mouseout_event
handler-onmouseout.summary: The mouseout event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (usually a mouse) is used to move the cursor so that it is no longer contained within the element or one of its children.
handler-onmouseout.title: Element: mouseout event

handler-onmouseover.name: mouseover_event
handler-onmouseover.summary: The mouseover event is fired at an Element when a pointing device (such as a mouse or trackpad) is used to move the cursor onto the element or one of its child elements.
handler-onmouseover.title: Element: mouseover event

handler-onmouseup.name: mouseup_event
handler-onmouseup.summary: The mouseup event is fired at an Element when a button on a pointing device (such as a mouse or trackpad) is released while the pointer is located inside it.
handler-onmouseup.title: Element: mouseup event

handler-onpaste.name: paste_event
handler-onpaste.summary: The paste event is fired when the user has initiated a "paste" action through the browser's user interface.

notes: Before Internet Explorer 11, copying files does not trigger the paste event.
Before Internet Explorer 9, this event is not supported via addEventListener; however, the event handler is supported since IE 5.5. The event can be listened to via element.oncopy.

handler-onpaste.title: Element: paste event

handler-onsecuritypolicyviolation.name: securitypolicyviolation_event
handler-onsecuritypolicyviolation.summary: The securitypolicyviolation event is fired when a Content Security Policy is violated.
handler-onsecuritypolicyviolation.title: Element: securitypolicyviolation event

handler-onwheel.name: wheel_event
handler-onwheel.summary: The wheel event fires when the user rotates a wheel button on a pointing device (typically a mouse).

ie.notes: The onwheel event handler property is not supported. To listen to this event, use element.addEventListener('wheel', function() {});. See IE bug 782835.

handler-onwheel.title: Element: wheel event

dom-elementinternals-checkvalidity.name: checkValidity
dom-elementinternals-checkvalidity.summary: The checkValidity() method of the ElementInternals interface checks if the element meets any constraint validation rules applied to it.
dom-elementinternals-checkvalidity.title: ElementInternals: checkValidity() method

dom-elementinternals-form.name: form
dom-elementinternals-form.summary: The form read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns the HTMLFormElement associated with this element.
dom-elementinternals-form.title: ElementInternals: form property

dom-elementinternals-labels.name: labels
dom-elementinternals-labels.summary: The labels read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns the labels associated with the element.
dom-elementinternals-labels.title: ElementInternals: labels property

dom-elementinternals-reportvalidity.name: reportValidity
dom-elementinternals-reportvalidity.summary: The reportValidity() method of the ElementInternals interface checks if the element meets any constraint validation rules applied to it.
dom-elementinternals-reportvalidity.title: ElementInternals: reportValidity() method

dom-elementinternals-setformvalue.name: setFormValue
dom-elementinternals-setformvalue.summary: The setFormValue() method of the ElementInternals interface sets the element's submission value and state, communicating these to the user agent.
dom-elementinternals-setformvalue.title: ElementInternals: setFormValue() method

dom-elementinternals-setvalidity.name: setValidity
dom-elementinternals-setvalidity.summary: The setValidity() method of the ElementInternals interface sets the validity of the element.
dom-elementinternals-setvalidity.title: ElementInternals: setValidity() method

dom-elementinternals-shadowroot.name: shadowRoot
dom-elementinternals-shadowroot.summary: The shadowRoot read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns the ShadowRoot for this element.
dom-elementinternals-shadowroot.title: ElementInternals: shadowRoot property

dom-elementinternals-validationmessage.name: validationMessage
dom-elementinternals-validationmessage.summary: The validationMessage read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns the validation message for the element.
dom-elementinternals-validationmessage.title: ElementInternals: validationMessage property

dom-elementinternals-validity.name: validity
dom-elementinternals-validity.summary: The validity read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns a ValidityState object which represents the different validity states the element can be in, with respect to constraint validation.
dom-elementinternals-validity.title: ElementInternals: validity property

dom-elementinternals-willvalidate.name: willValidate
dom-elementinternals-willvalidate.summary: The willValidate read-only property of the ElementInternals interface returns true if the element is a submittable element that is a candidate for constraint validation.
dom-elementinternals-willvalidate.title: ElementInternals: willValidate property

the-elementinternals-interface.name: ElementInternals
the-elementinternals-interface.summary: The ElementInternals interface of the Document Object Model gives web developers a way to allow custom elements to fully participate in HTML forms. It provides utilities for working with these elements in the same way you would work with any standard HTML form element, and also exposes the Accessibility Object Model to the element.

safari.notes: See bug 197960.

the-elementinternals-interface.title: ElementInternals

the-errorevent-interface.name: ErrorEvent
the-errorevent-interface.summary: The ErrorEvent interface represents events providing information related to errors in scripts or in files.
the-errorevent-interface.title: ErrorEvent

dom-eventsource-dev.name: EventSource
dom-eventsource-dev.summary: The EventSource() constructor returns a newly-created EventSource, which represents a remote resource.
dom-eventsource-dev.title: EventSource: EventSource() constructor

dom-eventsource-close-dev.name: close
dom-eventsource-close-dev.summary: The close() method of the EventSource interface closes the connection, if one is made, and sets the EventSource.readyState attribute to 2 (closed).
dom-eventsource-close-dev.title: EventSource: close() method

event-error.name: error_event
event-error.summary: The error event of the EventSource API is fired when a connection with an event source fails to be opened.
event-error.title: EventSource: error event

event-error.name: error_event
event-error.summary: The error event is fired on a Window object when a resource failed to load or couldn't be used  for example if a script has an execution error.
event-error.title: Window: error event

handler-eventsource-onerror.name: error_event
handler-eventsource-onerror.summary: The error event of the EventSource API is fired when a connection with an event source fails to be opened.
handler-eventsource-onerror.title: EventSource: error event

handler-eventsource-onmessage.name: message_event
handler-eventsource-onmessage.summary: The message event of the EventSource API is fired when data is received through an event source.
handler-eventsource-onmessage.title: EventSource: message event

event-open.name: open_event
event-open.summary: The open event of the EventSource API is fired when a connection with an event source is opened.
event-open.title: EventSource: open event

handler-eventsource-onopen.name: open_event
handler-eventsource-onopen.summary: The open event of the EventSource API is fired when a connection with an event source is opened.
handler-eventsource-onopen.title: EventSource: open event

dom-eventsource-readystate-dev.name: readyState
dom-eventsource-readystate-dev.summary: The readyState read-only property of the EventSource interface returns a number representing the state of the connection.
dom-eventsource-readystate-dev.title: EventSource: readyState property

dom-eventsource-url-dev.name: url
dom-eventsource-url-dev.summary: The url read-only property of the EventSource interface returns a string representing the URL of the source.
dom-eventsource-url-dev.title: EventSource: url property

dom-eventsource-withcredentials-dev.name: withCredentials
dom-eventsource-withcredentials-dev.summary: The withCredentials read-only property of the EventSource interface returns a boolean value indicating whether the EventSource object was instantiated with CORS credentials set.
dom-eventsource-withcredentials-dev.title: EventSource: withCredentials property

the-eventsource-interface.name: EventSource
the-eventsource-interface.summary: The EventSource interface is web content's interface to server-sent events.
the-eventsource-interface.title: EventSource

dom-input-files-dev.name: FileList
dom-input-files-dev.summary: An object of this type is returned by the files property of the HTML <input> element; this lets you access the list of files selected with the <input type="file"> element. It's also used for a list of files dropped into web content when using the drag and drop API; see the DataTransfer object for details on this usage.
dom-input-files-dev.title: FileList

dom-input-files-dev.name: files
dom-input-files-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.files property allows you to access the FileList selected with the <input type="file"> element.

ie.notes: This property is read-only.

dom-input-files-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: files property

the-formdataevent-interface.name: FormDataEvent
the-formdataevent-interface.summary: The FormDataEvent() constructor creates a new FormDataEvent object.
the-formdataevent-interface.title: FormDataEvent: FormDataEvent() constructor

the-formdataevent-interface.name: FormDataEvent
the-formdataevent-interface.summary: The FormDataEvent interface represents a formdata event  such an event is fired on an HTMLFormElement object after the entry list representing the form's data is constructed. This happens when the form is submitted, but can also be triggered by the invocation of a FormData() constructor.
the-formdataevent-interface.title: FormDataEvent

the-formdataevent-interface:dom-formdata.name: formData
the-formdataevent-interface:dom-formdata.summary: The formData read-only property of the FormDataEvent interface contains the FormData object representing the data contained in the form when the event was fired.
the-formdataevent-interface:dom-formdata.title: FormDataEvent: formData property

dom-a-download.name: download
dom-a-download.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.download property is a string indicating that the linked resource is intended to be downloaded rather than displayed in the browser. The value, if any, specifies the default file name for use in labeling the resource in a local file system. If the name is not a valid file name in the underlying OS, the browser will adjust it.
dom-a-download.title: HTMLAnchorElement: download property

dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.name: hash
dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.hash property returns a string containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL.

firefox.notes: From Firefox 29 to Firefox 40, the returned value was incorrectly percent-decoded.

dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: hash property

dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.name: hash
dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.hash property returns a string containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL.

firefox.notes: From Firefox 29 to Firefox 40, the returned value was incorrectly percent-decoded.

dom-hyperlink-hash-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: hash property

dom-hyperlink-host-dev.name: host
dom-hyperlink-host-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.host property is a string containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 9, the host of an <a> always include the port (e.g. developer.mozilla.org:443), even if there is no explicit port in the href attribute value.

dom-hyperlink-host-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: host property

dom-hyperlink-host-dev.name: host
dom-hyperlink-host-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.host property is a string containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 9, the host of an <a> always include the port (e.g. developer.mozilla.org:443), even if there is no explicit port in the href attribute value.

dom-hyperlink-host-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: host property

dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.name: hostname
dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.hostname property is a string containing the domain of the URL.
dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: hostname property

dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.name: hostname
dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.hostname property is a string containing the domain of the URL.
dom-hyperlink-hostname-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: hostname property

dom-hyperlink-href-dev.name: href
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.href property is a stringifier that returns a string containing the whole URL, and allows the href to be updated.
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: href property

dom-hyperlink-href-dev.name: toString
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.toString() stringifier method returns a string containing the whole URL. It is a read-only version of HTMLAnchorElement.href.
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: toString() method

dom-hyperlink-href-dev.name: href
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.href property is a stringifier that returns a string containing the whole URL, and allows the href to be updated.
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: href property

dom-hyperlink-href-dev.name: toString
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.toString() stringifier method returns a string containing the whole URL. It is a read-only version of HTMLAreaElement.href.
dom-hyperlink-href-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: toString() method

dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.name: origin
dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.origin read-only property is a string containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 49, results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: origin property

dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.name: origin
dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.origin read-only property is a string containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 49, results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

dom-hyperlink-origin-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: origin property

dom-hyperlink-password-dev.name: password
dom-hyperlink-password-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.password property is a string containing the password specified before the domain name.
dom-hyperlink-password-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: password property

dom-hyperlink-password-dev.name: password
dom-hyperlink-password-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.password property is a string containing the password specified before the domain name.
dom-hyperlink-password-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: password property

dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.name: pathname
dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.pathname property is a string containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL not including the query string or fragment (or the empty string if there is no path).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the pathname and search HTMLHyperlinkElementUtils properties returned the wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return '/x?a=true&b=false' and search would return '', rather than '/x' and '?a=true&b=false' respectively. This has now been fixed.

dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: pathname property

dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.name: pathname
dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.pathname property is a string containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL not including the query string or fragment (or the empty string if there is no path).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the pathname and search HTMLHyperlinkElementUtils properties returned the wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return '/x?a=true&b=false' and search would return '', rather than '/x' and '?a=true&b=false' respectively. This has now been fixed.

dom-hyperlink-pathname-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: pathname property

dom-hyperlink-port-dev.name: port
dom-hyperlink-port-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.port property is a string containing the port number of the URL. If the URL does not contain an explicit port number, it will be set to ''.
dom-hyperlink-port-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: port property

dom-hyperlink-port-dev.name: port
dom-hyperlink-port-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.port property is a string containing the port number of the URL. If the URL does not contain an explicit port number, it will be set to ''.
dom-hyperlink-port-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: port property

dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.name: protocol
dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.protocol property is a string representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: protocol property

dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.name: protocol
dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.protocol property is a string representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-hyperlink-protocol-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: protocol property

dom-a-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-a-referrerpolicy.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.referrerPolicy property reflect the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the <a> element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.
dom-a-referrerpolicy.title: HTMLAnchorElement: referrerPolicy property

dom-a-rel.name: rel
dom-a-rel.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.rel property reflects the rel attribute. It is a string containing a space-separated list of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <a> element and the current document.
dom-a-rel.title: HTMLAnchorElement: rel property

dom-a-rellist.name: relList
dom-a-rellist.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.relList read-only property reflects the rel attribute. It is a live DOMTokenList containing the set of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <a> element and the current document.
dom-a-rellist.title: HTMLAnchorElement: relList property

dom-hyperlink-search-dev.name: search
dom-hyperlink-search-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.search property is a search string, also called a query string, that is a string containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the pathname and search HTMLHyperlinkElementUtils properties returned the wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return '/x?a=true&b=false' and search would return '', rather than '/x' and '?a=true&b=false' respectively. This has now been fixed.

dom-hyperlink-search-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: search property

dom-hyperlink-search-dev.name: search
dom-hyperlink-search-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.search property is a search string, also called a query string, that is a string containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the pathname and search HTMLHyperlinkElementUtils properties returned the wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return '/x?a=true&b=false' and search would return '', rather than '/x' and '?a=true&b=false' respectively. This has now been fixed.

dom-hyperlink-search-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: search property

dom-hyperlink-username-dev.name: username
dom-hyperlink-username-dev.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.username property is a string containing the username specified before the domain name.
dom-hyperlink-username-dev.title: HTMLAnchorElement: username property

dom-hyperlink-username-dev.name: username
dom-hyperlink-username-dev.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.username property is a string containing the username specified before the domain name.
dom-hyperlink-username-dev.title: HTMLAreaElement: username property

htmlanchorelement.name: HTMLAnchorElement
htmlanchorelement.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement interface represents hyperlink elements and provides special properties and methods (beyond those of the regular HTMLElement object interface that they inherit from) for manipulating the layout and presentation of such elements. This interface corresponds to <a> element; not to be confused with <link>, which is represented by HTMLLinkElement)
htmlanchorelement.title: HTMLAnchorElement

dom-area-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-area-referrerpolicy.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.referrerPolicy property reflect the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the <area> element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.
dom-area-referrerpolicy.title: HTMLAreaElement: referrerPolicy property

dom-area-rel.name: rel
dom-area-rel.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.rel property reflects the rel attribute. It is a string containing a space-separated list of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <area> element and the current document.
dom-area-rel.title: HTMLAreaElement: rel property

dom-area-rellist.name: relList
dom-area-rellist.summary: The HTMLAreaElement.relList read-only property reflects the rel attribute. It is a live DOMTokenList containing the set of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <area> element and the current document.
dom-area-rellist.title: HTMLAreaElement: relList property

htmlareaelement.name: HTMLAreaElement
htmlareaelement.summary: The HTMLAreaElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond those of the regular object HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <area> elements.
htmlareaelement.title: HTMLAreaElement

dom-audio-dev.name: Audio
dom-audio-dev.summary: The Audio() constructor creates and returns a new HTMLAudioElement which can be either attached to a document for the user to interact with and/or listen to, or can be used offscreen to manage and play audio.
dom-audio-dev.title: HTMLAudioElement: Audio() constructor

htmlaudioelement.name: HTMLAudioElement
htmlaudioelement.summary: The HTMLAudioElement interface provides access to the properties of <audio> elements, as well as methods to manipulate them.
htmlaudioelement.title: HTMLAudioElement

htmlbrelement.name: HTMLBRElement
htmlbrelement.summary:
The HTMLBRElement interface represents an HTML line break element (
). It inherits from HTMLElement.
htmlbrelement.title: HTMLBRElement

htmlbaseelement.name: HTMLBaseElement
htmlbaseelement.summary: The HTMLBaseElement interface contains the base URI for a document. This object inherits all of the properties and methods as described in the HTMLElement interface.
htmlbaseelement.title: HTMLBaseElement

htmlbodyelement.name: HTMLBodyElement
htmlbodyelement.summary: The HTMLBodyElement interface provides special properties (beyond those inherited from the regular HTMLElement interface) for manipulating <body> elements.
htmlbodyelement.title: HTMLBodyElement

dom-fe-disabled.name: disabled
dom-fe-disabled.summary: The HTMLButtonElement.disabled property indicates whether the control is disabled, meaning that it does not accept any clicks.
dom-fe-disabled.title: HTMLButtonElement: disabled property

dom-fe-disabled.name: disabled
dom-fe-disabled.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.disabled property is a boolean value that reflects the disabled HTML attribute, which indicates whether the control is disabled. If it is disabled, it does not accept clicks. A disabled element is unusable and un-clickable.
dom-fe-disabled.title: HTMLSelectElement: disabled property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLButtonElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <button> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLButtonElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <input> element, if the element is not hidden. If the element has the type hidden, the property returns null.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLMeterElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <meter> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLMeterElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLOutputElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <output> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLOutputElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLProgressElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <progress> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLProgressElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <select> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: labels property

dom-lfe-labels-dev.name: labels
dom-lfe-labels-dev.summary: The HTMLTextAreaElement.labels read-only property returns a NodeList of the <label> elements associated with the <textarea> element.
dom-lfe-labels-dev.title: HTMLTextAreaElement: labels property

dom-popovertargetaction.name: popoverTargetAction
dom-popovertargetaction.summary: The popoverTargetAction property of the HTMLButtonElement interface gets and sets the action to be performed ("hide", "show", or "toggle") on a popover element being controlled by a button.
dom-popovertargetaction.title: HTMLButtonElement: popoverTargetAction property

dom-popovertargetaction.name: popoverTargetAction
dom-popovertargetaction.summary: The popoverTargetAction property of the HTMLInputElement interface gets and sets the action to be performed ("hide", "show", or "toggle") on a popover element being controlled by an <input> element of type="button".
dom-popovertargetaction.title: HTMLInputElement: popoverTargetAction property

dom-popovertargetelement.name: popoverTargetElement
dom-popovertargetelement.summary: The popoverTargetElement property of the HTMLButtonElement interface gets and sets the popover element to control via a button.
dom-popovertargetelement.title: HTMLButtonElement: popoverTargetElement property

dom-popovertargetelement.name: popoverTargetElement
dom-popovertargetelement.summary: The popoverTargetElement property of the HTMLInputElement interface gets and sets the popover element to control via an <input> element of type="button".
dom-popovertargetelement.title: HTMLInputElement: popoverTargetElement property

htmlbuttonelement.name: HTMLButtonElement
htmlbuttonelement.summary: The HTMLButtonElement interface provides properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <button> elements.
htmlbuttonelement.title: HTMLButtonElement

event-contextlost.name: contextlost_event
event-contextlost.summary: The webglcontextlost event of the WebGL API is fired if the user agent detects that the drawing buffer associated with a WebGLRenderingContext object has been lost.
event-contextlost.title: HTMLCanvasElement: webglcontextlost event

event-contextrestored.name: contextrestored_event
event-contextrestored.summary: The contextrestored event of the Canvas API is fired if the user agent restores the backing storage for a CanvasRenderingContext2D.
event-contextrestored.title: HTMLCanvasElement: contextrestored event

dom-canvas-getcontext-dev.name: getContext
dom-canvas-getcontext-dev.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.getContext() method returns a drawing context on the canvas, or null if the context identifier is not supported, or the canvas has already been set to a different context mode.
dom-canvas-getcontext-dev.title: HTMLCanvasElement: getContext() method

dom-canvas-height.name: height
dom-canvas-height.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.height property is a positive integer reflecting the height HTML attribute of the <canvas> element interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 150 is used.
dom-canvas-height.title: HTMLCanvasElement: height property

dom-canvas-height.name: width
dom-canvas-height.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.width property is a positive integer reflecting the width HTML attribute of the <canvas> element interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an invalid value, like a negative, the default value of 300 is used.
dom-canvas-height.title: HTMLCanvasElement: width property

dom-canvas-toblob-dev.name: toBlob
dom-canvas-toblob-dev.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.toBlob() method creates a Blob object representing the image contained in the canvas. This file may be cached on the disk or stored in memory at the discretion of the user agent.
dom-canvas-toblob-dev.title: HTMLCanvasElement: toBlob() method

dom-canvas-todataurl-dev.name: toDataURL
dom-canvas-todataurl-dev.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.toDataURL() method returns a data URL containing a representation of the image in the format specified by the type parameter.
dom-canvas-todataurl-dev.title: HTMLCanvasElement: toDataURL() method

dom-canvas-transfercontroltooffscreen-de.name: transferControlToOffscreen
dom-canvas-transfercontroltooffscreen-de.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement.transferControlToOffscreen() method transfers control to an OffscreenCanvas object, either on the main thread or on a worker.
dom-canvas-transfercontroltooffscreen-de.title: HTMLCanvasElement: transferControlToOffscreen() method

htmlcanvaselement.name: HTMLCanvasElement
htmlcanvaselement.summary: The HTMLCanvasElement interface provides properties and methods for manipulating the layout and presentation of <canvas> elements. The HTMLCanvasElement interface also inherits the properties and methods of the HTMLElement interface.
htmlcanvaselement.title: HTMLCanvasElement

htmldlistelement.name: HTMLDListElement
htmldlistelement.summary: The HTMLDListElement interface provides special properties (beyond those of the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating definition list (<dl>) elements.
htmldlistelement.title: HTMLDListElement

dom-data-value.name: value
dom-data-value.summary: The value property of the HTMLDataElement interface returns a string reflecting the value HTML attribute.
dom-data-value.title: HTMLDataElement: value property

htmldataelement.name: HTMLDataElement
htmldataelement.summary: The HTMLDataElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <data> elements.
htmldataelement.title: HTMLDataElement

htmldatalistelement.name: HTMLDataListElement
htmldatalistelement.summary: The HTMLDataListElement interface provides special properties (beyond the HTMLElement object interface it also has available to it by inheritance) to manipulate <datalist> elements and their content.
htmldatalistelement.title: HTMLDataListElement

dom-details-open.name: open
dom-details-open.summary: The open property of the HTMLDetailsElement interface is a boolean value reflecting the open HTML attribute, indicating whether the <details>'s contents (not counting the <summary>) is to be shown to the user.
dom-details-open.title: HTMLDetailsElement: open property

event-toggle.name: toggle_event
event-toggle.summary: The toggle event fires when the open/closed state of a <details> element is toggled.
event-toggle.title: HTMLDetailsElement: toggle event

event-toggle.name: toggle_event
event-toggle.summary: The toggle event of the HTMLElement interface fires on a popover element (i.e. one that has a valid popover attribute) just after it is shown or hidden.
event-toggle.title: HTMLElement: toggle event

htmldetailselement.name: HTMLDetailsElement
htmldetailselement.summary: The HTMLDetailsElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <details> elements.
htmldetailselement.title: HTMLDetailsElement

event-cancel.name: cancel_event
event-cancel.summary: The cancel event fires on a <dialog> when the user instructs the browser that they wish to dismiss the current open dialog. The browser fires this event when the user presses the Esc key.
event-cancel.title: HTMLDialogElement: cancel event

handler-oncancel.name: cancel_event
handler-oncancel.summary: The cancel event fires on a <dialog> when the user instructs the browser that they wish to dismiss the current open dialog. The browser fires this event when the user presses the Esc key.
handler-oncancel.title: HTMLDialogElement: cancel event

dom-dialog-close-dev.name: close
dom-dialog-close-dev.summary: The close() method of the HTMLDialogElement interface closes the <dialog>. An optional string may be passed as an argument, updating the returnValue of the dialog.
dom-dialog-close-dev.title: HTMLDialogElement: close() method

event-close.name: close_event
event-close.summary: The close event is fired on an HTMLDialogElement object when the <dialog> it represents has been closed.
event-close.title: HTMLDialogElement: close event

dom-dialog-open.name: open
dom-dialog-open.summary: The open property of the HTMLDialogElement interface is a boolean value reflecting the open HTML attribute, indicating whether the <dialog> is available for interaction.
dom-dialog-open.title: HTMLDialogElement: open property

dom-dialog-returnvalue-dev.name: returnValue
dom-dialog-returnvalue-dev.summary: The returnValue property of the HTMLDialogElement interface gets or sets the return value for the <dialog>, usually to indicate which button the user pressed to close it.
dom-dialog-returnvalue-dev.title: HTMLDialogElement: returnValue property

dom-dialog-show-dev.name: show
dom-dialog-show-dev.summary: The show() method of the HTMLDialogElement interface displays the dialog modelessly, i.e. still allowing interaction with content outside of the dialog.
dom-dialog-show-dev.title: HTMLDialogElement: show() method

dom-dialog-showmodal-dev.name: showModal
dom-dialog-showmodal-dev.summary: The showModal() method of the HTMLDialogElement interface displays the dialog as a modal, over the top of any other dialogs that might be present. It displays in the top layer, along with a ::backdrop pseudo-element. Interaction outside the dialog is blocked and the content outside it is rendered inert.
dom-dialog-showmodal-dev.title: HTMLDialogElement: showModal() method

htmldialogelement.name: HTMLDialogElement
htmldialogelement.summary: The HTMLDialogElement interface provides methods to manipulate <dialog> elements. It inherits properties and methods from the HTMLElement interface.
htmldialogelement.title: HTMLDialogElement

htmldivelement.name: HTMLDivElement
htmldivelement.summary: The HTMLDivElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <div> elements.
htmldivelement.title: HTMLDivElement

htmldocument.name: HTMLDocument
htmldocument.summary: For historical reasons, Window objects have a window.HTMLDocument property whose value is the Document interface. So you can think of HTMLDocument as an alias for Document, and you can find documentation for HTMLDocument members under the documentation for the Document interface.
htmldocument.title: HTMLDocument

dom-accesskey.name: accessKey
dom-accesskey.summary: The HTMLElement.accessKey property sets the keystroke which a user can press to jump to a given element.
dom-accesskey.title: HTMLElement: accessKey property

dom-accesskeylabel.name: accessKeyLabel
dom-accesskeylabel.summary: The HTMLElement.accessKeyLabel read-only property returns a string containing the element's browser-assigned access key (if any); otherwise it returns an empty string.

chrome.notes: See bug 393466.

edge_blink.notes: See bug 393466.

dom-accesskeylabel.title: HTMLElement: accessKeyLabel property

dom-attachinternals.name: attachInternals
dom-attachinternals.summary: The HTMLElement.attachInternals() method returns an ElementInternals object. This method allows a custom element to participate in HTML forms. The ElementInternals interface provides utilities for working with these elements in the same way you would work with any standard HTML form element, and also exposes the Accessibility Object Model to the element.

safari.notes: See bug 197960.

dom-attachinternals.title: HTMLElement: attachInternals() method

event-beforetoggle.name: beforetoggle_event
event-beforetoggle.summary: The beforetoggle event of the HTMLElement interface fires on a popover element (i.e. one that has a valid popover attribute) just before it is shown or hidden.
event-beforetoggle.title: HTMLElement: beforetoggle event

dom-blur-dev.name: blur
dom-blur-dev.summary: The HTMLElement.blur() method removes keyboard focus from the current element.
dom-blur-dev.title: HTMLElement: blur() method

event-change.name: change_event

handler-onchange.name: change_event
handler-onchange.summary: The change event is fired for <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements when the user modifies the element's value. Unlike the input event, the change event is not necessarily fired for each alteration to an element's value.
handler-onchange.title: HTMLElement: change event

dom-click-dev.name: click
dom-click-dev.summary: The HTMLElement.click() method simulates a mouse click on an element.

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 19, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs.

notes: Before Firefox 5, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs, and has no effect on text and file inputs.
Starting in Firefox 75, the click() function works even when the element is not attached to a DOM tree.
Before Firefox 5, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs, and has no effect on text and file inputs.
Starting in Firefox for Android 79, the click() function works even when the element is not attached to a DOM tree.

samsunginternet_android.notes: Before Samsung Internet 1.5, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs.

webview_android.notes: Before Android WebView 4.4, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs.

edge_blink.notes: Before Chrome 19, click() is only defined on buttons and inputs.

dom-click-dev.title: HTMLElement: click() method

contenteditable.name: contentEditable
contenteditable.summary: The contentEditable property of the HTMLElement interface specifies whether or not the element is editable.
contenteditable.title: HTMLElement: contentEditable property

dom-dataset-dev.name: dataset
dom-dataset-dev.summary: The dataset read-only property of the HTMLElement interface provides read/write access to custom data attributes (data-*) on elements. It exposes a map of strings (DOMStringMap) with an entry for each data-* attribute.
dom-dataset-dev.title: HTMLElement: dataset property

dom-dataset-dev.name: dataset
dom-dataset-dev.summary: The dataset read-only property of the HTMLElement interface provides read/write access to custom data attributes (data-*) on elements. It exposes a map of strings (DOMStringMap) with an entry for each data-* attribute.
dom-dataset-dev.title: HTMLElement: dataset property

dom-dir.name: dir
dom-dir.summary: The HTMLElement.dir property gets or sets the text writing directionality of the content of the current element.
dom-dir.title: HTMLElement: dir property

ix-handler-ondrag.name: drag_event
ix-handler-ondrag.summary: The drag event is fired every few hundred milliseconds as an element or text selection is being dragged by the user.
ix-handler-ondrag.title: HTMLElement: drag event

event-dnd-drag.name: drag_event
event-dnd-drag.summary: The drag event is fired every few hundred milliseconds as an element or text selection is being dragged by the user.
event-dnd-drag.title: HTMLElement: drag event

ix-handler-ondragend.name: dragend_event
ix-handler-ondragend.summary: The dragend event is fired when a drag operation is being ended (by releasing a mouse button or hitting the escape key).
ix-handler-ondragend.title: HTMLElement: dragend event

event-dnd-dragend.name: dragend_event
event-dnd-dragend.summary: The dragend event is fired when a drag operation is being ended (by releasing a mouse button or hitting the escape key).
event-dnd-dragend.title: HTMLElement: dragend event

ix-handler-ondragenter.name: dragenter_event
ix-handler-ondragenter.summary: The dragenter event is fired when a dragged element or text selection enters a valid drop target.
ix-handler-ondragenter.title: HTMLElement: dragenter event

event-dnd-dragenter.name: dragenter_event
event-dnd-dragenter.summary: The dragenter event is fired when a dragged element or text selection enters a valid drop target.
event-dnd-dragenter.title: HTMLElement: dragenter event

ix-handler-ondragleave.name: dragleave_event
ix-handler-ondragleave.summary: The dragleave event is fired when a dragged element or text selection leaves a valid drop target.
ix-handler-ondragleave.title: HTMLElement: dragleave event

event-dnd-dragleave.name: dragleave_event
event-dnd-dragleave.summary: The dragleave event is fired when a dragged element or text selection leaves a valid drop target.
event-dnd-dragleave.title: HTMLElement: dragleave event

ix-handler-ondragover.name: dragover_event
ix-handler-ondragover.summary: The dragover event is fired when an element or text selection is being dragged over a valid drop target (every few hundred milliseconds).
ix-handler-ondragover.title: HTMLElement: dragover event

event-dnd-dragover.name: dragover_event
event-dnd-dragover.summary: The dragover event is fired when an element or text selection is being dragged over a valid drop target (every few hundred milliseconds).
event-dnd-dragover.title: HTMLElement: dragover event

ix-handler-ondragstart.name: dragstart_event
ix-handler-ondragstart.summary: The dragstart event is fired when the user starts dragging an element or text selection.
ix-handler-ondragstart.title: HTMLElement: dragstart event

event-dnd-dragstart.name: dragstart_event
event-dnd-dragstart.summary: The dragstart event is fired when the user starts dragging an element or text selection.
event-dnd-dragstart.title: HTMLElement: dragstart event

ix-handler-ondrop.name: drop_event
ix-handler-ondrop.summary: The drop event is fired when an element or text selection is dropped on a valid drop target. To ensure that the drop event always fires as expected, you should always include a preventDefault() call in the part of your code which handles the dragover event.
ix-handler-ondrop.title: HTMLElement: drop event

event-dnd-drop.name: drop_event
event-dnd-drop.summary: The drop event is fired when an element or text selection is dropped on a valid drop target. To ensure that the drop event always fires as expected, you should always include a preventDefault() call in the part of your code which handles the dragover event.
event-dnd-drop.title: HTMLElement: drop event

dom-enterkeyhint.name: enterKeyHint
dom-enterkeyhint.summary: The enterKeyHint property is an enumerated property defining what action label (or icon) to present for the enter key on virtual keyboards. It reflects the enterkeyhint HTML global attribute and is an enumerated property, only accepting the following values as a string:
dom-enterkeyhint.title: HTMLElement: enterKeyHint property

dom-focus-dev.name: focus
dom-focus-dev.summary: The HTMLElement.focus() method sets focus on the specified element, if it can be focused. The focused element is the element that will receive keyboard and similar events by default.
dom-focus-dev.title: HTMLElement: focus() method

dom-hidden.name: hidden
dom-hidden.summary: The HTMLElement property hidden reflects the value of the element's hidden attribute.
dom-hidden.title: HTMLElement: hidden property

dom-hidepopover.name: hidePopover
dom-hidepopover.summary: The hidePopover() method of the HTMLElement interface hides a popover element (i.e. one that has a valid popover attribute) by removing it from the top layer and styling it with display: none.
dom-hidepopover.title: HTMLElement: hidePopover() method

dom-inert.name: inert
dom-inert.summary: The HTMLElement property inert reflects the value of the element's inert attribute. It is a boolean value that, when present, makes the browser "ignore" user input events for the element, including focus events and events from assistive technologies. The browser may also ignore page search and text selection in the element. This can be useful when building UIs such as modals where you would want to "trap" the focus inside the modal when it's visible.
dom-inert.title: HTMLElement: inert property

the-innertext-idl-attribute.name: innerText
the-innertext-idl-attribute.summary: The innerText property of the HTMLElement interface represents the rendered text content of a node and its descendants.
the-innertext-idl-attribute.title: HTMLElement: innerText property

handler-oninput.name: input_event
handler-oninput.summary: The input event fires when the value of an <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element has been changed.

ie.notes: Only supports input of type text and password.

handler-oninput.title: HTMLElement: input event

dom-inputmode.name: inputMode
dom-inputmode.summary: The HTMLElement property inputMode reflects the value of the element's inputmode attribute.
dom-inputmode.title: HTMLElement: inputMode property

dom-iscontenteditable-dev.name: isContentEditable
dom-iscontenteditable-dev.summary: The HTMLElement.isContentEditable read-only property returns a boolean value that is true if the contents of the element are editable; otherwise it returns false.
dom-iscontenteditable-dev.title: HTMLElement: isContentEditable property

dom-lang.name: lang
dom-lang.summary: The HTMLElement.lang property gets or sets the base language of an element's attribute values and text content.
dom-lang.title: HTMLElement: lang property

dom-noncedelement-nonce.name: nonce
dom-noncedelement-nonce.summary: The nonce property of the HTMLElement interface returns the cryptographic number used once that is used by Content Security Policy to determine whether a given fetch will be allowed to proceed.

safari.notes: The property is defined only for its useful elements: <link>, <script>, and <style>; it is undefined for all other elements.

dom-noncedelement-nonce.title: HTMLElement: nonce property

dom-outertext.name: outerText
dom-outertext.summary: The outerText property of the HTMLElement interface returns the same value as HTMLElement.innerText. When used as a setter it replaces the whole current node with the given text (this differs from innerText, which replaces the content inside the current node).
dom-outertext.title: HTMLElement: outerText property

dom-popover.name: popover
dom-popover.summary: The popover property of the HTMLElement interface gets and sets an element's popover state via JavaScript ("auto" or "manual"), and can be used for feature detection.
dom-popover.title: HTMLElement: popover property

dom-showpopover.name: showPopover
dom-showpopover.summary: The showPopover() method of the HTMLElement interface shows a popover element (i.e. one that has a valid popover attribute) by adding it to the top layer.
dom-showpopover.title: HTMLElement: showPopover() method

dom-tabindex.name: tabIndex
dom-tabindex.summary: The tabIndex property of the HTMLElement interface represents the tab order of the current element.

dom-tabindex.title: HTMLElement: tabIndex property

dom-title.name: title
dom-title.summary: The HTMLElement.title property represents the title of the element: the text usually displayed in a 'tooltip' popup when the mouse is over the node.
dom-title.title: HTMLElement: title property

dom-togglepopover.name: togglePopover
dom-togglepopover.summary: The togglePopover() method of the HTMLElement interface toggles a popover element (i.e. one that has a valid popover attribute) between the hidden and showing states.
dom-togglepopover.title: HTMLElement: togglePopover() method

htmlelement.name: HTMLElement
htmlelement.summary: The HTMLElement interface represents any HTML element. Some elements directly implement this interface, while others implement it via an interface that inherits it.
htmlelement.title: HTMLElement

htmlembedelement.name: HTMLEmbedElement
htmlembedelement.summary: The HTMLEmbedElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <embed> elements.

chrome.notes: Starting with Chrome 58, this interface can no longer be called as a function.

opera.notes: Starting with Opera 45, this interface can no longer be called as a function.

opera_android.notes: Starting with Opera 45, this interface can no longer be called as a function.

edge_blink.notes: Starting with Chrome 58, this interface can no longer be called as a function.

htmlembedelement.title: HTMLEmbedElement

htmlfieldsetelement.name: HTMLFieldSetElement
htmlfieldsetelement.summary: The HTMLFieldSetElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <fieldset> elements.
htmlfieldsetelement.title: HTMLFieldSetElement

dom-htmlformcontrolscollection-nameditem.name: namedItem
dom-htmlformcontrolscollection-nameditem.summary: The HTMLFormControlsCollection.namedItem() method returns the RadioNodeList or the Element in the collection whose name or id match the specified name, or null if no node matches.

htmlformcontrolscollection.name: HTMLFormControlsCollection

htmlformcontrolscollection.title: HTMLFormControlsCollection

dom-form-acceptcharset.name: acceptCharset
dom-form-acceptcharset.summary: The HTMLFormElement.acceptCharset property represents a list of the supported character encodings for the given <form> element. This list can be comma-separated or space-separated.
dom-form-acceptcharset.title: HTMLFormElement: acceptCharset property

dom-fs-action.name: action

dom-fs-encoding.name: encoding
dom-fs-encoding.summary: The HTMLFormElement.encoding property is an alternative name for the enctype element on the DOM HTMLFormElement object.
dom-fs-encoding.title: HTMLFormElement: encoding property

dom-fs-enctype.name: enctype
dom-fs-enctype.summary: The HTMLFormElement.enctype property is the MIME type of content that is used to submit the form to the server. Possible values are:
dom-fs-enctype.title: HTMLFormElement: enctype property

event-formdata.name: formdata_event
event-formdata.summary: The formdata event fires after the entry list representing the form's data is constructed. This happens when the form is submitted, but can also be triggered by the invocation of a FormData() constructor.
event-formdata.title: HTMLFormElement: formdata event

dom-form-length-dev.name: length
dom-form-length-dev.summary: The HTMLFormElement.length read-only property returns the number of controls in the <form> element.
dom-form-length-dev.title: HTMLFormElement: length property

dom-fs-method.name: method
dom-fs-method.summary: The HTMLFormElement.method property represents the HTTP method used to submit the <form>.
dom-fs-method.title: HTMLFormElement: method property

dom-form-name.name: name
dom-form-name.summary: The HTMLFormElement.name property represents the name of the current <form> element as a string.
dom-form-name.title: HTMLFormElement: name property

dom-cva-reportvalidity-dev.name: reportValidity
dom-cva-reportvalidity-dev.summary: The HTMLFormElement.reportValidity() method returns true if the element's child controls satisfy their validation constraints. When false is returned, cancelable invalid events are fired for each invalid child and validation problems are reported to the user.

If the value is invalid, this method also fires the invalid event on the element, and (if the event isn't canceled) reports the problem to the user.

dom-form-requestsubmit-dev.name: requestSubmit
dom-form-requestsubmit-dev.summary: The HTMLFormElement method requestSubmit() requests that the form be submitted using a specific submit button.

dom-form-reset-dev.name: reset
dom-form-reset-dev.summary: The HTMLFormElement.reset() method restores a form element's default values. This method does the same thing as clicking the form's <input type="reset"> control.

event-reset.name: reset_event

dom-form-submit-dev.name: submit
dom-form-submit-dev.summary: The HTMLFormElement.submit() method submits a given <form>.

event-submit.name: submit_event
event-submit.summary: The submit event fires when a <form> is submitted.

handler-onsubmit.name: submit_event
handler-onsubmit.summary: The submit event fires when a <form> is submitted.
handler-onsubmit.title: HTMLFormElement: submit event

dom-fs-target.name: target
dom-fs-target.summary: The target property of the HTMLFormElement interface represents the target of the form's action (i.e., the frame in which to render its output).

htmlformelement.name: HTMLFormElement
htmlformelement.summary: The HTMLFormElement interface represents a <form> element in the DOM. It allows access toand, in some cases, modification ofaspects of the form, as well as access to its component elements.
htmlformelement.title: HTMLFormElement

htmlhrelement.name: HTMLHRElement
htmlhrelement.summary: The HTMLHRElement interface provides special properties (beyond those of the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <hr> elements.
htmlhrelement.title: HTMLHRElement

htmlheadelement.name: HTMLHeadElement
htmlheadelement.summary: The HTMLHeadElement interface contains the descriptive information, or metadata, for a document. This object inherits all of the properties and methods described in the HTMLElement interface.
htmlheadelement.title: HTMLHeadElement

htmlheadingelement.name: HTMLHeadingElement
htmlheadingelement.summary: The HTMLHeadingElement interface represents the different heading elements, <h1> through <h6>. It inherits methods and properties from the HTMLElement interface.
htmlheadingelement.title: HTMLHeadingElement

htmlhtmlelement.name: HTMLHtmlElement
htmlhtmlelement.summary: The HTMLHtmlElement interface serves as the root node for a given HTML document. This object inherits the properties and methods described in the HTMLElement interface.

dom-iframe-contentdocument.name: contentDocument
dom-iframe-contentdocument.summary: If the iframe and the iframe's parent document are Same Origin, returns a Document (that is, the active document in the inline frame's nested browsing context), else returns null.

dom-iframe-contentwindow.summary: The contentWindow property returns the Window object of an HTMLIFrameElement. You can use this Window object to access the iframe's document and its internal DOM. This attribute is read-only, but its properties can be manipulated like the global Window object.

dom-iframe-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-iframe-referrerpolicy.summary: The HTMLIFrameElement.referrerPolicy property reflects the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the <iframe> element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.
dom-iframe-referrerpolicy.title: HTMLIFrameElement: referrerPolicy property

dom-iframe-src.name: src
dom-iframe-src.summary: The HTMLIFrameElement.src property reflects the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the <iframe> element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.

dom-iframe-srcdoc.name: srcdoc
dom-iframe-srcdoc.summary: The srcdoc property of the HTMLIFrameElement specifies the content of the page.

htmliframeelement.name: HTMLIFrameElement
htmliframeelement.summary: The HTMLIFrameElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond those of the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of inline frame elements.

dom-image-dev.name: Image
dom-image-dev.summary: The Image() constructor creates a new HTMLImageElement instance. It is functionally equivalent to document.createElement('img').

dom-img-alt.name: alt

dom-img-alt.title: HTMLImageElement: alt property

dom-img-complete-dev.name: complete
dom-img-complete-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLImageElement interface's complete attribute is a Boolean value which indicates whether or not the image has completely loaded.

dom-img-complete-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: complete property

dom-img-crossorigin.name: crossOrigin
dom-img-crossorigin.summary: The HTMLImageElement interface's crossOrigin attribute is a string which specifies the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) setting to use when retrieving the image.
dom-img-crossorigin.title: HTMLImageElement: crossOrigin property

dom-img-currentsrc-dev.name: currentSrc
dom-img-currentsrc-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLImageElement property currentSrc indicates the URL of the image which is currently presented in the element it represents.

dom-img-decode-dev.name: decode
dom-img-decode-dev.summary: The decode() method of the HTMLImageElement interface returns a Promise that resolves when the image is decoded and it is safe to append the image to the DOM.
dom-img-decode-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: decode() method

dom-img-decode-dev.name: decode
dom-img-decode-dev.summary: The decode() method of the SVGImageElement interface initiates asynchronous decoding of an image, returning a Promise that resolves once the image data is ready for use.
dom-img-decode-dev.title: SVGImageElement: decode() method

dom-img-decoding.name: decoding
dom-img-decoding.summary: The decoding property of the HTMLImageElement interface represents a hint given to the browser on how it should decode the image.
dom-img-decoding.title: HTMLImageElement: decoding property

dom-img-decoding.name: decoding
dom-img-decoding.summary: The decoding property of the SVGImageElement interface represents a hint given to the browser on how it should decode the image.
dom-img-decoding.title: SVGImageElement: decoding property

attr-img-fetchpriority.name: fetchPriority
attr-img-fetchpriority.summary: The fetchPriority property of the HTMLImageElement interface represents a hint given to the browser on how it should prioritize the fetch of the image relative to other images.
attr-img-fetchpriority.title: HTMLImageElement: fetchPriority property

dom-img-height-dev.name: height
dom-img-height-dev.summary: The height property of the HTMLImageElement interface indicates the height at which the image is drawn, in CSS pixels if the image is being drawn or rendered to any visual medium such as the screen or a printer; otherwise, it's the natural, pixel density corrected height of the image.
dom-img-height-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: height property

dom-img-ismap.name: isMap
dom-img-ismap.summary: The HTMLImageElement property isMap is a Boolean value which indicates that the image is to be used by a server-side image map. This may only be used on images located within an <a> element.
dom-img-ismap.title: HTMLImageElement: isMap property

dom-img-loading.name: loading
dom-img-loading.summary: The HTMLImageElement property loading is a string whose value provides a hint to the user agent on how to handle the loading of the image which is currently outside the window's visual viewport.
dom-img-loading.title: HTMLImageElement: loading property

dom-img-naturalheight-dev.name: naturalHeight
dom-img-naturalheight-dev.summary: The HTMLImageElement interface's naturalHeight property is a read-only value which returns the intrinsic (natural), density-corrected height of the image in CSS pixels.
dom-img-naturalheight-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: naturalHeight property

dom-img-naturalwidth-dev.name: naturalWidth
dom-img-naturalwidth-dev.summary: The HTMLImageElement interface's read-only naturalWidth property returns the intrinsic (natural), density-corrected width of the image in CSS pixels.
dom-img-naturalwidth-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: naturalWidth property

dom-img-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-img-referrerpolicy.summary: The HTMLImageElement.referrerPolicy property reflects the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.

dom-img-sizes.name: sizes
dom-img-sizes.summary: The HTMLImageElement property sizes allows you to specify the layout width of the image for each of a list of media conditions. This provides the ability to automatically select among different imageseven images of different orientations or aspect ratiosas the document state changes to match different media conditions.
dom-img-sizes.title: HTMLImageElement: sizes property

attr-img-src.name: src
attr-img-src.summary: The HTMLImageElement property src, which reflects the HTML src attribute, specifies the image to display in the element.
attr-img-src.title: HTMLImageElement: src property

dom-img-srcset.name: srcset
dom-img-srcset.summary: The HTMLImageElement property srcset is a string which identifies one or more image candidate strings, separated using commas (,) each specifying image resources to use under given circumstances.
dom-img-srcset.title: HTMLImageElement: srcset property

dom-img-usemap.name: useMap
dom-img-usemap.summary: The useMap property on the HTMLImageElement interface reflects the value of the HTML usemap attribute, which is a string providing the name of the client-side image map to apply to the image.
dom-img-usemap.title: HTMLImageElement: useMap property

dom-img-width-dev.name: width
dom-img-width-dev.summary: The width property of the HTMLImageElement interface indicates the width at which an image is drawn in CSS pixels if it's being drawn or rendered to any visual medium such as a screen or printer. Otherwise, it's the natural, pixel density-corrected width of the image.
dom-img-width-dev.title: HTMLImageElement: width property

htmlimageelement.name: HTMLImageElement
htmlimageelement.summary: The HTMLImageElement interface represents an HTML element, providing the properties and methods used to manipulate image elements.
htmlimageelement.title: HTMLImageElement

dom-cva-checkvalidity-dev.name: checkValidity

dom-textarea/input-select.summary: The HTMLInputElement.select() method selects all the text in a <textarea> element or in an <input> element that includes a text field.

dom-textarea/input-select.name: select

event-select.name: select_event

event-select.name: select_event
event-select.summary: The select event fires when some text has been selected.
event-select.title: HTMLTextAreaElement: select event

handler-onselect.name: select_event

handler-onselect.title: HTMLTextAreaElement: select event

dom-cva-setcustomvalidity.name: setCustomValidity
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity.summary: The HTMLInputElement.setCustomValidity() method sets a custom validity message for the element.
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity.title: HTMLInputElement: setCustomValidity() method

dom-textarea/input-setrangetext-dev.name: setRangeText
dom-textarea/input-setrangetext-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.setRangeText() method replaces a range of text in an <input> or <textarea> element with a new string.
dom-textarea/input-setrangetext-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: setRangeText() method

dom-textarea/input-setselectionrange-dev.name: setSelectionRange
dom-textarea/input-setselectionrange-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.setSelectionRange() method sets the start and end positions of the current text selection in an <input> or <textarea> element.
dom-textarea/input-setselectionrange-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: setSelectionRange() method

dom-input-showpicker.name: showPicker
dom-input-showpicker.summary: The HTMLInputElement.showPicker() method displays the browser picker for an input element.
dom-input-showpicker.title: HTMLInputElement: showPicker() method

dom-input-stepdown-dev.name: stepDown
dom-input-stepdown-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.stepDown([n]) method decrements the value of a numeric type of <input> element by the value of the step attribute or up to n multiples of the step attribute if a number is passed as the parameter.

firefox.notes: Does not have a specific UI. There are still differences with the latest spec; see bug 835773.

dom-input-stepdown-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: stepDown() method

dom-input-stepup-dev.name: stepUp
dom-input-stepup-dev.summary: The HTMLInputElement.stepUp() method increments the value of a numeric type of <input> element by the value of the step attribute, or the default step value if the step attribute is not explicitly set. The method, when invoked, increments the value by (step * n), where n defaults to 1 if not specified, and step defaults to the default value for step if not specified.

firefox.notes: Does not have a specific UI. There are still differences with the latest spec; see bug 835773.

dom-input-stepup-dev.title: HTMLInputElement: stepUp() method

htmlinputelement.name: HTMLInputElement
htmlinputelement.summary: The HTMLInputElement interface provides special properties and methods for manipulating the options, layout, and presentation of <input> elements.
htmlinputelement.title: HTMLInputElement

htmllielement.name: HTMLLIElement
htmllielement.summary: The HTMLLIElement interface exposes specific properties and methods (beyond those defined by regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating list elements.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 10, Gecko incorrectly reflected negative value attributes to 0.

htmllielement.title: HTMLLIElement

dom-label-control-dev.name: control
dom-label-control-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLLabelElement.control property returns a reference to the control (in the form of an object of type HTMLElement or one of its derivatives) with which the <label> element is associated, or null if the label isn't associated with a control.
dom-label-control-dev.title: HTMLLabelElement: control property

dom-label-form-dev.name: form
dom-label-form-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLLabelElement.form property returns an HTMLFormElement object which represents the form of which the label's associated control is a part, or null if there is either no associated control, or if that control isn't in a form.
dom-label-form-dev.title: HTMLLabelElement: form property

dom-label-htmlfor.name: htmlFor
dom-label-htmlfor.summary: The HTMLLabelElement.htmlFor property reflects the value of the for content property. That means that this script-accessible property is used to set and read the value of the content property for, which is the ID of the label's associated control element.
dom-label-htmlfor.title: HTMLLabelElement: htmlFor property

htmllabelelement.name: HTMLLabelElement
htmllabelelement.summary: The HTMLLabelElement interface gives access to properties specific to <label> elements. It inherits methods and properties from the base HTMLElement interface.
htmllabelelement.title: HTMLLabelElement

htmllegendelement.name: HTMLLegendElement
htmllegendelement.summary: The HTMLLegendElement is an interface allowing to access properties of the <legend> elements. It inherits properties and methods from the HTMLElement interface.
htmllegendelement.title: HTMLLegendElement

dom-link-as.name: as
dom-link-as.summary: The as property of the HTMLLinkElement interface returns a string representing the type of content to be preloaded by a link element.
dom-link-as.title: HTMLLinkElement: as property

attr-link-fetchpriority.name: fetchPriority
attr-link-fetchpriority.summary: The fetchPriority property of the HTMLLinkElement interface represents a hint given to the browser on how it should prioritize the preload of the given resource relative to other resources of the same type.
attr-link-fetchpriority.title: HTMLLinkElement: fetchPriority property

dom-link-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-link-referrerpolicy.summary: The HTMLLinkElement.referrerPolicy property reflects the HTML referrerpolicy attribute of the <link> element defining which referrer is sent when fetching the resource.
dom-link-referrerpolicy.title: HTMLLinkElement: referrerPolicy property

dom-link-rel.name: rel
dom-link-rel.summary: The HTMLLinkElement.rel property reflects the rel attribute. It is a string containing a space-separated list of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <link> element and the current document.
dom-link-rel.title: HTMLLinkElement: rel property

dom-link-rellist.name: relList
dom-link-rellist.summary: The HTMLLinkElement.relList read-only property reflects the rel attribute. It is a live DOMTokenList containing the set of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the <link> element and the current document.
dom-link-rellist.title: HTMLLinkElement: relList property

htmllinkelement.name: HTMLLinkElement
htmllinkelement.summary: The HTMLLinkElement interface represents reference information for external resources and the relationship of those resources to a document and vice versa (corresponds to <link> element; not to be confused with <a>, which is represented by HTMLAnchorElement). This object inherits all of the properties and methods of the HTMLElement interface.
htmllinkelement.title: HTMLLinkElement

htmlmapelement.name: HTMLMapElement
htmlmapelement.summary: The HTMLMapElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond those of the regular object HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of map elements.
htmlmapelement.title: HTMLMapElement

event-media-abort.name: abort_event
event-media-abort.summary: The abort event is fired when the resource was not fully loaded, but not as the result of an error.
event-media-abort.title: HTMLMediaElement: abort event

handler-onabort.name: abort_event
handler-onabort.summary: The abort event is fired when the resource was not fully loaded, but not as the result of an error.
handler-onabort.title: HTMLMediaElement: abort event

dom-media-audiotracks-dev.name: audioTracks
dom-media-audiotracks-dev.summary: The read-only audioTracks property on HTMLMediaElement objects returns an AudioTrackList object listing all of the AudioTrack objects representing the media element's audio tracks.
dom-media-audiotracks-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: audioTracks property

dom-media-autoplay.name: autoplay
dom-media-autoplay.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.autoplay property reflects the autoplay HTML attribute, indicating whether playback should automatically begin as soon as enough media is available to do so without interruption.
dom-media-autoplay.title: HTMLMediaElement: autoplay property

dom-media-buffered-dev.name: buffered
