dom-media-buffered-dev.summary: The buffered read-only property of HTMLMediaElement objects returns a new static normalized TimeRanges object that represents the ranges of the media resource, if any, that the user agent has buffered at the moment the buffered property is accessed.
dom-media-buffered-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: buffered property

event-media-canplay.name: canplay_event
event-media-canplay.summary: The canplay event is fired when the user agent can play the media, but estimates that not enough data has been loaded to play the media up to its end without having to stop for further buffering of content.
event-media-canplay.title: HTMLMediaElement: canplay event

handler-oncanplay.name: canplay_event
handler-oncanplay.summary: The canplay event is fired when the user agent can play the media, but estimates that not enough data has been loaded to play the media up to its end without having to stop for further buffering of content.
handler-oncanplay.title: HTMLMediaElement: canplay event

event-media-canplaythrough.name: canplaythrough_event
event-media-canplaythrough.summary: The canplaythrough event is fired when the user agent can play the media, and estimates that enough data has been loaded to play the media up to its end without having to stop for further buffering of content.
event-media-canplaythrough.title: HTMLMediaElement: canplaythrough event

handler-oncanplaythrough.name: canplaythrough_event
handler-oncanplaythrough.summary: The canplaythrough event is fired when the user agent can play the media, and estimates that enough data has been loaded to play the media up to its end without having to stop for further buffering of content.
handler-oncanplaythrough.title: HTMLMediaElement: canplaythrough event

dom-navigator-canplaytype-dev.name: canPlayType
dom-navigator-canplaytype-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement method canPlayType() reports how likely it is that the current browser will be able to play media of a given MIME type.

notes: codecs string can contain any subset of optional parameters (should be all or none).
Errors if codecs string contains unexpected characters (should evaluate string up to character).

Before Firefox 28, canPlayType() returned probably when asked about WebM audio or video files without the codecs parameter. Since multiple codecs are supported, this is not enough information to determine if a file can be played, so maybe is now correctly returned.
Before Firefox 101, canPlayType() ignored codecs parameter options for av01 codecs (treating them as av1).
codecs string can contain any subset of optional parameters (should be all or none).
Errors if codecs string contains unexpected characters (should evaluate string up to character).
codecs string can contain any subset of optional parameters (should be all or none).
Errors if codecs string contains unexpected characters (should evaluate string up to character).
codecs string can contain any subset of optional parameters (should be all or none).
Errors if codecs string contains unexpected characters (should evaluate string up to character).
codecs string can contain any subset of optional parameters (should be all or none).
Errors if codecs string contains unexpected characters (should evaluate string up to character).

dom-navigator-canplaytype-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: canPlayType() method

dom-media-controls.name: controls
dom-media-controls.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.controls property reflects the controls HTML attribute, which controls whether user interface controls for playing the media item will be displayed.
dom-media-controls.title: HTMLMediaElement: controls property

dom-media-crossorigin.name: crossOrigin
dom-media-crossorigin.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.crossOrigin property is the CORS setting for this media element. See CORS settings attributes for details.
dom-media-crossorigin.title: HTMLMediaElement: crossOrigin property

dom-media-currentsrc-dev.name: currentSrc
dom-media-currentsrc-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.currentSrc property contains the absolute URL of the chosen media resource. This could happen, for example, if the web server selects a media file based on the resolution of the user's display. The value is an empty string if the networkState property is EMPTY.
dom-media-currentsrc-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: currentSrc property

dom-media-currenttime-dev.name: currentTime
dom-media-currenttime-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement interface's currentTime property specifies the current playback time in seconds.
dom-media-currenttime-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: currentTime property

dom-media-defaultmuted.name: defaultMuted
dom-media-defaultmuted.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.defaultMuted property reflects the muted HTML attribute, which indicates whether the media element's audio output should be muted by default. This property has no dynamic effect. To mute and unmute the audio output, use the muted property.
dom-media-defaultmuted.title: HTMLMediaElement: defaultMuted property

dom-media-defaultplaybackrate-dev.name: defaultPlaybackRate
dom-media-defaultplaybackrate-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.defaultPlaybackRate property indicates the default playback rate for the media.
dom-media-defaultplaybackrate-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: defaultPlaybackRate property

dom-media-duration-dev.name: duration
dom-media-duration-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLMediaElement property duration indicates the length of the element's media in seconds.
dom-media-duration-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: duration property

event-media-durationchange.name: durationchange_event
event-media-durationchange.summary: The durationchange event is fired when the duration attribute has been updated.
event-media-durationchange.title: HTMLMediaElement: durationchange event

handler-ondurationchange.name: durationchange_event
handler-ondurationchange.summary: The durationchange event is fired when the duration attribute has been updated.
handler-ondurationchange.title: HTMLMediaElement: durationchange event

event-media-emptied.name: emptied_event
event-media-emptied.summary: The emptied event is fired when the media has become empty; for example, this event is sent if the media has already been loaded (or partially loaded), and the load() method is called to reload it.
event-media-emptied.title: HTMLMediaElement: emptied event

handler-onemptied.name: emptied_event
handler-onemptied.summary: The emptied event is fired when the media has become empty; for example, this event is sent if the media has already been loaded (or partially loaded), and the load() method is called to reload it.
handler-onemptied.title: HTMLMediaElement: emptied event

dom-media-ended-dev.name: ended
dom-media-ended-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.ended property indicates whether the media element has ended playback.
dom-media-ended-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: ended property

event-media-ended.name: ended_event
event-media-ended.summary: The ended event is fired when playback or streaming has stopped because the end of the media was reached or because no further data is available.
event-media-ended.title: HTMLMediaElement: ended event

handler-onended.name: ended_event
handler-onended.summary: The ended event is fired when playback or streaming has stopped because the end of the media was reached or because no further data is available.
handler-onended.title: HTMLMediaElement: ended event

dom-media-error-dev.name: error
dom-media-error-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.error property is the MediaError object for the most recent error, or null if there has not been an error. When an error event is received by the element, you can determine details about what happened by examining this object.
dom-media-error-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: error property

event-media-error.name: error_event
event-media-error.summary: The error event is fired when the resource could not be loaded due to an error (for example, a network connectivity problem).
event-media-error.title: HTMLMediaElement: error event

handler-window-onmessageerror.name: error_event
handler-window-onmessageerror.summary: The error event is fired when the resource could not be loaded due to an error (for example, a network connectivity problem).
handler-window-onmessageerror.title: HTMLMediaElement: error event

handler-window-onmessageerror.name: messageerror_event
handler-window-onmessageerror.summary: The messageerror event is fired on a Window object when it receives a message that can't be deserialized.

safari.notes: See bug 171216.

handler-window-onmessageerror.title: Window: messageerror event

dom-media-fastseek-dev.name: fastSeek
dom-media-fastseek-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.fastSeek() method quickly seeks the media to the new time with precision tradeoff.

chrome.notes: See bug 648207.

edge_blink.notes: See bug 648207.

dom-media-fastseek-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: fastSeek() method

dom-media-load-dev.name: load
dom-media-load-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement method load() resets the media element to its initial state and begins the process of selecting a media source and loading the media in preparation for playback to begin at the beginning.
dom-media-load-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: load() method

event-media-loadeddata.name: loadeddata_event
event-media-loadeddata.summary: The loadeddata event is fired when the frame at the current playback position of the media has finished loading; often the first frame.
event-media-loadeddata.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadeddata event

handler-onloadeddata.name: loadeddata_event
handler-onloadeddata.summary: The loadeddata event is fired when the frame at the current playback position of the media has finished loading; often the first frame.
handler-onloadeddata.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadeddata event

event-media-loadedmetadata.name: loadedmetadata_event
event-media-loadedmetadata.summary: The loadedmetadata event is fired when the metadata has been loaded.
event-media-loadedmetadata.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadedmetadata event

handler-onloadedmetadata.name: loadedmetadata_event
handler-onloadedmetadata.summary: The loadedmetadata event is fired when the metadata has been loaded.
handler-onloadedmetadata.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadedmetadata event

event-media-loadstart.name: loadstart_event
event-media-loadstart.summary: The loadstart event is fired when the browser has started to load a resource.
event-media-loadstart.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadstart event

handler-onloadstart.name: loadstart_event
handler-onloadstart.summary: The loadstart event is fired when the browser has started to load a resource.
handler-onloadstart.title: HTMLMediaElement: loadstart event

dom-media-loop.name: loop
dom-media-loop.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.loop property reflects the loop HTML attribute, which controls whether the media element should start over when it reaches the end.
dom-media-loop.title: HTMLMediaElement: loop property

dom-media-muted-dev.name: muted
dom-media-muted-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.muted property indicates whether the media element is muted.
dom-media-muted-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: muted property

dom-media-networkstate-dev.name: networkState
dom-media-networkstate-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.networkState property indicates the current state of the fetching of media over the network.

firefox.notes: The NETWORK_LOADED state was removed to align with the HTML spec in Firefox 4.

dom-media-networkstate-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: networkState property

dom-media-pause-dev.name: pause
dom-media-pause-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.pause() method will pause playback of the media, if the media is already in a paused state this method will have no effect.
dom-media-pause-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: pause() method

event-media-pause.name: pause_event
event-media-pause.summary: The pause event is sent when a request to pause an activity is handled and the activity has entered its paused state, most commonly after the media has been paused through a call to the element's pause() method.
event-media-pause.title: HTMLMediaElement: pause event

handler-onpause.name: pause_event
handler-onpause.summary: The pause event is sent when a request to pause an activity is handled and the activity has entered its paused state, most commonly after the media has been paused through a call to the element's pause() method.
handler-onpause.title: HTMLMediaElement: pause event

dom-media-paused-dev.name: paused
dom-media-paused-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLMediaElement.paused property tells whether the media element is paused.
dom-media-paused-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: paused property

dom-media-play-dev.name: play
dom-media-play-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement play() method attempts to begin playback of the media. It returns a Promise which is resolved when playback has been successfully started.
dom-media-play-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: play() method

event-media-play.name: play_event
event-media-play.summary: The play event is fired when the paused property is changed from true to false, as a result of the play method, or the autoplay attribute.
event-media-play.title: HTMLMediaElement: play event

handler-onplay.name: play_event
handler-onplay.summary: The play event is fired when the paused property is changed from true to false, as a result of the play method, or the autoplay attribute.
handler-onplay.title: HTMLMediaElement: play event

dom-media-playbackrate-dev.name: playbackRate
dom-media-playbackrate-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.playbackRate property sets the rate at which the media is being played back. This is used to implement user controls for fast forward, slow motion, and so forth. The normal playback rate is multiplied by this value to obtain the current rate, so a value of 1.0 indicates normal speed.
dom-media-playbackrate-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: playbackRate property

event-media-playing.name: playing_event
event-media-playing.summary: The playing event is fired after playback is first started, and whenever it is restarted. For example it is fired when playback resumes after having been paused or delayed due to lack of data.
event-media-playing.title: HTMLMediaElement: playing event

handler-onplaying.name: playing_event
handler-onplaying.summary: The playing event is fired after playback is first started, and whenever it is restarted. For example it is fired when playback resumes after having been paused or delayed due to lack of data.
handler-onplaying.title: HTMLMediaElement: playing event

dom-media-preservespitch-dev.name: preservesPitch
dom-media-preservespitch-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.preservesPitch property determines whether or not the browser should adjust the pitch of the audio to compensate for changes to the playback rate made by setting HTMLMediaElement.playbackRate.

firefox.notes: Disable by default in version 115 (behind preference dom.media.mozPreservesPitch.enabled). May be fully removed in a future release (see bug 1765201).

safari.notes: See bug 214922.

dom-media-preservespitch-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: preservesPitch property

event-media-progress.name: progress_event
event-media-progress.summary: The progress event is fired periodically as the browser loads a resource.
event-media-progress.title: HTMLMediaElement: progress event

handler-onprogress.name: progress_event
handler-onprogress.summary: The progress event is fired periodically as the browser loads a resource.
handler-onprogress.title: HTMLMediaElement: progress event

event-media-ratechange.name: ratechange_event
event-media-ratechange.summary: The ratechange event is fired when the playback rate has changed.
event-media-ratechange.title: HTMLMediaElement: ratechange event

handler-onratechange.name: ratechange_event
handler-onratechange.summary: The ratechange event is fired when the playback rate has changed.
handler-onratechange.title: HTMLMediaElement: ratechange event

dom-media-readystate-dev.name: readyState
dom-media-readystate-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.readyState property indicates the readiness state of the media.
dom-media-readystate-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: readyState property

dom-media-seekable-dev.name: seekable
dom-media-seekable-dev.summary: The seekable read-only property of HTMLMediaElement objects returns a new static normalized TimeRanges object that represents the ranges of the media resource, if any, that the user agent is able to seek to at the time seekable property is accessed.
dom-media-seekable-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: seekable property

event-media-seeked.name: seeked_event
event-media-seeked.summary: The seeked event is fired when a seek operation completed, the current playback position has changed, and the Boolean seeking attribute is changed to false.
event-media-seeked.title: HTMLMediaElement: seeked event

handler-onseeked.name: seeked_event
handler-onseeked.summary: The seeked event is fired when a seek operation completed, the current playback position has changed, and the Boolean seeking attribute is changed to false.
handler-onseeked.title: HTMLMediaElement: seeked event

event-media-seeking.name: seeking_event
event-media-seeking.summary: The seeking event is fired when a seek operation starts, meaning the Boolean seeking attribute has changed to true and the media is seeking a new position.
event-media-seeking.title: HTMLMediaElement: seeking event

handler-onseeking.name: seeking_event
handler-onseeking.summary: The seeking event is fired when a seek operation starts, meaning the Boolean seeking attribute has changed to true and the media is seeking a new position.
handler-onseeking.title: HTMLMediaElement: seeking event

dom-media-src.name: src
dom-media-src.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.src property reflects the value of the HTML media element's src attribute, which indicates the URL of a media resource to use in the element.
dom-media-src.title: HTMLMediaElement: src property

dom-media-srcobject-dev.name: srcObject
dom-media-srcobject-dev.summary: The srcObject property of the HTMLMediaElement interface sets or returns the object which serves as the source of the media associated with the HTMLMediaElement.

chrome.notes: Support added for MediaSourceHandle objects transferred from dedicated workers where they were obtained from MediaSource.handle (see bug 878133).
Support added for MediaStream objects (see bug 506273).

firefox.notes: Only supports MediaStream objects (see bug 886194).

edge_blink.notes: Support added for MediaSourceHandle objects transferred from dedicated workers where they were obtained from MediaSource.handle (see bug 878133).
Support added for MediaStream objects (see bug 506273).

dom-media-srcobject-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: srcObject property

event-media-stalled.name: stalled_event
event-media-stalled.summary: The stalled event is fired when the user agent is trying to fetch media data, but data is unexpectedly not forthcoming.
event-media-stalled.title: HTMLMediaElement: stalled event

handler-onstalled.name: stalled_event
handler-onstalled.summary: The stalled event is fired when the user agent is trying to fetch media data, but data is unexpectedly not forthcoming.
handler-onstalled.title: HTMLMediaElement: stalled event

event-media-suspend.name: suspend_event
event-media-suspend.summary: The suspend event is fired when media data loading has been suspended.
event-media-suspend.title: HTMLMediaElement: suspend event

handler-onsuspend.name: suspend_event
handler-onsuspend.summary: The suspend event is fired when media data loading has been suspended.
handler-onsuspend.title: HTMLMediaElement: suspend event

dom-media-texttracks-dev.name: textTracks
dom-media-texttracks-dev.summary: The read-only textTracks property on HTMLMediaElement objects returns a TextTrackList object listing all of the TextTrack objects representing the media element's text tracks, in the same order as in the list of text tracks.
dom-media-texttracks-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: textTracks property

event-media-timeupdate.name: timeupdate_event
event-media-timeupdate.summary: The timeupdate event is fired when the time indicated by the currentTime attribute has been updated.
event-media-timeupdate.title: HTMLMediaElement: timeupdate event

handler-ontimeupdate.name: timeupdate_event
handler-ontimeupdate.summary: The timeupdate event is fired when the time indicated by the currentTime attribute has been updated.
handler-ontimeupdate.title: HTMLMediaElement: timeupdate event

dom-media-videotracks-dev.name: videoTracks
dom-media-videotracks-dev.summary: The read-only videoTracks property on HTMLMediaElement objects returns a VideoTrackList object listing all of the VideoTrack objects representing the media element's video tracks.
dom-media-videotracks-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: videoTracks property

dom-media-volume-dev.name: volume
dom-media-volume-dev.summary: The HTMLMediaElement.volume property sets the volume at which the media will be played.

safari_ios.notes: volume returns a value and is writable; however, the value is always 1, and setting a value has no effect on the volume of the media object.

dom-media-volume-dev.title: HTMLMediaElement: volume property

event-media-volumechange.name: volumechange_event
event-media-volumechange.summary: The volumechange event is fired when either the volume attribute or the muted attribute has changed.
event-media-volumechange.title: HTMLMediaElement: volumechange event

handler-onvolumechange.name: volumechange_event
handler-onvolumechange.summary: The volumechange event is fired when either the volume attribute or the muted attribute has changed.
handler-onvolumechange.title: HTMLMediaElement: volumechange event

event-media-waiting.name: waiting_event
event-media-waiting.summary: The waiting event is fired when playback has stopped because of a temporary lack of data.
event-media-waiting.title: HTMLMediaElement: waiting event

handler-onwaiting.name: waiting_event
handler-onwaiting.summary: The waiting event is fired when playback has stopped because of a temporary lack of data.
handler-onwaiting.title: HTMLMediaElement: waiting event

htmlmediaelement.name: HTMLMediaElement
htmlmediaelement.summary: The HTMLMediaElement interface adds to HTMLElement the properties and methods needed to support basic media-related capabilities that are common to audio and video.
htmlmediaelement.title: HTMLMediaElement

htmlmenuelement.name: HTMLMenuElement
htmlmenuelement.summary: The HTMLMenuElement interface provides special properties (beyond those defined on the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <menu> elements.
htmlmenuelement.title: HTMLMenuElement

htmlmetaelement.name: HTMLMetaElement
htmlmetaelement.summary: The HTMLMetaElement interface contains descriptive metadata about a document provided in HTML as <meta> elements. This interface inherits all of the properties and methods described in the HTMLElement interface.
htmlmetaelement.title: HTMLMetaElement

htmlmeterelement.name: HTMLMeterElement
htmlmeterelement.summary: The HTML <meter> elements expose the HTMLMeterElement interface, which provides special properties and methods (beyond the HTMLElement object interface they also have available to them by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <meter> elements.
htmlmeterelement.title: HTMLMeterElement

htmlmodelement.name: HTMLModElement
htmlmodelement.summary: The HTMLModElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular methods and properties available through the HTMLElement interface they also have available to them by inheritance) for manipulating modification elements, that is <del> and <ins>.
htmlmodelement.title: HTMLModElement

htmlolistelement.name: HTMLOListElement
htmlolistelement.summary: The HTMLOListElement interface provides special properties (beyond those defined on the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating ordered list elements.
htmlolistelement.title: HTMLOListElement

dom-object-contentdocument.name: contentDocument
dom-object-contentdocument.summary: The contentDocument read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface Returns a Document representing the active document of the object element's nested browsing context, if any; otherwise null.
dom-object-contentdocument.title: HTMLObjectElement: contentDocument property

dom-object-contentwindow.name: contentWindow
dom-object-contentwindow.summary: The contentWindow read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a WindowProxy representing the window proxy of the object element's nested browsing context, if any; otherwise null.
dom-object-contentwindow.title: HTMLObjectElement: contentWindow property

dom-object-data.name: data
dom-object-data.summary: The data property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string that reflects the data HTML attribute, specifying the address of a resource's data.
dom-object-data.title: HTMLObjectElement: data property

dom-fae-form-dev.name: form
dom-fae-form-dev.summary: The form read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a HTMLFormElement representing the object element's form owner, or null if there isn't one.
dom-fae-form-dev.title: HTMLObjectElement: form property

dom-fae-form-dev.name: form
dom-fae-form-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.form read-only property returns a HTMLFormElement representing the form that this element is associated with. If the element is not associated with a <form> element, then it returns null.
dom-fae-form-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: form property

dom-dim-height.name: height
dom-dim-height.summary: The height property of the HTMLObjectElement interface Returns a string that reflects the height HTML attribute, specifying the displayed height of the resource in CSS pixels.
dom-dim-height.title: HTMLObjectElement: height property

dom-object-name.name: name
dom-object-name.summary: The name property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string that reflects the name HTML attribute, specifying the name of the browsing context.
dom-object-name.title: HTMLObjectElement: name property

dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.name: setCustomValidity
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.summary: The setCustomValidity() method of the HTMLObjectElement interface sets a custom validity message for the element.
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.title: HTMLObjectElement: setCustomValidity() method

dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.name: setCustomValidity
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.setCustomValidity() method sets the custom validity message for the selection element to the specified message. Use the empty string to indicate that the element does not have a custom validity error.
dom-cva-setcustomvalidity-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: setCustomValidity() method

dom-object-type.name: type
dom-object-type.summary: The type property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string that reflects the type HTML attribute, specifying the MIME type of the resource.
dom-object-type.title: HTMLObjectElement: type property

dom-object-usemap.name: useMap
dom-object-usemap.summary: The useMap property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string that reflects the usemap HTML attribute, specifying a <map> element to use.
dom-object-usemap.title: HTMLObjectElement: useMap property

dom-cva-validationmessage-dev.name: validationMessage
dom-cva-validationmessage-dev.summary: The validationMessage read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string representing a localized message that describes the validation constraints that the control does not satisfy (if any). This is the empty string if the control is not a candidate for constraint validation (willValidate is false), or it satisfies its constraints.
dom-cva-validationmessage-dev.title: HTMLObjectElement: validationMessage property

dom-cva-validity.name: validity
dom-cva-validity.summary: The validity read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a ValidityState with the validity states that this element is in.
dom-cva-validity.title: HTMLObjectElement: validity property

dom-dim-width.name: width
dom-dim-width.summary: The width property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a string that reflects the width HTML attribute, specifying the displayed width of the resource in CSS pixels.
dom-dim-width.title: HTMLObjectElement: width property

dom-cva-willvalidate-dev.name: willValidate
dom-cva-willvalidate-dev.summary: The willValidate read-only property of the HTMLObjectElement interface returns a boolean value that indicates whether the element is a candidate for constraint validation. Always false for HTMLObjectElement objects.
dom-cva-willvalidate-dev.title: HTMLObjectElement: willValidate property

htmlobjectelement.name: HTMLObjectElement
htmlobjectelement.summary: The HTMLObjectElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond those on the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <object> element, representing external resources.
htmlobjectelement.title: HTMLObjectElement

htmloptgroupelement.name: HTMLOptGroupElement
htmloptgroupelement.summary: The HTMLOptGroupElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement object interface they also have available to them by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <optgroup> elements.
htmloptgroupelement.title: HTMLOptGroupElement

dom-option-dev.name: Option
dom-option-dev.summary: The Option() constructor creates a new HTMLOptionElement.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 9, the outerHTML of elements lose their text when constructing with new Option().

dom-option-dev.title: HTMLOptionElement: Option() constructor

htmloptionelement.name: HTMLOptionElement
htmloptionelement.summary: The HTMLOptionElement interface represents <option> elements and inherits all properties and methods of the HTMLElement interface.
htmloptionelement.title: HTMLOptionElement

the-htmloptionscollection-interface.name: HTMLOptionsCollection
the-htmloptionscollection-interface.summary: The HTMLOptionsCollection interface represents a collection of <option> HTML elements (in document order) and offers methods and properties for selecting from the list as well as optionally altering its items. This object is returned only by the options property of select.
the-htmloptionscollection-interface.title: HTMLOptionsCollection

htmloutputelement.name: HTMLOutputElement
htmloutputelement.summary: The HTMLOutputElement interface provides properties and methods (beyond those inherited from HTMLElement) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <output> elements.
htmloutputelement.title: HTMLOutputElement

htmlparagraphelement.name: HTMLParagraphElement
htmlparagraphelement.summary:
The HTMLParagraphElement interface provides special properties (beyond those of the regular HTMLElement object interface it inherits) for manipulating

elements.
htmlparagraphelement.title: HTMLParagraphElement

htmlpictureelement.name: HTMLPictureElement
htmlpictureelement.summary: The HTMLPictureElement interface represents a <picture> HTML element. It doesn't implement specific properties or methods.
htmlpictureelement.title: HTMLPictureElement

htmlpreelement.name: HTMLPreElement
htmlpreelement.summary: The HTMLPreElement interface exposes specific properties and methods (beyond those of the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating a block of preformatted text (<pre>).
htmlpreelement.title: HTMLPreElement

htmlprogresselement.name: HTMLProgressElement
htmlprogresselement.summary: The HTMLProgressElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of <progress> elements.
htmlprogresselement.title: HTMLProgressElement

htmlquoteelement.name: HTMLQuoteElement
htmlquoteelement.summary: The HTMLQuoteElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating quoting elements, like <blockquote> and <q>, but not the <cite> element.
htmlquoteelement.title: HTMLQuoteElement

dom-script-referrerpolicy.name: referrerPolicy
dom-script-referrerpolicy.summary: The referrerPolicy property of the HTMLScriptElement interface reflects the HTML referrerpolicy of the <script> element, which defines how the referrer is set when fetching the script and any scripts it imports.
dom-script-referrerpolicy.title: HTMLScriptElement: referrerPolicy property

dom-script-supports.name: supports_static
dom-script-supports.summary: The supports() static method of the HTMLScriptElement interface provides a simple and consistent method to feature-detect what types of scripts are supported by the user agent.
dom-script-supports.title: HTMLScriptElement: supports() static method

htmlscriptelement.name: HTMLScriptElement
htmlscriptelement.summary: HTML <script> elements expose the HTMLScriptElement interface, which provides special properties and methods for manipulating the behavior and execution of <script> elements (beyond the inherited HTMLElement interface).
htmlscriptelement.title: HTMLScriptElement

dom-select-add-dev.name: add
dom-select-add-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.add() method adds an element to the collection of option elements for this select element.
dom-select-add-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: add() method

dom-select-item-dev.name: item
dom-select-item-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.item() method returns the Element corresponding to the HTMLOptionElement whose position in the options list corresponds to the index given in the parameter, or null if there are none.
dom-select-item-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: item() method

dom-select-nameditem-dev.name: namedItem
dom-select-nameditem-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.namedItem() method returns the HTMLOptionElement corresponding to the HTMLOptionElement whose name or id match the specified name, or null if no option matches.

ie.notes: namedItem does not appear to take the name attribute into account (only the id attribute) on Internet Explorer and Edge. There is a bug report to Microsoft about this.

dom-select-nameditem-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: namedItem() method

dom-select-options-dev.name: options
dom-select-options-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.options read-only property returns a HTMLOptionsCollection of the <option> elements contained by the <select> element.
dom-select-options-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: options property

dom-select-remove.name: remove
dom-select-remove.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.remove() method removes the element at the specified index from the options collection for this select element.
dom-select-remove.title: HTMLSelectElement: remove() method

dom-select-selectedindex-dev.name: selectedIndex
dom-select-selectedindex-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.selectedIndex property is a long that reflects the index of the first or last selected <option> element, depending on the value of multiple. The value -1 indicates that no element is selected.
dom-select-selectedindex-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: selectedIndex property

dom-select-selectedoptions-dev.name: selectedOptions
dom-select-selectedoptions-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLSelectElement property selectedOptions contains a list of the <option> elements contained within the <select> element that are currently selected. The list of selected options is an HTMLCollection object with one entry per currently selected option.
dom-select-selectedoptions-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: selectedOptions property

dom-select-type-dev.name: type
dom-select-type-dev.summary: The HTMLSelectElement.type read-only property returns the form control's type.
dom-select-type-dev.title: HTMLSelectElement: type property

htmlselectelement.name: HTMLSelectElement
htmlselectelement.summary: The HTMLSelectElement interface represents a <select> HTML Element. These elements also share all of the properties and methods of other HTML elements via the HTMLElement interface.

firefox.notes: You should watch for change events on <select> instead of watching <option> elements for events. See bug 1090602 and Multiprocess Firefox Web content compatibility for details.

htmlselectelement.title: HTMLSelectElement

dom-slot-assign.name: assign
dom-slot-assign.summary: The assign() method of the HTMLSlotElement interface sets the slot's manually assigned nodes to an ordered set of slottables. The manually assigned nodes set is initially empty until nodes are assigned using assign().
dom-slot-assign.title: HTMLSlotElement: assign() method

dom-slot-assignedelements-dev.name: assignedElements
dom-slot-assignedelements-dev.summary: The assignedElements() method of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns a sequence of the elements assigned to this slot (and no other nodes).
dom-slot-assignedelements-dev.title: HTMLSlotElement: assignedElements() method

dom-slot-assignednodes-dev.name: assignedNodes
dom-slot-assignednodes-dev.summary: The assignedNodes() method of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns a sequence of the nodes assigned to this slot.
dom-slot-assignednodes-dev.title: HTMLSlotElement: assignedNodes() method

dom-slot-name-dev.name: name
dom-slot-name-dev.summary: The name property of the HTMLSlotElement interface returns or sets the slot name. A slot is a placeholder inside a web component that users can fill with their own markup.
dom-slot-name-dev.title: HTMLSlotElement: name property

handler-onslotchange.name: slotchange_event
handler-onslotchange.summary: The slotchange event is fired on an HTMLSlotElement instance (<slot> element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
handler-onslotchange.title: HTMLSlotElement: slotchange event

htmlslotelement.name: HTMLSlotElement
htmlslotelement.summary: The HTMLSlotElement interface of the Shadow DOM API enables access to the name and assigned nodes of an HTML <slot> element.
htmlslotelement.title: HTMLSlotElement

htmlsourceelement.name: HTMLSourceElement
htmlsourceelement.summary: The HTMLSourceElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement object interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <source> elements.
htmlsourceelement.title: HTMLSourceElement

htmlspanelement.name: HTMLSpanElement
htmlspanelement.summary: The HTMLSpanElement interface represents a <span> element and derives from the HTMLElement interface, but without implementing any additional properties or methods.
htmlspanelement.title: HTMLSpanElement

dom-style-disabled.name: disabled
dom-style-disabled.summary: The HTMLStyleElement.disabled property can be used to get and set whether the stylesheet is disabled (true) or not (false).
dom-style-disabled.title: HTMLStyleElement: disabled property

dom-style-media.name: media
dom-style-media.summary: The HTMLStyleElement.media property specifies the intended destination medium for style information.
dom-style-media.title: HTMLStyleElement: media property

htmlstyleelement.name: HTMLStyleElement
htmlstyleelement.summary: The HTMLStyleElement interface represents a <style> element. It inherits properties and methods from its parent, HTMLElement.
htmlstyleelement.title: HTMLStyleElement

htmltablecaptionelement.name: HTMLTableCaptionElement
htmltablecaptionelement.summary: The HTMLTableCaptionElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating table <caption> elements.
htmltablecaptionelement.title: HTMLTableCaptionElement

htmltablecellelement.name: HTMLTableCellElement
htmltablecellelement.summary: The HTMLTableCellElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of table cells, either header cells (<th>)) or data cells (<td>), in an HTML document.
htmltablecellelement.title: HTMLTableCellElement

htmltablecolelement.name: HTMLTableColElement
htmltablecolelement.summary: The HTMLTableColElement interface provides properties for manipulating single or grouped table column elements.
htmltablecolelement.title: HTMLTableColElement

dom-table-caption-dev.name: caption
dom-table-caption-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.caption property represents the table caption. If no caption element is associated with the table, this property is null.
dom-table-caption-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: caption property

dom-table-createcaption-dev.name: createCaption
dom-table-createcaption-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.createCaption() method returns the <caption> element associated with a given <table>. If no <caption> element exists on the table, this method creates it, and then returns it.
dom-table-createcaption-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: createCaption() method

dom-table-createtbody-dev.name: createTBody
dom-table-createtbody-dev.summary: The createTBody() method of HTMLTableElement objects creates and returns a new <tbody> element associated with a given <table>.
dom-table-createtbody-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: createTBody() method

dom-table-createtfoot-dev.name: createTFoot
dom-table-createtfoot-dev.summary: The createTFoot() method of HTMLTableElement objects returns the <tfoot> element associated with a given <table>. If no footer exists in the table, this method creates it, and then returns it.
dom-table-createtfoot-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: createTFoot() method

dom-table-createthead-dev.name: createTHead
dom-table-createthead-dev.summary: The createTHead() method of HTMLTableElement objects returns the <thead> element associated with a given <table>. If no header exists in the table, this method creates it, and then returns it.
dom-table-createthead-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: createTHead() method

dom-table-deletecaption-dev.name: deleteCaption
dom-table-deletecaption-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.deleteCaption() method removes the <caption> element from a given <table>. If there is no <caption> element associated with the table, this method does nothing.
dom-table-deletecaption-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: deleteCaption() method

dom-table-deleterow-dev.name: deleteRow
dom-table-deleterow-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.deleteRow() method removes a specific row (<tr>) from a given <table>.
dom-table-deleterow-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: deleteRow() method

dom-table-deletetfoot-dev.name: deleteTFoot
dom-table-deletetfoot-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.deleteTFoot() method removes the <tfoot> element from a given <table>.
dom-table-deletetfoot-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: deleteTFoot() method

dom-table-deletethead-dev.name: deleteTHead
dom-table-deletethead-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.deleteTHead() removes the <thead> element from a given <table>.
dom-table-deletethead-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: deleteTHead() method

dom-table-insertrow-dev.name: insertRow
dom-table-insertrow-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.insertRow() method inserts a new row (<tr>) in a given <table>, and returns a reference to the new row.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 20, the index parameter has been made optional and defaults to -1 as per HTML specification.

dom-table-insertrow-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: insertRow() method

dom-table-rows-dev.name: rows
dom-table-rows-dev.summary: The read-only HTMLTableElement property rows returns a live HTMLCollection of all the rows in the table, including the rows contained within any <thead>, <tfoot>, and <tbody> elements.
dom-table-rows-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: rows property

dom-table-tbodies-dev.name: tBodies
dom-table-tbodies-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.tBodies read-only property returns a live HTMLCollection of the bodies in a <table>.
dom-table-tbodies-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: tBodies property

dom-table-tfoot-dev.name: tFoot
dom-table-tfoot-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.tFoot property represents the <tfoot> element of a <table>. Its value will be null if there is no such element.
dom-table-tfoot-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: tFoot property

dom-table-thead-dev.name: tHead
dom-table-thead-dev.summary: The HTMLTableElement.tHead represents the <thead> element of a <table>. Its value will be null if there is no such element.
dom-table-thead-dev.title: HTMLTableElement: tHead property

htmltableelement.name: HTMLTableElement
htmltableelement.summary: The HTMLTableElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular HTMLElement object interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of tables in an HTML document.
htmltableelement.title: HTMLTableElement

dom-tr-insertcell-dev.name: insertCell
dom-tr-insertcell-dev.summary: The HTMLTableRowElement.insertCell() method inserts a new cell (<td>) into a table row (<tr>) and returns a reference to the cell.
dom-tr-insertcell-dev.title: HTMLTableRowElement: insertCell() method

dom-tr-rowindex-dev.name: rowIndex
dom-tr-rowindex-dev.summary: The HTMLTableRowElement.rowIndex read-only property represents the position of a row in relation to the whole <table>.
dom-tr-rowindex-dev.title: HTMLTableRowElement: rowIndex property

htmltablerowelement.name: HTMLTableRowElement
htmltablerowelement.summary: The HTMLTableRowElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of rows in an HTML table.
htmltablerowelement.title: HTMLTableRowElement

htmltablesectionelement.name: HTMLTableSectionElement
htmltablesectionelement.summary: The HTMLTableSectionElement interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of sections, that is headers, footers and bodies (<thead>, <tfoot>, and <tbody>, respectively) in an HTML table.
htmltablesectionelement.title: HTMLTableSectionElement

dom-template-content-dev.name: content
dom-template-content-dev.summary: The HTMLTemplateElement.content property returns a <template> element's template contents (a DocumentFragment).
dom-template-content-dev.title: HTMLTemplateElement: content property

htmltemplateelement.name: HTMLTemplateElement
htmltemplateelement.summary: The HTMLTemplateElement interface enables access to the contents of an HTML <template> element.
htmltemplateelement.title: HTMLTemplateElement

htmltextareaelement.name: HTMLTextAreaElement
htmltextareaelement.summary: The HTMLTextAreaElement interface provides special properties and methods for manipulating the layout and presentation of <textarea> elements.
htmltextareaelement.title: HTMLTextAreaElement

dom-time-datetime.name: dateTime
dom-time-datetime.summary: The HTMLTimeElement.dateTime property is a string that reflects the datetime HTML attribute, containing a machine-readable form of the element's date and time value.
dom-time-datetime.title: HTMLTimeElement: dateTime property

htmltimeelement.name: HTMLTimeElement
htmltimeelement.summary: The HTMLTimeElement interface provides special properties (beyond the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating <time> elements.
htmltimeelement.title: HTMLTimeElement

htmltitleelement.name: HTMLTitleElement
htmltitleelement.summary: The HTMLTitleElement interface is implemented by a document's <title>. This element inherits all of the properties and methods of the HTMLElement interface.
htmltitleelement.title: HTMLTitleElement

event-media-cuechange.name: cuechange_event
event-media-cuechange.summary: The cuechange event fires when a TextTrack has changed the currently displaying cues. The event is fired on both the TextTrack and the HTMLTrackElement in which it's being presented, if any.

chrome.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

opera.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

opera_android.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

safari.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

webview_android.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

edge_blink.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

event-media-cuechange.title: HTMLTrackElement: cuechange event

event-media-cuechange.name: cuechange_event
event-media-cuechange.summary: The cuechange event fires when a TextTrack has changed the currently displaying cues. The event is fired on both the TextTrack and the HTMLTrackElement in which it's being presented, if any.
event-media-cuechange.title: TextTrack: cuechange event

handler-oncuechange.name: cuechange_event
handler-oncuechange.summary: The cuechange event fires when a TextTrack has changed the currently displaying cues. The event is fired on both the TextTrack and the HTMLTrackElement in which it's being presented, if any.

chrome.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

opera.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

opera_android.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

safari.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

webview_android.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

edge_blink.notes: The oncuechange event handler property is not supported.

handler-oncuechange.title: HTMLTrackElement: cuechange event

dom-track-src.name: src
dom-track-src.summary: The HTMLTrackElement.src property reflects the value of the <track> element's src attribute, which indicates the URL of the text track's data.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 50, setting the src property did not work properly.

dom-track-src.title: HTMLTrackElement: src property

htmltrackelement.name: HTMLTrackElement
htmltrackelement.summary: The HTMLTrackElement interface represents an HTML <track> element within the DOM. This element can be used as a child of either <audio> or <video> to specify a text track containing information such as closed captions or subtitles.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 50, text tracks would only load if the <track> element is in a document.

htmltrackelement.title: HTMLTrackElement

htmlulistelement.name: HTMLUListElement
htmlulistelement.summary: The HTMLUListElement interface provides special properties (beyond those defined on the regular HTMLElement interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating unordered list (<ul>) elements.
htmlulistelement.title: HTMLUListElement

htmlunknownelement.name: HTMLUnknownElement
htmlunknownelement.summary: The HTMLUnknownElement interface represents an invalid HTML element and derives from the HTMLElement interface, but without implementing any additional properties or methods.
htmlunknownelement.title: HTMLUnknownElement

dom-video-videoheight-dev.name: videoHeight
dom-video-videoheight-dev.summary: The HTMLVideoElement interface's read-only videoHeight property indicates the intrinsic height of the video, expressed in CSS pixels. In simple terms, this is the height of the media in its natural size.
dom-video-videoheight-dev.title: HTMLVideoElement: videoHeight property

dom-video-videowidth-dev.name: videoWidth
dom-video-videowidth-dev.summary: The HTMLVideoElement interface's read-only videoWidth property indicates the intrinsic width of the video, expressed in CSS pixels. In simple terms, this is the width of the media in its natural size.
dom-video-videowidth-dev.title: HTMLVideoElement: videoWidth property

htmlvideoelement.name: HTMLVideoElement
htmlvideoelement.summary: Implemented by the <video> element, the HTMLVideoElement interface provides special properties and methods for manipulating video objects. It also inherits properties and methods of HTMLMediaElement and HTMLElement.
htmlvideoelement.title: HTMLVideoElement

the-hashchangeevent-interface.name: HashChangeEvent
the-hashchangeevent-interface.summary: The HashChangeEvent() constructor creates a new HashChangeEvent object, that is used by the hashchange event fired at the window object when the fragment of the URL changes.
the-hashchangeevent-interface.title: HashChangeEvent: HashChangeEvent() constructor

the-hashchangeevent-interface.name: HashChangeEvent
the-hashchangeevent-interface.summary: The HashChangeEvent interface represents events that fire when the fragment identifier of the URL has changed.
the-hashchangeevent-interface.title: HashChangeEvent

dom-hashchangeevent-newurl-dev.name: newURL
dom-hashchangeevent-newurl-dev.summary: The newURL read-only property of the HashChangeEvent interface returns the new URL to which the window is navigating.
dom-hashchangeevent-newurl-dev.title: HashChangeEvent: newURL property

dom-hashchangeevent-oldurl-dev.name: oldURL
dom-hashchangeevent-oldurl-dev.summary: The oldURL read-only property of the HashChangeEvent interface returns the previous URL from which the window was navigated.
dom-hashchangeevent-oldurl-dev.title: HashChangeEvent: oldURL property

dom-history-back-dev.name: back
dom-history-back-dev.summary: The History.back() method causes the browser to move back one page in the session history.
dom-history-back-dev.title: History: back() method

dom-history-forward-dev.name: forward
dom-history-forward-dev.summary: The History.forward() method causes the browser to move forward one page in the session history. It has the same effect as calling history.go(1).
dom-history-forward-dev.title: History: forward() method

dom-history-go-dev.name: go
dom-history-go-dev.summary: The History.go() method loads a specific page from the session history. You can use it to move forwards and backwards through the history depending on the value of a parameter.
dom-history-go-dev.title: History: go() method

dom-history-length-dev.name: length
dom-history-length-dev.summary: The History.length read-only property returns an integer representing the number of elements in the session history, including the currently loaded page.
dom-history-length-dev.title: History: length property

dom-history-pushstate-dev.name: pushState
dom-history-pushstate-dev.summary: In an HTML document, the history.pushState() method adds an entry to the browser's session history stack.

firefox.notes: Until Firefox 5, the passed object is serialized using JSON. Starting in Firefox 6, the object is serialized using the structured clone algorithm. This allows a wider variety of objects to be safely passed.

dom-history-pushstate-dev.title: History: pushState() method

dom-history-replacestate-dev.name: replaceState
dom-history-replacestate-dev.summary: The History.replaceState() method modifies the current history entry, replacing it with the state object and URL passed in the method parameters. This method is particularly useful when you want to update the state object or URL of the current history entry in response to some user action.

firefox.notes: Until Firefox 5, the passed object is serialized using JSON. Starting in Firefox 6, the object is serialized using the structured clone algorithm. This allows a wider variety of objects to be safely passed.

dom-history-replacestate-dev.title: History: replaceState() method

dom-history-scroll-restoration-dev.name: scrollRestoration
dom-history-scroll-restoration-dev.summary: The scrollRestoration property of History interface allows web applications to explicitly set default scroll restoration behavior on history navigation.
dom-history-scroll-restoration-dev.title: History: scrollRestoration property

dom-history-state-dev.name: state
dom-history-state-dev.summary: The History.state property returns a value representing the state at the top of the history stack. This is a way to look at the state without having to wait for a popstate event.
dom-history-state-dev.title: History: state property

the-history-interface.name: History
the-history-interface.summary: The History interface allows manipulation of the browser session history, that is the pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in.
the-history-interface.title: History

the-history-interface.name: history
the-history-interface.summary: The Window.history read-only property returns a reference to the History object, which provides an interface for manipulating the browser session history (pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in).
the-history-interface.title: Window: history property

dom-imagebitmap-close-dev.name: close
dom-imagebitmap-close-dev.summary: The ImageBitmap.close() method disposes of all graphical resources associated with an ImageBitmap.
dom-imagebitmap-close-dev.title: ImageBitmap: close() method

dom-imagebitmap-height-dev.name: height
dom-imagebitmap-height-dev.summary: The read-only ImageBitmap.height property returns the ImageBitmap object's height in CSS pixels.
dom-imagebitmap-height-dev.title: ImageBitmap: height property

dom-imagebitmap-width-dev.name: width
dom-imagebitmap-width-dev.summary: The read-only ImageBitmap.width property returns the ImageBitmap object's width in CSS pixels.
dom-imagebitmap-width-dev.title: ImageBitmap: width property

imagebitmap.name: ImageBitmap
imagebitmap.summary: The ImageBitmap interface represents a bitmap image which can be drawn to a <canvas> without undue latency. It can be created from a variety of source objects using the createImageBitmap() factory method. ImageBitmap provides an asynchronous and resource efficient pathway to prepare textures for rendering in WebGL.
imagebitmap.title: ImageBitmap

dom-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-transfer.name: transferFromImageBitmap
dom-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-transfer.summary: The ImageBitmapRenderingContext.transferFromImageBitmap() method displays the given ImageBitmap in the canvas associated with this rendering context. The ownership of the ImageBitmap is transferred to the canvas as well.
dom-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-transfer.title: ImageBitmapRenderingContext: transferFromImageBitmap() method

the-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-interfac.name: ImageBitmapRenderingContext
the-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-interfac.summary: The ImageBitmapRenderingContext interface is a canvas rendering context that provides the functionality to replace the canvas's contents with the given ImageBitmap. Its context id (the first argument to HTMLCanvasElement.getContext() or OffscreenCanvas.getContext()) is "bitmaprenderer".
the-imagebitmaprenderingcontext-interfac.title: ImageBitmapRenderingContext

dom-imagedata-dev.name: ImageData
dom-imagedata-dev.summary: The ImageData() constructor returns a newly instantiated ImageData object built from the typed array given and having the specified width and height.
dom-imagedata-dev.title: ImageData: ImageData() constructor

dom-imagedata-colorspace.name: colorSpace
dom-imagedata-colorspace.summary: The read-only ImageData.colorSpace property is a string indicating the color space of the image data.
dom-imagedata-colorspace.title: ImageData: colorSpace property

dom-imagedata-data-dev.name: data
dom-imagedata-data-dev.summary: The readonly ImageData.data property returns a Uint8ClampedArray that contains the ImageData object's pixel data. Data is stored as a one-dimensional array in the RGBA order, with integer values between 0 and 255 (inclusive).
dom-imagedata-data-dev.title: ImageData: data property

dom-imagedata-height-dev.name: height
dom-imagedata-height-dev.summary: The readonly ImageData.height property returns the number of rows in the ImageData object.
dom-imagedata-height-dev.title: ImageData: height property

dom-imagedata-width-dev.name: width
dom-imagedata-width-dev.summary: The readonly ImageData.width property returns the number of pixels per row in the ImageData object.
dom-imagedata-width-dev.title: ImageData: width property

imagedata.name: ImageData
imagedata.summary: The ImageData interface represents the underlying pixel data of an area of a <canvas> element.
imagedata.title: ImageData

dom-location-ancestororigins-dev.name: ancestorOrigins
dom-location-ancestororigins-dev.summary: The ancestorOrigins read-only property of the Location interface is a static DOMStringList containing, in reverse order, the origins of all ancestor browsing contexts of the document associated with the given Location object.
dom-location-ancestororigins-dev.title: location: ancestorOrigins property

dom-location-assign-dev.name: assign
dom-location-assign-dev.summary: The Location.assign() method causes the window to load and display the document at the URL specified. After the navigation occurs, the user can navigate back to the page that called Location.assign() by pressing the "back" button.
dom-location-assign-dev.title: location: assign() method

dom-location-hash-dev.name: hash
dom-location-hash-dev.summary: The hash property of the Location interface returns a string containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL  the ID on the page that the URL is trying to target.
dom-location-hash-dev.title: location: hash property

dom-location-host-dev.name: host
dom-location-host-dev.summary: The host property of the Location interface is a string containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', and the port of the URL.
dom-location-host-dev.title: location: host property

dom-location-hostname-dev.name: hostname
dom-location-hostname-dev.summary: The hostname property of the Location interface is a string containing the domain of the URL.
dom-location-hostname-dev.title: location: hostname property

dom-location-href-dev.name: href
dom-location-href-dev.summary: The href property of the Location interface is a stringifier that returns a string containing the whole URL, and allows the href to be updated.
dom-location-href-dev.title: location: href property

dom-location-href-dev.name: toString
dom-location-href-dev.summary: The toString() stringifier method of the Location interface returns a string containing the whole URL. It is a read-only version of Location.href.

ie.notes: Intranet sites are set to Compatibility View, which will emulate IE7 and omit window.location.toString.

dom-location-href-dev.title: location: toString() method

dom-location-origin-dev.name: origin
dom-location-origin-dev.summary: The origin read-only property of the Location interface is a string containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 49, results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

ie.notes: Intranet sites are set to Compatibility View, which will emulate IE7 and omit window.location.origin.

dom-location-origin-dev.title: location: origin property

dom-location-pathname-dev.name: pathname
dom-location-pathname-dev.summary: The pathname property of the Location interface is a string containing the path of the URL for the location. If there is no path, pathname will be empty: otherwise, pathname contains an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL, not including the query string or fragment.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the pathname property returned wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" rather than "/x".

ie.notes: Internet Explorer does not provide the leading slash character in the pathname (docs/Web/API/Location instead of /docs/Web/API/Location).

dom-location-pathname-dev.title: location: pathname property

dom-location-port-dev.name: port
dom-location-port-dev.summary: The port property of the Location interface is a string containing the port number of the URL. If the URL does not contain an explicit port number, it will be set to ''.
dom-location-port-dev.title: location: port property

dom-location-protocol-dev.name: protocol
dom-location-protocol-dev.summary: The protocol property of the Location interface is a string representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-location-protocol-dev.title: location: protocol property

dom-location-reload-dev.name: reload
dom-location-reload-dev.summary: The location.reload() method reloads the current URL, like the Refresh button.

ie.notes: If a page added to Trusted Sites contains a cross-origin iframe, then calling reload() from within the iframe reloads the trusted page (in other words, the top page reloads, not the iframe).

dom-location-reload-dev.title: location: reload() method

dom-location-replace-dev.name: replace
dom-location-replace-dev.summary: The replace() method of the Location interface replaces the current resource with the one at the provided URL. The difference from the assign() method is that after using replace() the current page will not be saved in session History, meaning the user won't be able to use the back button to navigate to it.
dom-location-replace-dev.title: location: replace() method

dom-location-search-dev.name: search
dom-location-search-dev.summary: The search property of the Location interface is a search string, also called a query string; that is, a string containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 53, the search property returned wrong parts of the URL. For example, for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, search would return "", rather than "?a=true&b=false".

dom-location-search-dev.title: location: search property

dom-mediaerror-code-dev.name: code
dom-mediaerror-code-dev.summary: The read-only property MediaError.code returns a numeric value which represents the kind of error that occurred on a media element. To get a text string with specific diagnostic information, see MediaError.message.
dom-mediaerror-code-dev.title: MediaError: code property

dom-mediaerror-message-dev.name: message
dom-mediaerror-message-dev.summary: The read-only property MediaError.message returns a human-readable string offering specific diagnostic details related to the error described by the MediaError object, or an empty string ("") if no diagnostic information can be determined or provided.
dom-mediaerror-message-dev.title: MediaError: message property

error-codes.name: MediaError
error-codes.summary: The MediaError interface represents an error which occurred while handling media in an HTML media element based on HTMLMediaElement, such as <audio> or <video>.
error-codes.title: MediaError

dom-messagechannel-dev.name: MessageChannel
dom-messagechannel-dev.summary: The MessageChannel() constructor of the MessageChannel interface returns a new MessageChannel object with two new MessagePort objects.

nodejs.notes: Must be imported from the worker_threads module.

dom-messagechannel-dev.title: MessageChannel: MessageChannel() constructor

dom-messagechannel-port1-dev.name: port1
dom-messagechannel-port1-dev.summary: The port1 read-only property of the MessageChannel interface returns the first port of the message channel  the port attached to the context that originated the channel.
dom-messagechannel-port1-dev.title: MessageChannel: port1 property

dom-messagechannel-port2-dev.name: port2
dom-messagechannel-port2-dev.summary: The port2 read-only property of the MessageChannel interface returns the second port of the message channel  the port attached to the context at the other end of the channel, which the message is initially sent to.
dom-messagechannel-port2-dev.title: MessageChannel: port2 property

message-channels.name: MessageChannel
message-channels.summary: The MessageChannel interface of the Channel Messaging API allows us to create a new message channel and send data through it via its two MessagePort properties.

nodejs.notes: Must be imported from the worker_threads module.

message-channels.title: MessageChannel

the-messageevent-interface:dom-event-con.name: MessageEvent
the-messageevent-interface:dom-event-con.summary: The MessageEvent() constructor creates a new MessageEvent object.
the-messageevent-interface:dom-event-con.title: MessageEvent: MessageEvent() constructor

dom-messageevent-data-dev.name: data
dom-messageevent-data-dev.summary: The data read-only property of the MessageEvent interface represents the data sent by the message emitter.
dom-messageevent-data-dev.title: MessageEvent: data property

dom-messageevent-lasteventid-dev.name: lastEventId
dom-messageevent-lasteventid-dev.summary: The lastEventId read-only property of the MessageEvent interface is a string representing a unique ID for the event.
dom-messageevent-lasteventid-dev.title: MessageEvent: lastEventId property

dom-messageevent-origin-dev.name: origin
dom-messageevent-origin-dev.summary: The origin read-only property of the MessageEvent interface is a string representing the origin of the message emitter.
dom-messageevent-origin-dev.title: MessageEvent: origin property

dom-messageevent-ports-dev.name: ports
dom-messageevent-ports-dev.summary: The ports read-only property of the MessageEvent interface is an array of MessagePort objects representing the ports associated with the channel the message is being sent through (where appropriate, e.g. in channel messaging or when sending a message to a shared worker).
dom-messageevent-ports-dev.title: MessageEvent: ports property

dom-messageevent-source-dev.name: source
dom-messageevent-source-dev.summary: The source read-only property of the MessageEvent interface is a MessageEventSource (which can be a WindowProxy, MessagePort, or ServiceWorker object) representing the message emitter.
dom-messageevent-source-dev.title: MessageEvent: source property

the-messageevent-interface.name: MessageEvent
the-messageevent-interface.summary: The MessageEvent interface represents a message received by a target object.
the-messageevent-interface.title: MessageEvent

dom-messageport-close-dev.name: close
dom-messageport-close-dev.summary: The close() method of the MessagePort interface disconnects the port, so it is no longer active. This stops the flow of messages to that port.

nodejs.notes: Supports the event, but only via Node EventEmitter.

dom-messageport-close-dev.title: MessagePort: close() method

handler-messageport-onmessage.name: message_event
handler-messageport-onmessage.summary: The message event is fired on a MessagePort object when a message arrives on that channel.

nodejs.notes: Supports the event, but only via Node EventEmitter.

handler-messageport-onmessage.title: MessagePort: message event

handler-messageport-onmessageerror.name: messageerror_event
handler-messageport-onmessageerror.summary: The messageerror event is fired on a MessagePort object when it receives a message that can't be deserialized.

nodejs.notes: Supports the event, but only via Node EventEmitter.

safari.notes: See bug 171216.

handler-messageport-onmessageerror.title: MessagePort: messageerror event

dom-messageport-postmessage-dev.name: postMessage
dom-messageport-postmessage-dev.summary: The postMessage() method of the MessagePort interface sends a message from the port, and optionally, transfers ownership of objects to other browsing contexts.

deno.notes: The message parameter does not support cloning Blob values.

notes: The message parameter does not support cloning Blob values.
The transfer parameter does not accept ArrayBuffer items. Passing an ArrayBuffer results in an error being thrown.

dom-messageport-postmessage-dev.title: MessagePort: postMessage() method

dom-messageport-start-dev.name: start
dom-messageport-start-dev.summary: The start() method of the MessagePort interface starts the sending of messages queued on the port. This method is only needed when using EventTarget.addEventListener; it is implied when using onmessage.
dom-messageport-start-dev.title: MessagePort: start() method

message-ports.name: MessagePort
message-ports.summary: The MessagePort interface of the Channel Messaging API represents one of the two ports of a MessageChannel, allowing messages to be sent from one port and listening out for them arriving at the other.

nodejs.notes: Is a Node EventEmitter instead of DOM EventTarget.

message-ports.title: MessagePort

dom-navigator-cookieenabled-dev.name: cookieEnabled
dom-navigator-cookieenabled-dev.summary: navigator.cookieEnabled returns a Boolean value that indicates whether cookies are enabled or not.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 8, navigator.cookieEnabled would report the wrong result if a site exception was in place for the page on which the check was performed. This has been fixed.

ie.notes: navigator.cookieEnabled returns true even if the browser is set to block cookies (for example, if the page is in the Restricted sites security zone).

dom-navigator-cookieenabled-dev.title: Navigator: cookieEnabled property

dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.name: hardwareConcurrency
dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.summary: The navigator.hardwareConcurrency read-only property returns the number of logical processors available to run threads on the user's computer.
dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.title: Navigator: hardwareConcurrency property

dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.name: hardwareConcurrency
dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.summary: The navigator.hardwareConcurrency read-only property returns the number of logical processors available to run threads on the user's computer.
dom-navigator-hardwareconcurrency-dev.title: Navigator: hardwareConcurrency property

dom-navigator-language-dev.name: language
dom-navigator-language-dev.summary: The Navigator.language read-only property returns a string representing the preferred language of the user, usually the language of the browser UI.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this property's value was also part of the user agent string, as reported by navigator.userAgent. Starting in Firefox 5, this property's value is based on the value of the Accept-Language HTTP header.

ie.notes: Closest available (non-standard) properties are userLanguage and browserLanguage.

dom-navigator-language-dev.title: Navigator: language property

dom-navigator-language-dev.name: language
dom-navigator-language-dev.summary: The WorkerNavigator.language read-only property returns a string representing the preferred language of the user, usually the language of the browser UI.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this property's value was also part of the user agent string, as reported by navigator.userAgent. Starting in Firefox 5, this property's value is based on the value of the Accept-Language HTTP header.

ie.notes: Closest available (non-standard) properties are userLanguage and browserLanguage.

dom-navigator-language-dev.title: WorkerNavigator: language property

dom-navigator-languages-dev.name: languages
dom-navigator-languages-dev.summary: The Navigator.languages read-only property returns an array of strings representing the user's preferred languages. The language is described using language tags according to RFC 5646: Tags for Identifying Languages (also known as BCP 47). In the returned array they are ordered by preference with the most preferred language first.

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

firefox.notes: In Firefox, the navigator.languages property's value is taken from the intl.accept_languages preference.

ie.notes: Closest available (non-standard) properties are userLanguage and browserLanguage.

webview_android.notes: Before version 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

edge_blink.notes: Before Chrome 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

dom-navigator-languages-dev.title: Navigator: languages property

dom-navigator-languages-dev.name: languages
dom-navigator-languages-dev.summary: The WorkerNavigator.languages read-only property returns an array of strings representing the user's preferred languages. The language is described using language tags according to RFC 5646: Tags for Identifying Languages (also known as BCP 47). In the returned array they are ordered by preference with the most preferred language first.

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

firefox.notes: In Firefox, the navigator.languages property's value is taken from the intl.accept_languages preference.

ie.notes: Closest available (non-standard) properties are userLanguage and browserLanguage.

webview_android.notes: Before version 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

edge_blink.notes: Before Chrome 65, navigator.languages[0] is not guaranteed to equal navigator.language.

dom-navigator-languages-dev.title: WorkerNavigator: languages property

dom-navigator-online-dev.name: onLine
dom-navigator-online-dev.summary: Returns the online status of the browser. The property returns a boolean value, with true meaning online and false meaning offline. The property sends updates whenever the browser's ability to connect to the network changes. The update occurs when the user follows links or when a script requests a remote page. For example, the property should return false when users click links soon after they lose internet connection.

chrome.notes: Earlier versions of Chrome incorrectly return true when a tab is first opened, but it starts reporting the correct connectivity status after the first network event. Windows: 11, macOS: 14, Chrome OS: 13, Linux: Always returns true. For history, see crbug.com/7469.

firefox.notes: Since Firefox 4 the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity. Since Firefox 41, on OS X and Windows, the returned values follow the actual network connectivity, unless 'Work offline' mode is selected (where it will always return false).

ie.notes: in Internet Explorer 8 'online' and 'offline' events are raised on the document.body; under IE 9 they are raised on both document.body and window.

opera.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.

opera_android.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.

webview_android.notes: Can incorrectly return true, see bug 811122.

edge_blink.notes: Earlier versions of Chrome incorrectly return true when a tab is first opened, but it starts reporting the correct connectivity status after the first network event. Windows: 11, macOS: 14, Chrome OS: 13, Linux: Always returns true. For history, see crbug.com/7469.

dom-navigator-online-dev.title: Navigator: onLine property

dom-navigator-online-dev.name: onLine
dom-navigator-online-dev.summary: Returns the online status of the browser. The property returns a boolean value, with true meaning online and false meaning offline. The property sends updates whenever the browser's ability to connect to the network changes. The update occurs when the user follows links or when a script requests a remote page.

firefox.notes: Since Firefox 4 the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity. Since Firefox 41, on OS X and Windows, the returned values follow the actual network connectivity, unless 'Work offline' mode is selected (where it will always return false).

opera.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.

opera_android.notes: From Opera 11.1 until Opera 12.1, the browser returns true when 'Work Offline' mode is disabled and false when it is enabled, regardless of actual connectivity.
