the-workerglobalscope-common-interface.name: WorkerGlobalScope
the-workerglobalscope-common-interface.summary: The WorkerGlobalScope interface of the Web Workers API is an interface representing the scope of any worker. Workers have no browsing context; this scope contains the information usually conveyed by Window objects  in this case event handlers, the console or the associated WorkerNavigator object. Each WorkerGlobalScope has its own event loop.
the-workerglobalscope-common-interface.title: WorkerGlobalScope

dom-workerlocation-hash.name: hash
dom-workerlocation-hash.summary: The hash property of a WorkerLocation object returns the hash part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-hash.title: WorkerLocation: hash property

dom-workerlocation-host.name: host
dom-workerlocation-host.summary: The host property of a WorkerLocation object returns the host part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-host.title: WorkerLocation: host property

dom-workerlocation-hostname.name: hostname
dom-workerlocation-hostname.summary: The hostname property of a WorkerLocation object returns the hostname part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-hostname.title: WorkerLocation: hostname property

dom-workerlocation-href.name: href
dom-workerlocation-href.summary: The href property of a WorkerLocation object returns a string containing the serialized URL for the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-href.title: WorkerLocation: href property

dom-workerlocation-origin.name: origin
dom-workerlocation-origin.summary: The origin property of a WorkerLocation object returns the worker's origin.
dom-workerlocation-origin.title: WorkerLocation: origin property

dom-workerlocation-pathname.name: pathname
dom-workerlocation-pathname.summary: The pathname property of a WorkerLocation object returns the pathname part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-pathname.title: WorkerLocation: pathname property

dom-workerlocation-port.name: port
dom-workerlocation-port.summary: The port property of a WorkerLocation object returns the port part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-port.title: WorkerLocation: port property

dom-workerlocation-protocol.name: protocol
dom-workerlocation-protocol.summary: The protocol property of a WorkerLocation object returns the protocol part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-protocol.title: WorkerLocation: protocol property

dom-workerlocation-search.name: search
dom-workerlocation-search.summary: The search property of a WorkerLocation object returns the search part of the worker's location.
dom-workerlocation-search.title: WorkerLocation: search property

workerlocation.name: toString
workerlocation.summary: The toString() stringifier method of a WorkerLocation object returns a string containing the serialized URL for the worker's location. It is a synonym for WorkerLocation.href.
workerlocation.title: WorkerLocation: toString() method

worker-locations.name: WorkerLocation
worker-locations.summary: The WorkerLocation interface defines the absolute location of the script executed by the Worker. Such an object is initialized for each worker and is available via the WorkerGlobalScope.location property obtained by calling self.location.
worker-locations.title: WorkerLocation

the-workernavigator-object.name: WorkerNavigator
the-workernavigator-object.summary: The WorkerNavigator interface represents a subset of the Navigator interface allowed to be accessed from a Worker. Such an object is initialized for each worker and is available via the self.navigator property.
the-workernavigator-object.title: WorkerNavigator

dom-worklet-addmodule-dev.name: addModule
dom-worklet-addmodule-dev.summary: The addModule() method of the Worklet interface loads the module in the given JavaScript file and adds it to the current Worklet.
dom-worklet-addmodule-dev.title: Worklet: addModule() method

worklets-worklet.name: Worklet
worklets-worklet.summary: The Worklet interface is a lightweight version of Web Workers and gives developers access to low-level parts of the rendering pipeline.
worklets-worklet.title: Worklet

dom-atob-dev.name: atob
dom-atob-dev.summary: The atob() function decodes a string of data which has been encoded using Base64 encoding. You can use the btoa() method to encode and transmit data which may otherwise cause communication problems, then transmit it and use the atob() method to decode the data again. For example, you can encode, transmit, and decode control characters such as ASCII values 0 through 31.
dom-atob-dev.title: atob() global function

dom-btoa-dev.name: btoa
dom-btoa-dev.summary: The btoa() method creates a Base64-encoded ASCII string from a binary string (i.e., a string in which each character in the string is treated as a byte of binary data).
dom-btoa-dev.title: btoa() global function

dom-clearinterval-dev.name: clearInterval
dom-clearinterval-dev.summary: The global clearInterval() method cancels a timed, repeating action which was previously established by a call to setInterval(). If the parameter provided does not identify a previously established action, this method does nothing.

ie.notes: From Internet Explorer 4 through 8, clearInterval is an Object rather than a Function. This behavior was fixed in Internet Explorer 9.

nodejs.notes: Takes a Timeout object instead of the intervalID.

dom-clearinterval-dev.title: clearInterval() global function

dom-cleartimeout-dev.name: clearTimeout
dom-cleartimeout-dev.summary: The global clearTimeout() method cancels a timeout previously established by calling setTimeout().

ie.notes: From Internet Explorer 4 through 8, clearTimeout is an Object rather than a Function. This behavior was fixed in Internet Explorer 9.

nodejs.notes: Takes a Timeout object instead of the timeoutID.

dom-cleartimeout-dev.title: clearTimeout() global function

dom-createimagebitmap-dev.name: createImageBitmap
dom-createimagebitmap-dev.summary: The createImageBitmap() method creates a bitmap from a given source, optionally cropped to contain only a portion of that source. The method exists on the global scope in both windows and workers. It accepts a variety of different image sources, and returns a Promise which resolves to an ImageBitmap.

safari.notes: See bug 182424.

dom-createimagebitmap-dev.title: createImageBitmap() global function

dom-crossoriginisolated-dev.name: crossOriginIsolated
dom-crossoriginisolated-dev.summary: The global crossOriginIsolated read-only property returns a boolean value that indicates whether the website is in a cross-origin isolation state. That state mitigates the risk of side-channel attacks and unlocks a few capabilities:
dom-crossoriginisolated-dev.title: crossOriginIsolated global property

dom-issecurecontext-dev.name: isSecureContext
dom-issecurecontext-dev.summary: The global isSecureContext read-only property returns a boolean indicating whether the current context is secure (true) or not (false).
dom-issecurecontext-dev.title: isSecureContext global property

dom-origin-dev.name: origin
dom-origin-dev.summary: The global origin read-only property returns the origin of the global scope, serialized as a string.
dom-origin-dev.title: origin global property

microtask-queuing.name: queueMicrotask
microtask-queuing.summary: The queueMicrotask() method, which is exposed on the Window or Worker interface, queues a microtask to be executed at a safe time prior to control returning to the browser's event loop.
microtask-queuing.title: queueMicrotask() global function

runtime-script-errors.name: reportError
runtime-script-errors.summary: The reportError() global method may be used to report errors to the console or global event handlers, emulating an uncaught JavaScript exception.
runtime-script-errors.title: reportError() global function

dom-setinterval-dev.name: setInterval
dom-setinterval-dev.summary: The setInterval() method, offered on the Window and Worker interfaces, repeatedly calls a function or executes a code snippet, with a fixed time delay between each call.

notes: Returns a Timeout object instead of the intervalID.
Does not support passing a code string and throws when the first parameter is not a function.

dom-setinterval-dev.title: setInterval() global function

dom-settimeout-dev.name: setTimeout
dom-settimeout-dev.summary: The global setTimeout() method sets a timer which executes a function or specified piece of code once the timer expires.

notes: Returns a Timeout object instead of the timeoutID.
Does not support passing a code string and throws when the first parameter is not a function.

dom-settimeout-dev.title: setTimeout() global function

dom-structuredclone.name: structuredClone
dom-structuredclone.summary: The global structuredClone() method creates a deep clone of a given value using the structured clone algorithm.

deno.notes: The message parameter does not support cloning Blob values.

notes: The message parameter does not support cloning Blob values.
The transfer parameter does not accept ArrayBuffer items. Passing an ArrayBuffer results in an error being thrown.

dom-structuredclone.title: structuredClone() global function

selector-active.name: active
selector-active.summary: The :active CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as a button) that is being activated by the user. When using a mouse, "activation" typically starts when the user presses down the primary mouse button.
selector-active.title: :active

selector-autofill.name: autofill
selector-autofill.summary: The :autofill CSS pseudo-class matches when an <input> element has its value autofilled by the browser. The class stops matching if the user edits the field.
selector-autofill.title: :autofill

selector-checked.name: checked
selector-checked.summary: The :checked CSS pseudo-class selector represents any radio (<input type="radio">), checkbox (<input type="checkbox">), or option (<option> in a <select>) element that is checked or toggled to an on state.

chrome.notes: On macOS, styling <option> elements has no effect.

notes: From Firefox 56, <option> elements cannot be styled.
On macOS, styling <option> elements has no effect.

firefox_android.notes: From Firefox 56, <option> elements cannot be styled.

opera.notes: On macOS, styling <option> elements has no effect.

safari.notes: Styling <option> elements has no effect.

edge_blink.notes: On macOS, styling <option> elements has no effect.

selector-checked.title: :checked

selector-default.name: default
selector-default.summary: The :default CSS pseudo-class selects form elements that are the default in a group of related elements.
selector-default.title: :default

selector-defined.name: defined
selector-defined.summary: The :defined CSS pseudo-class represents any element that has been defined. This includes any standard element built in to the browser, and custom elements that have been successfully defined (i.e. with the CustomElementRegistry.define() method).
selector-defined.title: :defined

selector-ltr.name: dir
selector-ltr.summary: The :dir() CSS pseudo-class matches elements based on the directionality of the text contained in them.
selector-ltr.title: :dir()

selector-disabled.name: disabled
selector-disabled.summary: The :disabled CSS pseudo-class represents any disabled element. An element is disabled if it can't be activated (selected, clicked on, typed into, etc.) or accept focus. The element also has an enabled state, in which it can be activated or accept focus.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer does not recognize :disabled on the <fieldset> element.

selector-disabled.title: :disabled

selector-enabled.name: enabled
selector-enabled.summary: The :enabled CSS pseudo-class represents any enabled element. An element is enabled if it can be activated (selected, clicked on, typed into, etc.) or accept focus. The element also has a disabled state, in which it can't be activated or accept focus.
selector-enabled.title: :enabled

selector-focus.name: focus
selector-focus.summary: The :focus CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as a form input) that has received focus. It is generally triggered when the user clicks or taps on an element or selects it with the keyboard's Tab key.
selector-focus.title: :focus

selector-hover.name: hover
selector-hover.summary: The :hover CSS pseudo-class matches when the user interacts with an element with a pointing device, but does not necessarily activate it. It is generally triggered when the user hovers over an element with the cursor (mouse pointer).

safari_ios.notes: As of Safari for iOS 7.1.2, tapping a clickable element causes the element to enter the :hover state. The element will remain in the :hover state until a different element has entered the :hover state.

selector-hover.title: :hover

selector-in-range.name: in-range
selector-in-range.summary: The :in-range CSS pseudo-class represents an <input> element whose current value is within the range limits specified by the min and max attributes.

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 52, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In Chrome 52, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 50, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see bug 1264157). In Firefox 50, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

opera.notes: Before Opera 39, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In Opera 39, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

opera_android.notes: Before Opera 39, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In Opera 39, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

safari.notes: In Safari, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see bug 156530). It was later changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

samsunginternet_android.notes: Before version 6.0, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In version 6.0, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

webview_android.notes: Before version 52, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In version 52, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

edge_blink.notes: Before Chrome 52, :in-range matched disabled and read-only inputs (see Chromium bug 602568). In Chrome 52, it was changed to only match enabled read-write inputs.

selector-in-range.title: :in-range

selector-indeterminate.name: indeterminate
selector-indeterminate.summary: The :indeterminate CSS pseudo-class represents any form element whose state is indeterminate, such as checkboxes which have their HTML indeterminate attribute set to true, radio buttons which are members of a group in which all radio buttons are unchecked, and indeterminate <progress> elements.
selector-indeterminate.title: :indeterminate

selector-invalid.name: invalid
selector-invalid.summary: The :invalid CSS pseudo-class represents any <form>, <fieldset>, <input> or other <form> element whose contents fail to validate.
selector-invalid.title: :invalid

selector-link.name: link
selector-link.summary: The :link CSS pseudo-class represents an element that has not yet been visited. It matches every unvisited <a> or <area> element that has an href attribute.
selector-link.title: :link

selector-optional.name: optional
selector-optional.summary: The :optional CSS pseudo-class represents any <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element that does not have the required attribute set on it.
selector-optional.title: :optional

selector-out-of-range.name: out-of-range
selector-out-of-range.summary: The :out-of-range CSS pseudo-class represents an <input> element whose current value is outside the range limits specified by the min and max attributes.
selector-out-of-range.title: :out-of-range

selector-popover-open.name: popover-open
selector-popover-open.summary: The :popover-open CSS pseudo-class represents a popover element (i.e. one with a popover attribute) that is in the showing state. You can use this to apply style to popover elements only when they are shown.
selector-popover-open.title: :popover-open

selector-read-only.name: read-only
selector-read-only.summary: The :read-only CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as input or textarea) that is not editable by the user.
selector-read-only.title: :read-only

selector-read-write.name: read-write
selector-read-write.summary: The :read-write CSS pseudo-class represents an element (such as input or textarea) that is editable by the user.
selector-read-write.title: :read-write

selector-required.name: required
selector-required.summary: The :required CSS pseudo-class represents any <input>, <select>, or <textarea> element that has the required attribute set on it.
selector-required.title: :required

selector-target.name: target
selector-target.summary: The :target CSS pseudo-class represents a unique element (the target element) with an id matching the URL's fragment.
selector-target.title: :target

selector-valid.name: valid
selector-valid.summary: The :valid CSS pseudo-class represents any <input> or other <form> element whose contents validate successfully. This allows to easily make valid fields adopt an appearance that helps the user confirm that their data is formatted properly.
selector-valid.title: :valid

selector-visited.name: visited
selector-visited.summary: The :visited CSS pseudo-class applies once the link has been visited by the user. For privacy reasons, the styles that can be modified using this selector are very limited. The :visited pseudo-class applies only <a> and <area> elements that have an href attribute.
selector-visited.title: :visited

link-type-noopener.name: noopener
link-type-noopener.summary: The noopener keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser to navigate to the target resource without granting the new browsing context access to the document that opened it  by not setting the Window.opener property on the opened window (it returns null).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 63, rel="noopener" created windows with all features disabled by default. Starting with Firefox 63, these windows have the same features enabled by default as any other window.

link-type-noopener.title: rel=noopener

link-type-noopener.name: noopener
link-type-noopener.summary: The noopener keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser to navigate to the target resource without granting the new browsing context access to the document that opened it  by not setting the Window.opener property on the opened window (it returns null).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 63, rel="noopener" created windows with all features disabled by default. Starting with Firefox 63, these windows have the same features enabled by default as any other window.

link-type-noopener.title: rel=noopener

link-type-noreferrer.name: noreferrer
link-type-noreferrer.summary: The noreferrer keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser, when navigating to the target resource, to omit the Referer header and otherwise leak no referrer information  and additionally to behave as if the noopener keyword were also specified.

ie.notes: Only supported in IE11 in later versions of Windows 10 (creators update). (Per caniuse.com.)

link-type-noreferrer.title: rel=noreferrer

link-type-noreferrer.name: noreferrer
link-type-noreferrer.summary: The noreferrer keyword for the rel attribute of the <a>, <area>, and <form> elements instructs the browser, when navigating to the target resource, to omit the Referer header and otherwise leak no referrer information  and additionally to behave as if the noopener keyword were also specified.

ie.notes: Only supported in IE11 in later versions of Windows 10 (creators update). (Per caniuse.com.)

link-type-noreferrer.title: rel=noreferrer

the-a-element.name: a
the-a-element.summary: The <a> HTML element (or anchor element), with its href attribute, creates a hyperlink to web pages, files, email addresses, locations in the same page, or anything else a URL can address.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 41, <a> without href attribute is no longer classified as interactive content: clicking it inside <label> will activate labelled content (bug 1167816).

the-a-element.title: <a>: The Anchor element

the-abbr-element.name: abbr
the-abbr-element.summary: The <abbr> HTML element represents an abbreviation or acronym.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-abbr-element.title: <abbr>: The Abbreviation element

the-address-element.name: address
the-address-element.summary: The <address> HTML element indicates that the enclosed HTML provides contact information for a person or people, or for an organization.
the-address-element.title: <address>: The Contact Address element

the-area-element.name: area
the-area-element.summary: The <area> HTML element defines an area inside an image map that has predefined clickable areas. An image map allows geometric areas on an image to be associated with hypertext links.
the-area-element.title: <area>: The Image Map Area element

the-article-element.name: article
the-article-element.summary: The <article> HTML element represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication). Examples include: a forum post, a magazine or newspaper article, or a blog entry, a product card, a user-submitted comment, an interactive widget or gadget, or any other independent item of content.
the-article-element.title: <article>: The Article Contents element

the-aside-element.name: aside
the-aside-element.summary: The <aside> HTML element represents a portion of a document whose content is only indirectly related to the document's main content. Asides are frequently presented as sidebars or call-out boxes.
the-aside-element.title: <aside>: The Aside element

the-audio-element.name: audio
the-audio-element.summary: The <audio> HTML element is used to embed sound content in documents. It may contain one or more audio sources, represented using the src attribute or the <source> element: the browser will choose the most suitable one. It can also be the destination for streamed media, using a MediaStream.

firefox.notes: For Firefox to play audio, the server must serve the file using the correct MIME type.

the-audio-element.title: <audio>: The Embed Audio element

the-b-element.name: b
the-b-element.summary: The <b> HTML element is used to draw the reader's attention to the element's contents, which are not otherwise granted special importance. This was formerly known as the Boldface element, and most browsers still draw the text in boldface. However, you should not use <b> for styling text or granting importance. If you wish to create boldface text, you should use the CSS font-weight property. If you wish to indicate an element is of special importance, you should use the <strong> element.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-b-element.title: <b>: The Bring Attention To element

the-base-element.name: base
the-base-element.summary: The <base> HTML element specifies the base URL to use for all relative URLs in a document. There can be only one <base> element in a document.

ie.notes: Before Internet Explorer 7, <base> can be positioned anywhere in the document and the nearest value of <base> is used.

the-base-element.title: <base>: The Document Base URL element

the-bdi-element.name: bdi
the-bdi-element.summary: The <bdi> HTML element tells the browser's bidirectional algorithm to treat the text it contains in isolation from its surrounding text. It's particularly useful when a website dynamically inserts some text and doesn't know the directionality of the text being inserted.
the-bdi-element.title: <bdi>: The Bidirectional Isolate element

the-bdo-element.name: bdo
the-bdo-element.summary: The <bdo> HTML element overrides the current directionality of text, so that the text within is rendered in a different direction.
the-bdo-element.title: <bdo>: The Bidirectional Text Override element

the-blockquote-element.name: blockquote
the-blockquote-element.summary: The <blockquote> HTML element indicates that the enclosed text is an extended quotation. Usually, this is rendered visually by indentation (see Notes for how to change it). A URL for the source of the quotation may be given using the cite attribute, while a text representation of the source can be given using the <cite> element.
the-blockquote-element.title: <blockquote>: The Block Quotation element

the-body-element.name: body
the-body-element.summary: The <body> HTML element represents the content of an HTML document. There can be only one <body> element in a document.
the-body-element.title: <body>: The Document Body element

the-br-element.name: br
the-br-element.summary:
The
HTML element produces a line break in text (carriage-return). It is useful for writing a poem or an address, where the division of lines is significant.
the-br-element.title: : The Line Break element

attr-fe-disabled.name: disabled
attr-fe-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-fe-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

attr-fe-disabled.name: disabled
attr-fe-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.

ie.notes: Not all form control descendants of a disabled fieldset are properly disabled in IE11; see IE bug 817488: input[type='file'] not disabled inside disabled fieldset and IE bug 962368: Can still edit input[type='text'] within fieldset[disabled].

attr-fe-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

attr-fe-disabled.name: disabled
attr-fe-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-fe-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

attr-fe-disabled.name: disabled
attr-fe-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-fe-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

attr-fe-disabled.name: disabled
attr-fe-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-fe-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

the-button-element.name: button
the-button-element.summary: The <button> HTML element is an interactive element activated by a user with a mouse, keyboard, finger, voice command, or other assistive technology. Once activated, it then performs an action, such as submitting a form or opening a dialog.
the-button-element.title: <button>: The Button element

the-canvas-element.name: canvas
the-canvas-element.summary: Use the HTML <canvas> element with either the canvas scripting API or the WebGL API to draw graphics and animations.

notes: Before Firefox 5, the canvas width and height were signed integers instead of unsigned integers.
Before Firefox 6, a <canvas> element with a zero width or height would be rendered as if it had default dimensions.

Before Firefox 12, if JavaScript is disabled, the <canvas> element was being rendered instead of showing the fallback content as per the specification. Since then, the fallback content is rendered instead.

safari.notes: Although early versions of Apple's Safari browser don't require the closing tag, the specification indicates that it is required, so you should be sure to include it for broadest compatibility. Before version 2, Safari will render the content of the fallback in addition to the canvas itself unless you use CSS tricks to mask it.

the-canvas-element.title: <canvas>: The Graphics Canvas element

the-caption-element.name: caption
the-caption-element.summary: The <caption> HTML element specifies the caption (or title) of a table.
the-caption-element.title: <caption>: The Table Caption element

the-cite-element.name: cite
the-cite-element.summary: The <cite> HTML element is used to mark up the title of a cited creative work. The reference may be in an abbreviated form according to context-appropriate conventions related to citation metadata.
the-cite-element.title: <cite>: The Citation element

the-code-element.name: code
the-code-element.summary: The <code> HTML element displays its contents styled in a fashion intended to indicate that the text is a short fragment of computer code. By default, the content text is displayed using the user agent's default monospace font.
the-code-element.title: <code>: The Inline Code element

the-col-element.name: col
the-col-element.summary: The <col> HTML element defines a column within a table and is used for defining common semantics on all common cells. It is generally found within a <colgroup> element.
the-col-element.title: <col>: The Table Column element

the-colgroup-element.name: colgroup
the-colgroup-element.summary: The <colgroup> HTML element defines a group of columns within a table.
the-colgroup-element.title: <colgroup>: The Table Column Group element

the-data-element.name: data
the-data-element.summary: The <data> HTML element links a given piece of content with a machine-readable translation. If the content is time- or date-related, the <time> element must be used.
the-data-element.title: <data>: The Data element

the-datalist-element.name: datalist
the-datalist-element.summary: The <datalist> HTML element contains a set of <option> elements that represent the permissible or recommended options available to choose from within other controls.

firefox.notes: The <datalist> element will only create a dropdown for textual types, such as text, search, url, tel, email and number. The date, time, range and color types are not supported.

firefox_android.notes: The dropdown menu containing available options does not appear. See bug 1535985.

the-datalist-element.title: <datalist>: The HTML Data List element

the-dd-element.name: dd
the-dd-element.summary: The <dd> HTML element provides the description, definition, or value for the preceding term (<dt>) in a description list (<dl>).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element was implemented using the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of HTMLElement.

the-dd-element.title: <dd>: The Description Details element

the-del-element.name: del
the-del-element.summary: The <del> HTML element represents a range of text that has been deleted from a document. This can be used when rendering "track changes" or source code diff information, for example. The <ins> element can be used for the opposite purpose: to indicate text that has been added to the document.
the-del-element.title: <del>: The Deleted Text element

the-details-element.name: details
the-details-element.summary: The <details> HTML element creates a disclosure widget in which information is visible only when the widget is toggled into an "open" state. A summary or label must be provided using the <summary> element.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 57, there was a bug meaning that <details> elements can't be made open by default using the open attribute if they have a CSS animation active on them.

firefox_android.notes: There is a bug meaning that <details> elements can't be made open by default using the open attribute if they have a CSS animation active on them.

the-details-element.title: <details>: The Details disclosure element

the-dfn-element.name: dfn
the-dfn-element.summary:
The HTML element is used to indicate the term being defined within the context of a definition phrase or sentence. The ancestor

element, the

/
pairing, or the nearest
ancestor of the element, is considered to be the definition of the term.
the-dfn-element.title: <dfn>: The Definition element

the-dialog-element.name: dialog
the-dialog-element.summary: The <dialog> HTML element represents a dialog box or other interactive component, such as a dismissible alert, inspector, or subwindow.
the-dialog-element.title: <dialog>: The Dialog element

the-div-element.name: div
the-div-element.summary: The <div> HTML element is the generic container for flow content. It has no effect on the content or layout until styled in some way using CSS (e.g. styling is directly applied to it, or some kind of layout model like Flexbox is applied to its parent element).
the-div-element.title: <div>: The Content Division element

the-dl-element.name: dl
the-dl-element.summary: The <dl> HTML element represents a description list. The element encloses a list of groups of terms (specified using the <dt> element) and descriptions (provided by <dd> elements). Common uses for this element are to implement a glossary or to display metadata (a list of key-value pairs).
the-dl-element.title: <dl>: The Description List element

the-dt-element.name: dt
the-dt-element.summary: The <dt> HTML element specifies a term in a description or definition list, and as such must be used inside a <dl> element. It is usually followed by a <dd> element; however, multiple <dt> elements in a row indicate several terms that are all defined by the immediate next <dd> element.
the-dt-element.title: <dt>: The Description Term element

the-em-element.name: em
the-em-element.summary: The <em> HTML element marks text that has stress emphasis. The <em> element can be nested, with each level of nesting indicating a greater degree of emphasis.
the-em-element.title: <em>: The Emphasis element

the-embed-element.name: embed
the-embed-element.summary: The <embed> HTML element embeds external content at the specified point in the document. This content is provided by an external application or other source of interactive content such as a browser plug-in.
the-embed-element.title: <embed>: The Embed External Content element

the-fieldset-element.name: fieldset
the-fieldset-element.summary: The <fieldset> HTML element is used to group several controls as well as labels (<label>) within a web form.

chrome.notes: Before version 86, this element did not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

edge_blink.notes: Before version 86, this element did not support flexbox and grid layouts within this element. See bug 262679.

the-fieldset-element.title: <fieldset>: The Field Set element

the-figcaption-element.name: figcaption
the-figcaption-element.summary: The <figcaption> HTML element represents a caption or legend describing the rest of the contents of its parent <figure> element.
the-figcaption-element.title: <figcaption>: The Figure Caption element

the-figure-element.name: figure
the-figure-element.summary: The <figure> HTML element represents self-contained content, potentially with an optional caption, which is specified using the <figcaption> element. The figure, its caption, and its contents are referenced as a single unit.
the-figure-element.title: <figure>: The Figure with Optional Caption element

the-footer-element.name: footer
the-footer-element.summary: The <footer> HTML element represents a footer for its nearest ancestor sectioning content or sectioning root element. A <footer> typically contains information about the author of the section, copyright data or links to related documents.
the-footer-element.title: <footer>

the-form-element.name: form
the-form-element.summary: The <form> HTML element represents a document section containing interactive controls for submitting information.
the-form-element.title: <form>: The Form element

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h1
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h2
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h3
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h4
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h5
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.name: h6
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.summary: The <h1> to <h6> HTML elements represent six levels of section headings. <h1> is the highest section level and <h6> is the lowest.
the-h1,-h2,-h3,-h4,-h5,-and-h6-elements.title: <h1><h6>: The HTML Section Heading elements

the-head-element.name: head
the-head-element.summary: The <head> HTML element contains machine-readable information (metadata) about the document, like its title, scripts, and style sheets.
the-head-element.title: <head>: The Document Metadata (Header) element

the-header-element.name: header
the-header-element.summary: The <header> HTML element represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also a logo, a search form, an author name, and other elements.
the-header-element.title: <header>

the-hgroup-element.name: hgroup
the-hgroup-element.summary:
The
HTML element represents a heading and related content. It groups a single

element with one or more

.
the-hgroup-element.title: <hgroup>

the-hr-element.name: hr
the-hr-element.summary: The <hr> HTML element represents a thematic break between paragraph-level elements: for example, a change of scene in a story, or a shift of topic within a section.
the-hr-element.title: <hr>: The Thematic Break (Horizontal Rule) element

the-html-element.name: html
the-html-element.summary: The <html> HTML element represents the root (top-level element) of an HTML document, so it is also referred to as the root element. All other elements must be descendants of this element.
the-html-element.title: <html>: The HTML Document / Root element

the-i-element.name: i
the-i-element.summary: The <i> HTML element represents a range of text that is set off from the normal text for some reason, such as idiomatic text, technical terms, taxonomical designations, among others. Historically, these have been presented using italicized type, which is the original source of the <i> naming of this element.
the-i-element.title: <i>: The Idiomatic Text element

the-iframe-element.name: iframe
the-iframe-element.summary: The <iframe> HTML element represents a nested browsing context, embedding another HTML page into the current one.

firefox.notes: The resize CSS property doesn't have any effect on this element due to bug 680823.

safari.notes: Safari has a bug that prevents iframes from loading if the iframe element was hidden when added to the page. iframeElement.src = iframeElement.src should cause it to load the iframe.

the-iframe-element.title: <iframe>: The Inline Frame element

lazy-loading-attributes.name: loading
lazy-loading-attributes.summary: Lazy loading is a strategy to identify resources as non-blocking (non-critical) and load these only when needed. It's a way to shorten the length of the critical rendering path, which translates into reduced page load times.
lazy-loading-attributes.title: Lazy loading

the-img-element.name: img
the-img-element.summary: The HTML element embeds an image into the document.
the-img-element.title: : The Image Embed element

button-state-(type=button).name: type_button
button-state-(type=button).summary: <input> elements of type button are rendered as simple push buttons, which can be programmed to control custom functionality anywhere on a webpage as required when assigned an event handler function (typically for the click event).
button-state-(type=button).title: <input type="button">

checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).name: type_checkbox
checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).summary: <input> elements of type checkbox are rendered by default as boxes that are checked (ticked) when activated, like you might see in an official government paper form. The exact appearance depends upon the operating system configuration under which the browser is running. Generally this is a square but it may have rounded corners. A checkbox allows you to select single values for submission in a form (or not).
checkbox-state-(type=checkbox).title: <input type="checkbox">

color-state-(type=color).name: type_color
color-state-(type=color).summary: <input> elements of type color provide a user interface element that lets a user specify a color, either by using a visual color picker interface or by entering the color into a text field in #rrggbb hexadecimal format.

firefox_android.notes: Firefox for Android doesn't allow the user to choose a custom color, only one of the predefined ones.

color-state-(type=color).title: <input type="color">

date-state-(type=date).name: type_date
date-state-(type=date).summary: <input> elements of type="date" create input fields that let the user enter a date, either with a textbox that validates the input or a special date picker interface.
date-state-(type=date).title: <input type="date">

local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.name: type_datetime-local
local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.summary: <input> elements of type datetime-local create input controls that let the user easily enter both a date and a time, including the year, month, and day as well as the time in hours and minutes.
local-date-and-time-state-(type=datetime.title: <input type="datetime-local">

email-state-(type=email).name: type_email
email-state-(type=email).summary: <input> elements of type email are used to let the user enter and edit an email address, or, if the multiple attribute is specified, a list of email addresses.

notes: Doesn't do validation, but instead offers a custom 'email' keyboard, which is designed to make entering email addresses easier.
The custom 'email' keyboard does not provide a comma key, so users cannot enter multiple email addresses.
Automatically applies a default style of opacity: 0.4 to disable textual <input> elements, including those of type 'email'. Other major browsers don't currently share this particular default style.

email-state-(type=email).title: <input type="email">

file-upload-state-(type=file).name: type_file
file-upload-state-(type=file).summary: <input> elements with type="file" let the user choose one or more files from their device storage. Once chosen, the files can be uploaded to a server using form submission, or manipulated using JavaScript code and the File API.

firefox.notes: You can set as well as get the value of HTMLInputElement.files in all modern browsers; this was most recently added to Firefox, in version 57 (see bug 1384030).

file-upload-state-(type=file).title: <input type="file">

hidden-state-(type=hidden).name: type_hidden
hidden-state-(type=hidden).summary: <input> elements of type hidden let web developers include data that cannot be seen or modified by users when a form is submitted. For example, the ID of the content that is currently being ordered or edited, or a unique security token. Hidden inputs are completely invisible in the rendered page, and there is no way to make it visible in the page's content.
hidden-state-(type=hidden).title: <input type="hidden">

image-button-state-(type=image).name: type_image
image-button-state-(type=image).summary: <input> elements of type image are used to create graphical submit buttons, i.e. submit buttons that take the form of an image rather than text.
image-button-state-(type=image).title: <input type="image">

month-state-(type=month).name: type_month
month-state-(type=month).summary: <input> elements of type month create input fields that let the user enter a month and year allowing a month and year to be easily entered. The value is a string whose value is in the format "YYYY-MM", where YYYY is the four-digit year and MM is the month number.

firefox.notes: See bug 888320.

safari.notes: The input type is recognized, but there is no month-specific control. See bug 200416.

month-state-(type=month).title: <input type="month">

number-state-(type=number).name: type_number
number-state-(type=number).summary: <input> elements of type number are used to let the user enter a number. They include built-in validation to reject non-numerical entries.
number-state-(type=number).title: <input type="number">

password-state-(type=password).name: type_password
password-state-(type=password).summary: <input> elements of type password provide a way for the user to securely enter a password.
password-state-(type=password).title: <input type="password">

radio-button-state-(type=radio).name: type_radio
radio-button-state-(type=radio).summary: <input> elements of type radio are generally used in radio groupscollections of radio buttons describing a set of related options.
radio-button-state-(type=radio).title: <input type="radio">

range-state-(type=range).name: type_range
range-state-(type=range).summary: <input> elements of type range let the user specify a numeric value which must be no less than a given value, and no more than another given value. The precise value, however, is not considered important. This is typically represented using a slider or dial control rather than a text entry box like the number input type.

webview_android.notes: Pre-Chromium Android WebView recognizes the range type, but doesn't implement a range-specific control.

range-state-(type=range).title: <input type="range">

reset-button-state-(type=reset).name: type_reset
reset-button-state-(type=reset).summary: <input> elements of type reset are rendered as buttons, with a default click event handler that resets all inputs in the form to their initial values.

firefox.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a <button> across page loads. Use the autocomplete attribute to control this feature.

reset-button-state-(type=reset).title: <input type="reset">

text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.name: type_search
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.summary: <input> elements of type search are text fields designed for the user to enter search queries into. These are functionally identical to text inputs, but may be styled differently by the user agent.
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.title: <input type="search">

text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.name: type_text
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.summary: <input> elements of type text create basic single-line text fields.
text-(type=text)-state-and-search-state-.title: <input type="text">

submit-button-state-(type=submit).name: type_submit
submit-button-state-(type=submit).summary: <input> elements of type submit are rendered as buttons. When the click event occurs (typically because the user clicked the button), the user agent attempts to submit the form to the server.

firefox.notes: Unlike other browsers, Firefox by default persists the dynamic disabled state of a <button> across page loads. Use the autocomplete attribute to control this feature.

submit-button-state-(type=submit).title: <input type="submit">

telephone-state-(type=tel).name: type_tel
telephone-state-(type=tel).summary: <input> elements of type tel are used to let the user enter and edit a telephone number. Unlike <input type="email"> and <input type="url">, the input value is not automatically validated to a particular format before the form can be submitted, because formats for telephone numbers vary so much around the world.

chrome.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

safari.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

edge_blink.notes: The field type doesn't demonstrate any special behavior.

telephone-state-(type=tel).title: <input type="tel">

time-state-(type=time).name: type_time
time-state-(type=time).summary: <input> elements of type time create input fields designed to let the user easily enter a time (hours and minutes, and optionally seconds).
time-state-(type=time).title: <input type="time">

url-state-(type=url).name: type_url
url-state-(type=url).summary: <input> elements of type url are used to let the user enter and edit a URL.
url-state-(type=url).title: <input type="url">

week-state-(type=week).name: type_week
week-state-(type=week).summary: <input> elements of type week create input fields allowing easy entry of a year plus the ISO 8601 week number during that year (i.e., week 1 to 52 or 53).

firefox.notes: See bug 888320.

safari.notes: See bug 200416.

week-state-(type=week).title: <input type="week">

attr-input-accept.name: accept
attr-input-accept.summary: The accept attribute takes as its value a comma-separated list of one or more file types, or unique file type specifiers, describing which file types to allow.
attr-input-accept.title: HTML attribute: accept

attr-input-accept.name: attr-input-accept#attr-accept
attr-input-accept.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.
attr-input-accept.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

the-min-and-max-attributes.name: max
the-min-and-max-attributes.summary: The max attribute defines the maximum value that is acceptable and valid for the input containing the attribute. If the value of the element is greater than this, the element fails validation. This value must be greater than or equal to the value of the min attribute. If the max attribute is present but is not specified or is invalid, no max value is applied. If the max attribute is valid and a non-empty value is greater than the maximum allowed by the max attribute, constraint validation will prevent form submission.
the-min-and-max-attributes.title: HTML attribute: max

the-min-and-max-attributes.name: min
the-min-and-max-attributes.summary: The min attribute defines the minimum value that is acceptable and valid for the input containing the attribute. If the value of the element is less than this, the element fails validation. This value must be less than or equal to the value of the max attribute.
the-min-and-max-attributes.title: HTML attribute: min

the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.name: maxlength
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.summary: The maxlength attribute defines the maximum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.title: HTML attribute: maxlength

the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.name: minlength
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.summary: The minlength attribute defines the minimum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.title: HTML attribute: minlength

the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.name: maxlength
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.summary: The maxlength attribute defines the maximum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.title: HTML attribute: maxlength

the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.name: minlength
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.summary: The minlength attribute defines the minimum string length that the user can enter into an <input> or <textarea>. The attribute must have an integer value of 0 or higher.
the-maxlength-and-minlength-attributes.title: HTML attribute: minlength

attr-input-multiple.name: multiple
attr-input-multiple.summary: The Boolean multiple attribute, if set, means the form control accepts one or more values. Valid for the email and file input types and the <select>, the manner by which the user opts for multiple values depends on the form control.
attr-input-multiple.title: HTML attribute: multiple

attr-input-multiple.name: input#attr-multiple

attr-fe-name.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

attr-input-pattern.name: pattern
attr-input-pattern.summary: The pattern attribute specifies a regular expression the form control's value should match. If a non-null value doesn't conform to the constraints set by the pattern value, the ValidityState object's read-only patternMismatch property will be true.
attr-input-pattern.title: HTML attribute: pattern

the-readonly-attribute.name: readonly
the-readonly-attribute.summary: The Boolean readonly attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, meaning the user can not edit the control.
the-readonly-attribute.title: HTML attribute: readonly
