the-readonly-attribute.title: HTML attribute: readonly

attr-input-src.name: src
attr-input-src.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.
attr-input-src.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

attr-input-step.name: step
attr-input-step.summary: The step attribute is a number that specifies the granularity that the value must adhere to or the keyword any. It is valid for the numeric input types, including the date, month, week, time, datetime-local, number and range types.
attr-input-step.title: HTML attribute: step

the-input-element.name: input
the-input-element.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 89, manipulating the content of <input> elements using Document.execCommand() commands requires workarounds (see bug 1220696).

the-input-element.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

the-input-element.name: input
the-input-element.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.
the-input-element.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

the-ins-element.name: ins
the-ins-element.summary: The <ins> HTML element represents a range of text that has been added to a document. You can use the <del> element to similarly represent a range of text that has been deleted from the document.
the-ins-element.title: <ins>

the-kbd-element.name: kbd
the-kbd-element.summary: The <kbd> HTML element represents a span of inline text denoting textual user input from a keyboard, voice input, or any other text entry device. By convention, the user agent defaults to rendering the contents of a <kbd> element using its default monospace font, although this is not mandated by the HTML standard.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, creating a <kbd> element incorrectly resulted in an HTMLSpanElement object, instead of the expected HTMLElement.

the-kbd-element.title: <kbd>: The Keyboard Input element

attr-label-for.name: for
attr-label-for.summary: The for attribute is an allowed attribute for <label> and <output>. When used on a <label> element it indicates the form element that this label describes. When used on an <output> element it allows for an explicit relationship between the elements that represent values which are used in the output.
attr-label-for.title: HTML attribute: for

the-label-element.name: label
the-label-element.summary: The <label> HTML element represents a caption for an item in a user interface.
the-label-element.title: <label>: The Label element

the-legend-element.name: legend
the-legend-element.summary: The <legend> HTML element represents a caption for the content of its parent <fieldset>.
the-legend-element.title: <legend>: The Field Set Legend element

the-li-element.name: li
the-li-element.summary: The <li> HTML element is used to represent an item in a list. It must be contained in a parent element: an ordered list (<ol>), an unordered list (<ul>), or a menu (<menu>). In menus and unordered lists, list items are usually displayed using bullet points. In ordered lists, they are usually displayed with an ascending counter on the left, such as a number or letter.
the-li-element.title: <li>: The List Item element

attr-link-integrity.name: integrity
attr-link-integrity.summary: Subresource Integrity (SRI) is a security feature that enables browsers to verify that resources they fetch (for example, from a CDN) are delivered without unexpected manipulation. It works by allowing you to provide a cryptographic hash that a fetched resource must match.
attr-link-integrity.title: Subresource Integrity

rel-alternate.name: alternate_stylesheet
rel-alternate.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
rel-alternate.title: Alternative style sheets

the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.name: alternate_stylesheet
the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
the-link-is-an-alternative-stylesheet.title: Alternative style sheets

attr-style-title.name: alternate_stylesheet
attr-style-title.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
attr-style-title.title: Alternative style sheets

attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.name: alternate_stylesheet
attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.summary: Specifying alternative style sheets in a web page provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page, based on their needs or preferences.
attr-meta-http-equiv-default-style.title: Alternative style sheets

link-type-dns-prefetch.name: dns-prefetch
link-type-dns-prefetch.summary: The dns-prefetch keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need resources from the target resource's origin, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively performing DNS resolution for that origin.
link-type-dns-prefetch.title: rel=dns-prefetch

link-type-manifest.name: manifest
link-type-manifest.summary: The manifest keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element indicates that the target resource is a Web app manifest.
link-type-manifest.title: rel=manifest

link-type-modulepreload.name: modulepreload
link-type-modulepreload.summary: The modulepreload keyword, for the rel attribute of the <link> element, provides a declarative way to preemptively fetch a module script, parse and compile it, and store it in the document's module map for later execution.
link-type-modulepreload.title: rel=modulepreload

link-type-preconnect.name: preconnect
link-type-preconnect.summary: The preconnect keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need resources from the target resource's origin, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively initiating a connection to that origin. Preconnecting speeds up future loads from a given origin by preemptively performing part or all of the handshake (DNS+TCP for HTTP, and DNS+TCP+TLS for HTTPS origins).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 41, it doesn't obey the crossorigin attribute.

link-type-preconnect.title: rel=preconnect

link-type-prefetch.name: prefetch
link-type-prefetch.summary: The prefetch keyword for the rel attribute of the <link> element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need the target resource for future navigations, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively fetching and caching the resource.
link-type-prefetch.title: rel=prefetch

link-type-preload.name: preload
link-type-preload.summary: The preload value of the <link> element's rel attribute lets you declare fetch requests in the HTML's <head>, specifying resources that your page will need very soon, which you want to start loading early in the page lifecycle, before browsers' main rendering machinery kicks in. This ensures they are available earlier and are less likely to block the page's render, improving performance. Even though the name contains the term load, it doesn't load and execute the script but only schedules it to be downloaded and cached with a higher priority.

chrome.notes: Doesnt support as="audio", as="audioworklet", as="document", as="embed", as="manifest", as="object", as="paintworklet", as="report", as="sharedworker", as="video", as="worker", or as="xslt".

firefox.notes: Disabled due to various web compatibility issues (e.g. bug 1405761).

edge_blink.notes: Doesnt support as="audio", as="audioworklet", as="document", as="embed", as="manifest", as="object", as="paintworklet", as="report", as="sharedworker", as="video", as="worker", or as="xslt".

link-type-preload.title: rel=preload

linkTypes.name: rel
linkTypes.summary: The rel attribute defines the relationship between a linked resource and the current document. Valid on <link>, <a>, <area>, and <form>, the supported values depend on the element on which the attribute is found.
linkTypes.title: HTML attribute: rel

linkTypes.name: Link_types
linkTypes.summary: The rel attribute defines the relationship between a linked resource and the current document. Valid on <link>, <a>, <area>, and <form>, the supported values depend on the element on which the attribute is found.
linkTypes.title: HTML attribute: rel

the-link-element.name: link
the-link-element.summary: The <link> HTML element specifies relationships between the current document and an external resource. This element is most commonly used to link to stylesheets, but is also used to establish site icons (both "favicon" style icons and icons for the home screen and apps on mobile devices) among other things.
the-link-element.title: <link>: The External Resource Link element

the-main-element.name: main
the-main-element.summary: The <main> HTML element represents the dominant content of the <body> of a document. The main content area consists of content that is directly related to or expands upon the central topic of a document, or the central functionality of an application.
the-main-element.title: <main>

the-map-element.name: map
the-map-element.summary: The <map> HTML element is used with <area> elements to define an image map (a clickable link area).

notes: Before Firefox 5, in Quirks Mode, empty maps were no longer skipped over in favor of non-empty ones when matching.

Before Firefox 17, the default styling of the <map> HTML element was display: block;. This is now display: inline; and matches the behavior of the other browsers. It was already the case in Quirks Mode.

the-map-element.title: <map>: The Image Map element

the-mark-element.name: mark
the-mark-element.summary: The <mark> HTML element represents text which is marked or highlighted for reference or notation purposes due to the marked passage's relevance in the enclosing context.
the-mark-element.title: <mark>: The Mark Text element

the-menu-element.name: menu
the-menu-element.summary: The <menu> HTML element is described in the HTML specification as a semantic alternative to <ul>, but treated by browsers (and exposed through the accessibility tree) as no different than <ul>. It represents an unordered list of items (which are represented by <li> elements).
the-menu-element.title: <menu>: The Menu element

meta-theme-color.name: theme-color
meta-theme-color.summary: The theme-color value for the name attribute of the <meta> element indicates a suggested color that user agents should use to customize the display of the page or of the surrounding user interface. If specified, the content attribute must contain a valid CSS <color>.

chrome.notes: Chrome uses the color only on installed progressive web apps.
Chrome reports support, but does not actually use the color anywhere.

chrome_android.notes: Chrome for Android does not use the color on devices with native dark mode enabled.

edge_blink.notes: Chrome uses the color only on installed progressive web apps.
Chrome reports support, but does not actually use the color anywhere.

meta-theme-color.title: theme-color

standard-metadata-names.name: name
standard-metadata-names.summary: The <meta> element can be used to provide document metadata in terms of name-value pairs, with the name attribute giving the metadata name, and the content attribute giving the value.
standard-metadata-names.title: Standard metadata names

the-meta-element.name: meta
the-meta-element.summary: The <meta> HTML element represents metadata that cannot be represented by other HTML meta-related elements, like <base>, <link>, <script>, <style> or <title>.
the-meta-element.title: <meta>: The metadata element

attr-meter-max.name: max
attr-meter-max.summary: The max attribute defines the maximum value that is acceptable and valid for the input containing the attribute. If the value of the element is greater than this, the element fails validation. This value must be greater than or equal to the value of the min attribute. If the max attribute is present but is not specified or is invalid, no max value is applied. If the max attribute is valid and a non-empty value is greater than the maximum allowed by the max attribute, constraint validation will prevent form submission.
attr-meter-max.title: HTML attribute: max

attr-meter-max.name: min
attr-meter-max.summary: The min attribute defines the minimum value that is acceptable and valid for the input containing the attribute. If the value of the element is less than this, the element fails validation. This value must be less than or equal to the value of the max attribute.
attr-meter-max.title: HTML attribute: min

the-meter-element.name: meter
the-meter-element.summary: The <meter> HTML element represents either a scalar value within a known range or a fractional value.
the-meter-element.title: <meter>: The HTML Meter element

the-nav-element.name: nav
the-nav-element.summary: The <nav> HTML element represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents. Common examples of navigation sections are menus, tables of contents, and indexes.
the-nav-element.title: <nav>: The Navigation Section element

the-noscript-element.name: noscript
the-noscript-element.summary: The <noscript> HTML element defines a section of HTML to be inserted if a script type on the page is unsupported or if scripting is currently turned off in the browser.
the-noscript-element.title: <noscript>: The Noscript element

the-object-element.name: object
the-object-element.summary: The <object> HTML element represents an external resource, which can be treated as an image, a nested browsing context, or a resource to be handled by a plugin.
the-object-element.title: <object>: The External Object element

the-ol-element.name: ol
the-ol-element.summary: The <ol> HTML element represents an ordered list of items  typically rendered as a numbered list.
the-ol-element.title: <ol>: The Ordered List element

attr-optgroup-disabled.name: disabled
attr-optgroup-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-optgroup-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

the-optgroup-element.name: optgroup
the-optgroup-element.summary: The <optgroup> HTML element creates a grouping of options within a <select> element.
the-optgroup-element.title: <optgroup>: The Option Group element

attr-option-disabled.name: disabled
attr-option-disabled.summary: The Boolean disabled attribute, when present, makes the element not mutable, focusable, or even submitted with the form. The user can neither edit nor focus on the control, nor its form control descendants.
attr-option-disabled.title: HTML attribute: disabled

the-option-element.name: option
the-option-element.summary: The <option> HTML element is used to define an item contained in a <select>, an <optgroup>, or a <datalist> element. As such, <option> can represent menu items in popups and other lists of items in an HTML document.
the-option-element.title: <option>: The HTML Option element

attr-output-for.name: for
attr-output-for.summary: The for attribute is an allowed attribute for <label> and <output>. When used on a <label> element it indicates the form element that this label describes. When used on an <output> element it allows for an explicit relationship between the elements that represent values which are used in the output.
attr-output-for.title: HTML attribute: for

the-output-element.name: output
the-output-element.summary: The <output> HTML element is a container element into which a site or app can inject the results of a calculation or the outcome of a user action.
the-output-element.title: <output>: The Output element

the-p-element.name: p
the-p-element.summary:
The

HTML element represents a paragraph. Paragraphs are usually represented in visual media as blocks of text separated from adjacent blocks by blank lines and/or first-line indentation, but HTML paragraphs can be any structural grouping of related content, such as images or form fields.
the-p-element.title: : The Paragraph element

the-picture-element.name: picture
the-picture-element.summary: The HTML element contains zero or more elements and one element to offer alternative versions of an image for different display/device scenarios.
the-picture-element.title: <picture>: The Picture element

the-pre-element.name: pre
the-pre-element.summary: The <pre> HTML element represents preformatted text which is to be presented exactly as written in the HTML file. The text is typically rendered using a non-proportional, or monospaced, font. Whitespace inside this element is displayed as written.
the-pre-element.title: <pre>: The Preformatted Text element

attr-progress-max.name: max
attr-progress-max.summary: The max attribute defines the maximum value that is acceptable and valid for the input containing the attribute. If the value of the element is greater than this, the element fails validation. This value must be greater than or equal to the value of the min attribute. If the max attribute is present but is not specified or is invalid, no max value is applied. If the max attribute is valid and a non-empty value is greater than the maximum allowed by the max attribute, constraint validation will prevent form submission.
attr-progress-max.title: HTML attribute: max

the-progress-element.name: progress
the-progress-element.summary: The <progress> HTML element displays an indicator showing the completion progress of a task, typically displayed as a progress bar.

notes: Before Firefox 14, the <progress> element was incorrectly classified as a form element, and therefore had a form attribute. This has been fixed.
Firefox provides the ::-moz-progress-bar pseudo-element, which lets you style the part of the interior of the progress bar representing the amount of work completed so far.

safari_ios.notes: Safari on iOS does not support indeterminate progress bars (they are rendered like 0%-completed progress bars).

the-progress-element.title: <progress>: The Progress Indicator element

the-q-element.name: q
the-q-element.summary: The <q> HTML element indicates that the enclosed text is a short inline quotation. Most modern browsers implement this by surrounding the text in quotation marks. This element is intended for short quotations that don't require paragraph breaks; for long quotations use the <blockquote> element.
the-q-element.title: <q>: The Inline Quotation element

the-rp-element.name: rp
the-rp-element.summary: The <rp> HTML element is used to provide fall-back parentheses for browsers that do not support display of ruby annotations using the <ruby> element. One <rp> element should enclose each of the opening and closing parentheses that wrap the <rt> element that contains the annotation's text.
the-rp-element.title: <rp>: The Ruby Fallback Parenthesis element

the-rt-element.name: rt
the-rt-element.summary: The <rt> HTML element specifies the ruby text component of a ruby annotation, which is used to provide pronunciation, translation, or transliteration information for East Asian typography. The <rt> element must always be contained within a <ruby> element.
the-rt-element.title: <rt>: The Ruby Text element

the-ruby-element.name: ruby
the-ruby-element.summary: The <ruby> HTML element represents small annotations that are rendered above, below, or next to base text, usually used for showing the pronunciation of East Asian characters. It can also be used for annotating other kinds of text, but this usage is less common.
the-ruby-element.title: <ruby>: The Ruby Annotation element

the-s-element.name: s
the-s-element.summary: The <s> HTML element renders text with a strikethrough, or a line through it. Use the <s> element to represent things that are no longer relevant or no longer accurate. However, <s> is not appropriate when indicating document edits; for that, use the <del> and <ins> elements, as appropriate.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-s-element.title: <s>: The Strikethrough element

the-samp-element.name: samp
the-samp-element.summary: The <samp> HTML element is used to enclose inline text which represents sample (or quoted) output from a computer program. Its contents are typically rendered using the browser's default monospaced font (such as Courier or Lucida Console).
the-samp-element.title: <samp>: The Sample Output element

the-script-element.name: script
the-script-element.summary: The <script> HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The <script> element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 4, inserting <script> elements that have been created by calling document.createElement("script") no longer enforces execution in insertion order. This change lets Firefox properly abide by the specification. To make script-inserted external scripts execute in their insertion order, set .async=false on them.

the-script-element.title: <script>: The Script element

the-search-element.name: search
the-search-element.summary: The <search> HTML element is a container representing the parts of the document or application with form controls or other content related to performing a search or filtering operation. The <search> element semantically identifies the purpose of the element's contents as having search or filtering capabilities. The search or filtering functionality can be for the website or application, the current web page or document, or the entire Internet or subsection thereof.

chrome.notes: See bug 1294294 and bug 1277435.

firefox.notes: See bug 1824121.

safari.notes: See bug 254327.

edge_blink.notes: See bug 1294294 and bug 1277435.

the-search-element.title: <search>: The generic search element

the-section-element.name: section
the-section-element.summary: The <section> HTML element represents a generic standalone section of a document, which doesn't have a more specific semantic element to represent it. Sections should always have a heading, with very few exceptions.
the-section-element.title: <section>: The Generic Section element

attr-select-multiple.name: multiple
attr-select-multiple.summary: The Boolean multiple attribute, if set, means the form control accepts one or more values. Valid for the email and file input types and the <select>, the manner by which the user opts for multiple values depends on the form control.
attr-select-multiple.title: HTML attribute: multiple

attr-select-required.name: required
attr-select-required.summary: The Boolean required attribute, if present, indicates that the user must specify a value for the input before the owning form can be submitted.
attr-select-required.title: HTML attribute: required

attr-select-size.name: size
attr-select-size.summary: The size attribute defines the width of the <input> and the height of the <select> element. For the input, if the type attribute is text or password then it's the number of characters. This must be an integer value of 0 or higher. If no size is specified, or an invalid value is specified, the input has no size declared, and the form control will be the default width based on the user agent. If CSS targets the element with properties impacting the width, CSS takes precedence.
attr-select-size.title: HTML attribute: size

the-select-element.name: select
the-select-element.summary: The <select> HTML element represents a control that provides a menu of options.

chrome.notes: border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

firefox.notes: Historically, Firefox has allowed keyboard and mouse events to bubble up from the <option> element to the parent <select> element, although this behavior is inconsistent across many browsers. For better Web compatibility (and for technical reasons), when Firefox is in multi-process mode the <select> element is displayed as a drop-down list. The behavior is unchanged if the <select> is presented inline and it has either the multiple attribute defined or a size attribute set to more than 1. Rather than watching <option> elements for events, you should watch for change events on <select>. See bug 1090602 for details.

firefox_android.notes: Firefox for Android, by default, sets a background-image gradient on all <select multiple> elements. This can be disabled using background-image: none.

safari.notes: border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

notes: In the Browser app for Android 4.1 (and possibly later versions), there is a bug where the menu indicator triangle on the side of a <select> will not be displayed if a background, border, or border-radius style is applied to the <select>.
border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

edge_blink.notes: border-radius on <select> elements is ignored unless -webkit-appearance is overridden to an appropriate value.

the-select-element.title: <select>: The HTML Select element

the-slot-element.name: slot
the-slot-element.summary: The <slot> HTML elementpart of the Web Components technology suiteis a placeholder inside a web component that you can fill with your own markup, which lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
the-slot-element.title: <slot>: The Web Component Slot element

the-small-element.name: small
the-small-element.summary: The <small> HTML element represents side-comments and small print, like copyright and legal text, independent of its styled presentation. By default, it renders text within it one font-size smaller, such as from small to x-small.
the-small-element.title: <small>: the side comment element

the-source-element.name: source
the-source-element.summary: The <source> HTML element specifies multiple media resources for the <picture>, the <audio> element, or the <video> element. It is a void element, meaning that it has no content and does not have a closing tag. It is commonly used to offer the same media content in multiple file formats in order to provide compatibility with a broad range of browsers given their differing support for image file formats and media file formats.

firefox.notes: Until Firefox 15, Firefox picked the first source element that has a type matching the MIME-type of a supported media format; see bug 449363 for details.

the-source-element.title: <source>: The Media or Image Source element

the-span-element.name: span
the-span-element.summary: The <span> HTML element is a generic inline container for phrasing content, which does not inherently represent anything. It can be used to group elements for styling purposes (using the class or id attributes), or because they share attribute values, such as lang. It should be used only when no other semantic element is appropriate. <span> is very much like a <div> element, but <div> is a block-level element whereas a <span> is an inline-level element.
the-span-element.title: <span>: The Content Span element

the-strong-element.name: strong
the-strong-element.summary: The <strong> HTML element indicates that its contents have strong importance, seriousness, or urgency. Browsers typically render the contents in bold type.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, creating a <strong> element incorrectly resulted in an HTMLSpanElement object, instead of the expected HTMLElement.

the-strong-element.title: <strong>: The Strong Importance element

the-style-element.name: style
the-style-element.summary: The <style> HTML element contains style information for a document, or part of a document. It contains CSS, which is applied to the contents of the document containing the <style> element.
the-style-element.title: <style>: The Style Information element

the-sub-and-sup-elements.name: sub
the-sub-and-sup-elements.summary: The <sub> HTML element specifies inline text which should be displayed as subscript for solely typographical reasons. Subscripts are typically rendered with a lowered baseline using smaller text.
the-sub-and-sup-elements.title: <sub>: The Subscript element

the-sub-and-sup-elements.name: sup
the-sub-and-sup-elements.summary: The <sup> HTML element specifies inline text which is to be displayed as superscript for solely typographical reasons. Superscripts are usually rendered with a raised baseline using smaller text.
the-sub-and-sup-elements.title: <sup>: The Superscript element

the-summary-element.name: summary
the-summary-element.summary: The <summary> HTML element specifies a summary, caption, or legend for a <details> element's disclosure box. Clicking the <summary> element toggles the state of the parent <details> element open and closed.
the-summary-element.title: <summary>: The Disclosure Summary element

the-table-element.name: table
the-table-element.summary: The <table> HTML element represents tabular data  that is, information presented in a two-dimensional table comprised of rows and columns of cells containing data.
the-table-element.title: <table>: The Table element

the-tbody-element.name: tbody
the-tbody-element.summary: The <tbody> HTML element encapsulates a set of table rows (<tr> elements), indicating that they comprise the body of the table (<table>).
the-tbody-element.title: <tbody>: The Table Body element

the-td-element.name: td
the-td-element.summary: The <td> HTML element defines a cell of a table that contains data. It participates in the table model.
the-td-element.title: <td>: The Table Data Cell element

the-template-element.name: template
the-template-element.summary: The <template> HTML element is a mechanism for holding HTML that is not to be rendered immediately when a page is loaded but may be instantiated subsequently during runtime using JavaScript.
the-template-element.title: <template>: The Content Template element

the-textarea-element.name: textarea
the-textarea-element.summary: The <textarea> HTML element represents a multi-line plain-text editing control, useful when you want to allow users to enter a sizeable amount of free-form text, for example a comment on a review or feedback form.

notes: Before Firefox 6, when a <textarea> was focused, the insertion point was placed at the end of the text by default. Other major browsers place the insertion point at the beginning of the text.
A default background-image gradient is applied to all <textarea> elements, which can be disabled using background-image: none.
Before Firefox 89, manipulating the content of <textarea> elements using Document.execCommand() commands requires workarounds (see bug 1220696).

safari_ios.notes: Unlike other major browsers, a default style of opacity: 0.4 is applied to disabled <textarea> elements.

the-textarea-element.title: <textarea>: The Textarea element

the-tfoot-element.name: tfoot
the-tfoot-element.summary: The <tfoot> HTML element defines a set of rows summarizing the columns of the table.
the-tfoot-element.title: <tfoot>: The Table Foot element

the-th-element.name: th
the-th-element.summary: The <th> HTML element defines a cell as the header of a group of table cells. The exact nature of this group is defined by the scope and headers attributes.
the-th-element.title: <th>: The Table Header element

the-thead-element.name: thead
the-thead-element.summary: The <thead> HTML element defines a set of rows defining the head of the columns of the table.

safari.notes: Backgrounds applied to <thead> elements will be applied to each table cell, rather than the entire header. To mimic the behavior of other browsers, set the background-attachment CSS property to fixed.

the-thead-element.title: <thead>: The Table Head element

the-time-element.name: time
the-time-element.summary: The <time> HTML element represents a specific period in time. It may include the datetime attribute to translate dates into machine-readable format, allowing for better search engine results or custom features such as reminders.
the-time-element.title: <time>: The (Date) Time element

the-title-element.name: title
the-title-element.summary: The <title> HTML element defines the document's title that is shown in a browser's title bar or a page's tab. It only contains text; tags within the element are ignored.
the-title-element.title: <title>: The Document Title element

the-tr-element.name: tr
the-tr-element.summary: The <tr> HTML element defines a row of cells in a table. The row's cells can then be established using a mix of <td> (data cell) and <th> (header cell) elements.
the-tr-element.title: <tr>: The Table Row element

the-track-element.name: track
the-track-element.summary: The <track> HTML element is used as a child of the media elements, <audio> and <video>. It lets you specify timed text tracks (or time-based data), for example to automatically handle subtitles. The tracks are formatted in WebVTT format (.vtt files)  Web Video Text Tracks.
the-track-element.title: <track>: The Embed Text Track element

the-u-element.name: u
the-u-element.summary: The <u> HTML element represents a span of inline text which should be rendered in a way that indicates that it has a non-textual annotation. This is rendered by default as a simple solid underline, but may be altered using CSS.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 4, this element implemented the HTMLSpanElement interface instead of the standard HTMLElement interface.

the-u-element.title: <u>: The Unarticulated Annotation (Underline) element

the-ul-element.name: ul
the-ul-element.summary: The <ul> HTML element represents an unordered list of items, typically rendered as a bulleted list.
the-ul-element.title: <ul>: The Unordered List element

the-var-element.name: var
the-var-element.summary: The <var> HTML element represents the name of a variable in a mathematical expression or a programming context. It's typically presented using an italicized version of the current typeface, although that behavior is browser-dependent.
the-var-element.title: <var>: The Variable element

the-video-element.name: video
the-video-element.summary: The <video> HTML element embeds a media player which supports video playback into the document. You can use <video> for audio content as well, but the <audio> element may provide a more appropriate user experience.
the-video-element.title: <video>: The Video Embed element

the-wbr-element.name: wbr
the-wbr-element.summary: The <wbr> HTML element represents a word break opportunitya position within text where the browser may optionally break a line, though its line-breaking rules would not otherwise create a break at that location.
the-wbr-element.title: <wbr>: The Line Break Opportunity element

the-accesskey-attribute.name: accesskey
the-accesskey-attribute.summary: The accesskey global attribute provides a hint for generating a keyboard shortcut for the current element. The attribute value must consist of a single printable character (which includes accented and other characters that can be generated by the keyboard).
the-accesskey-attribute.title: accesskey

attr-autocapitalize.name: autocapitalize
attr-autocapitalize.summary: The autocapitalize global attribute is an enumerated attribute that controls whether and how text input is automatically capitalized as it is entered/edited by the user.
attr-autocapitalize.title: autocapitalize

attr-fe-autocomplete.name: autocomplete
attr-fe-autocomplete.summary: The HTML autocomplete attribute lets web developers specify what if any permission the user agent has to provide automated assistance in filling out form field values, as well as guidance to the browser as to the type of information expected in the field.

notes: In Chrome 66, support was added for the <textarea> and <select> elements.
Originally only supported on the <input> element.
Chrome does not accept off as a value. See bug 587466.
In Chrome 66, support was added for the <textarea> and <select> elements.
Originally only supported on the <input> element.
Chrome does not accept off as a value. See bug 587466.

attr-fe-autocomplete.title: HTML attribute: autocomplete

dom-fe-autofocus.name: autofocus
dom-fe-autofocus.summary: The autofocus global attribute is a Boolean attribute indicating that an element should be focused on page load, or when the <dialog> that it is part of is displayed.

chrome.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

firefox.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

ie.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

opera.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

opera_android.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

safari.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

edge_blink.notes: Supported for the <button>, <input>, <select>, and <textarea> elements.

dom-fe-autofocus.title: autofocus

global-attributes:classes-2.name: class
global-attributes:classes-2.summary: The class global attribute is a space-separated list of the case-sensitive classes of the element. Classes allow CSS and JavaScript to select and access specific elements via the class selectors or functions like the DOM method document.getElementsByClassName.
global-attributes:classes-2.title: class

attr-contenteditable.name: contenteditable
attr-contenteditable.summary: The contenteditable global attribute is an enumerated attribute indicating if the element should be editable by the user. If so, the browser modifies its widget to allow editing.
attr-contenteditable.title: contenteditable

attr-data-*.name: data_attributes
attr-data-*.summary: The data-* global attributes form a class of attributes called custom data attributes, that allow proprietary information to be exchanged between the HTML and its DOM representation by scripts.
attr-data-*.title: data-*

the-dir-attribute.name: dir
the-dir-attribute.summary: The dir global attribute is an enumerated attribute that indicates the directionality of the element's text.
the-dir-attribute.title: dir

the-draggable-attribute.name: draggable
the-draggable-attribute.summary: The draggable global attribute is an enumerated attribute that indicates whether the element can be dragged, either with native browser behavior or the HTML Drag and Drop API.
the-draggable-attribute.title: draggable

attr-enterkeyhint.name: enterkeyhint
attr-enterkeyhint.summary: The enterkeyhint global attribute is an enumerated attribute defining what action label (or icon) to present for the enter key on virtual keyboards.
attr-enterkeyhint.title: enterkeyhint

the-hidden-attribute.name: until-found_value
the-hidden-attribute.summary: The hidden global attribute is an enumerated attribute indicating that the browser should not render the contents of the element. For example, it can be used to hide elements of the page that can't be used until the login process has been completed.
the-hidden-attribute.title: hidden

the-hidden-attribute.name: hidden
the-hidden-attribute.summary: The hidden global attribute is an enumerated attribute indicating that the browser should not render the contents of the element. For example, it can be used to hide elements of the page that can't be used until the login process has been completed.
the-hidden-attribute.title: hidden

global-attributes:the-id-attribute-2.name: id
global-attributes:the-id-attribute-2.summary: The id global attribute defines an identifier (ID) which must be unique in the whole document. Its purpose is to identify the element when linking (using a fragment identifier), scripting, or styling (with CSS).

firefox.notes: id is a true global attribute only since Firefox 32.

global-attributes:the-id-attribute-2.title: id

the-inert-attribute.name: inert
the-inert-attribute.summary: The inert global attribute is a Boolean attribute indicating that the browser will ignore the element. With the inert attribute, all of the element's flat tree descendants (such as modal <dialog>s) that don't otherwise escape inertness are ignored. The inert attribute also makes the browser ignore input events sent by the user, including focus-related events and events from assistive technologies.
the-inert-attribute.title: inert

attr-inputmode.name: inputmode
attr-inputmode.summary: The inputmode global attribute is an enumerated attribute that hints at the type of data that might be entered by the user while editing the element or its contents. This allows a browser to display an appropriate virtual keyboard.
attr-inputmode.title: inputmode

attr-is.name: is
attr-is.summary: The is global attribute allows you to specify that a standard HTML element should behave like a defined custom built-in element (see Using custom elements for more details).

safari.notes: See bug 182671.

attr-is.title: is

attr-itemid.name: itemid
attr-itemid.summary: The itemid global attribute provides microdata in the form of a unique, global identifier of an item.
attr-itemid.title: itemid

names:-the-itemprop-attribute.name: itemprop
names:-the-itemprop-attribute.summary: The itemprop global attribute is used to add properties to an item. Every HTML element can have an itemprop attribute specified, and an itemprop consists of a name-value pair. Each name-value pair is called a property, and a group of one or more properties forms an item. Property values are either a string or a URL and can be associated with a very wide range of elements including
names:-the-itemprop-attribute.title: itemprop

attr-itemref.name: itemref
attr-itemref.summary: Properties that are not descendants of an element with the itemscope attribute can be associated with an item using the global attribute itemref.
attr-itemref.title: itemref

attr-itemscope.name: itemscope
attr-itemscope.summary: itemscope is a boolean global attribute that defines the scope of associated metadata. Specifying the itemscope attribute for an element creates a new item, which results in a number of name-value pairs that are associated with the element.
attr-itemscope.title: itemscope

attr-itemtype.name: itemtype
attr-itemtype.summary: The global attribute itemtype specifies the URL of the vocabulary that will be used to define itemprop's (item properties) in the data structure.
attr-itemtype.title: itemtype

attr-lang.name: lang
attr-lang.summary: The lang global attribute helps define the language of an element: the language that non-editable elements are written in, or the language that the editable elements should be written in by the user. The attribute contains a single "language tag" in the format defined in RFC 5646: Tags for Identifying Languages (also known as BCP 47).
attr-lang.title: lang

attr-nonce.name: nonce
attr-nonce.summary: The nonce global attribute is a content attribute defining a cryptographic nonce ("number used once") which can be used by Content Security Policy to determine whether or not a given fetch will be allowed to proceed for a given element.
attr-nonce.title: nonce

the-popover-attribute.name: popover
the-popover-attribute.summary: The popover global attribute is used to designate an element as a popover element.
the-popover-attribute.title: popover

attr-slot.name: slot
attr-slot.summary: The slot global attribute assigns a slot in a shadow DOM shadow tree to an element: An element with a slot attribute is assigned to the slot created by the <slot> element whose name attribute's value matches that slot attribute's value.
attr-slot.title: slot

attr-spellcheck.name: spellcheck
attr-spellcheck.summary: The spellcheck global attribute is an enumerated attribute that defines whether the element may be checked for spelling errors.
attr-spellcheck.title: spellcheck

the-style-attribute.name: style
the-style-attribute.summary: The style global attribute contains CSS styling declarations to be applied to the element. Note that it is recommended for styles to be defined in a separate file or files. This attribute and the <style> element have mainly the purpose of allowing for quick styling, for example for testing purposes.
the-style-attribute.title: style

attr-tabindex.name: tabindex
attr-tabindex.summary: The tabindex global attribute allows developers to make HTML elements focusable, allow or prevent them from being sequentially focusable (usually with the Tab key, hence the name) and determine their relative ordering for sequential focus navigation.
attr-tabindex.title: tabindex

the-title-attribute.name: title
the-title-attribute.summary: The title global attribute contains text representing advisory information related to the element it belongs to.
the-title-attribute.title: title

attr-translate.name: translate
attr-translate.summary: The translate global attribute is an enumerated attribute that is used to specify whether an element's translatable attribute values and its Text node children should be translated when the page is localized, or whether to leave them unchanged.
attr-translate.title: translate

coep.name: Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy
coep.summary: The HTTP Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy (COEP) response header configures embedding cross-origin resources into the document.
coep.title: Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy

the-coop-headers.name: Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy
the-coop-headers.summary: The HTTP Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy (COOP) response header allows you to ensure a top-level document does not share a browsing context group with cross-origin documents.
the-coop-headers.title: Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy

autoplay-feature.name: autoplay
autoplay-feature.summary: The HTTP Permissions-Policy header autoplay directive controls whether the current document is allowed to autoplay media requested through the HTMLMediaElement interface.
autoplay-feature.title: Permissions-Policy: autoplay

autoplay-feature.name: autoplay
autoplay-feature.summary: The HTTP Permissions-Policy header autoplay directive controls whether the current document is allowed to autoplay media requested through the HTMLMediaElement interface.
autoplay-feature.title: Permissions-Policy: autoplay

policy-controlled-features.name: document-domain
policy-controlled-features.summary: The HTTP Permissions-Policy header document-domain directive controls whether the current document is allowed to set document.domain.
policy-controlled-features.title: Permissions-Policy: document-domain

the-x-frame-options-header.name: X-Frame-Options
the-x-frame-options-header.summary: The X-Frame-Options HTTP response header can be used to indicate whether or not a browser should be allowed to render a page in a <frame>, <iframe>, <embed> or <object>. Sites can use this to avoid click-jacking attacks, by ensuring that their content is not embedded into other sites.
the-x-frame-options-header.title: X-Frame-Options

early-hints.summary: The HTTP 103 Early Hints information response may be sent by a server while it is still preparing a response, with hints about the resources that the server is expecting the final response will link. This allows a browser to start preloading resources even before the server has prepared and sent that final response.

chrome.notes: Supported in HTTP/2 and later (SPDY/QUIC)

firefox.notes: Supported in HTTP1.0 and later
Supported in HTTP1.0 and later

edge_blink.notes: Supported in HTTP/2 and later (SPDY/QUIC)

early-hints.title: 103 Early Hints

serializable-objects.name: serializable_object
serializable-objects.summary: Serializable objects are objects that can be serialized and later deserialized in any JavaScript environment ("realm"). This allows them to, for example, be stored on disk and later restored, or cloned with structuredClone(), or shared between workers using DedicatedWorkerGlobalScope.postMessage().

notes: Version 103 serialized properties: name, message, cause, fileName, lineNumber and columnNumber.
Version 104 adds serialization of stack in the main thread (window.postMessage() and structuredClone()).
Version 110 adds serialization of stack in workers (worker.postMessage() and structuredClone()).

incumbent-settings-object-tracking-in-pr.name: incumbent_settings_object_tracking
incumbent-settings-object-tracking-in-pr.summary: The Promise object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
incumbent-settings-object-tracking-in-pr.title: Promise

hostgetimportmetaproperties.name: resolve
hostgetimportmetaproperties.summary: import.meta.resolve() is a built-in function defined on the import.meta object of a JavaScript module that resolves a module specifier to a URL using the current module's URL as base.

nodejs.notes: Returns a Promise.

hostgetimportmetaproperties.title: import.meta.resolve()

hostgetimportmetaproperties.name: import_meta
hostgetimportmetaproperties.summary: The import.meta meta-property exposes context-specific metadata to a JavaScript module. It contains information about the module, such as the module's URL.
hostgetimportmetaproperties.title: import.meta

attr-fieldset-disabled.name: fieldset#attr-disabled
attr-fieldset-disabled.summary: The <fieldset> HTML element is used to group several controls as well as labels (<label>) within a web form.

ie.notes: Not all form control descendants of a disabled fieldset are properly disabled in IE11; see IE bug 817488: input[type='file'] not disabled inside disabled fieldset and IE bug 962368: Can still edit input[type='text'] within fieldset[disabled].

attr-fieldset-disabled.title: <fieldset>: The Field Set element

attr-iframe-sandbox.name: iframe#attr-sandbox
attr-iframe-sandbox.summary: The <iframe> HTML element represents a nested browsing context, embedding another HTML page into the current one.
attr-iframe-sandbox.title: <iframe>: The Inline Frame element

attr-iframe-srcdoc.name: iframe#attr-srcdoc
attr-iframe-srcdoc.summary: The <iframe> HTML element represents a nested browsing context, embedding another HTML page into the current one.
attr-iframe-srcdoc.title: <iframe>: The Inline Frame element

attr-img-crossorigin.name: crossorigin
attr-img-crossorigin.summary: The crossorigin attribute, valid on the
attr-img-crossorigin.title: HTML attribute: crossorigin

attr-img-srcset.name: img#attr-srcset
attr-img-srcset.summary: The HTML element embeds an image into the document.
attr-img-srcset.title: : The Image Embed element

attr-input-maxlength.name: attr-input-maxlength#attr-maxlength
attr-input-maxlength.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.

caniuse.title: maxlength attribute for input and textarea elements

attr-input-maxlength.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

attr-input-minlength.name: attr-input-minlength#attr-minlength
attr-input-minlength.summary: The <input> HTML element is used to create interactive controls for web-based forms in order to accept data from the user; a wide variety of types of input data and control widgets are available, depending on the device and user agent. The <input> element is one of the most powerful and complex in all of HTML due to the sheer number of combinations of input types and attributes.

caniuse.title: Minimum length attribute for input fields

attr-input-minlength.title: <input>: The Input (Form Input) element

attr-ol-reversed.name: ol#attr-reversed
attr-ol-reversed.summary: The <ol> HTML element represents an ordered list of items  typically rendered as a numbered list.
attr-ol-reversed.title: <ol>: The Ordered List element

attr-script-async.name: script#attr-async
attr-script-async.summary: The <script> HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The <script> element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.
attr-script-async.title: <script>: The Script element

attr-script-defer.name: script#attr-defer
attr-script-defer.summary: The <script> HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The <script> element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.

chrome.notes: Chrome does not defer scripts with the defer attribute when the page is served as XHTML (application/xhtml+xml) - Chromium Issue #611136, Chromium Issue #874749

firefox.notes: Since Firefox 3.6, the defer attribute is ignored on scripts that don't have the src attribute. However, in Firefox 3.5 even inline scripts are deferred if the defer attribute is set.

ie.notes: Before version 10, Internet Explorer implemented defer by a proprietary specification. Since version 10 it conforms to the W3C specification.

edge_blink.notes: Chrome does not defer scripts with the defer attribute when the page is served as XHTML (application/xhtml+xml) - Chromium Issue #611136, Chromium Issue #874749

attr-script-defer.title: <script>: The Script element

attr-script-type.name: script#attr-type
attr-script-type.summary: The <script> HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The <script> element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.
attr-script-type.title: <script>: The Script element

attributes-for-form-submission.name: form#Attributes_for_form_submission
attributes-for-form-submission.summary: The <form> HTML element represents a document section containing interactive controls for submitting information.
attributes-for-form-submission.title: <form>: The Form element

canvasimagesource.name: CanvasImageSource
canvasimagesource.summary: The CanvasRenderingContext2D interface, part of the Canvas API, provides the 2D rendering context for the drawing surface of a <canvas> element. It is used for drawing shapes, text, images, and other objects.
canvasimagesource.title: CanvasRenderingContext2D

channel-messaging.name: Channel_Messaging_API
channel-messaging.summary: The Channel Messaging API allows two separate scripts running in different browsing contexts attached to the same document (e.g., two IFrames, or the main document and an IFrame, two documents via a SharedWorker, or two workers) to communicate directly, passing messages between one another through two-way channels (or pipes) with a port at each end.

nodejs.notes: Must be imported from the worker_threads module.

channel-messaging.title: Channel Messaging API

channel-messaging.name: Using_channel_messaging
channel-messaging.summary: The Channel Messaging API allows two separate scripts running in different browsing contexts attached to the same document (e.g., two <iframe> elements, the main document and a single <iframe>, or two documents via a SharedWorker) to communicate directly, passing messages between each other through two-way channels (or pipes) with a port at each end.

nodejs.notes: Must be imported from the worker_threads module.

channel-messaging.title: Using channel messaging

client-side-form-validation.name: Form_validation
client-side-form-validation.summary: Client-side form validation sometimes requires JavaScript if you want to customize styling and error messages, but it always requires you to think carefully about the user. Always remember to help your users correct the data they provide. To that end, be sure to:
client-side-form-validation.title: Client-side form validation

cors-settings-attributes.name: crossorigin
cors-settings-attributes.summary: The crossorigin attribute, valid on the
cors-settings-attributes.title: HTML attribute: crossorigin

crossDocumentMessages.name: postMessage
crossDocumentMessages.summary: The window.postMessage() method safely enables cross-origin communication between Window objects; e.g., between a page and a pop-up that it spawned, or between a page and an iframe embedded within it.

notes: Firefox 8 and up supports sending File and FileList objects between windows. This is only allowed if the recipient's principal is contained within the sender's principal for security reasons.

Before Firefox 6, the message parameter must be a string. Since Firefox 6, the message parameter is serialized using the structured clone algorithm. This means you can pass a broad variety of data objects safely to the destination window without having to serialize them yourself.

ie.notes: IE10 had an important limitation: see this article for details.
Support only for <frame> and <iframe>.

crossDocumentMessages.title: Window: postMessage() method

custom-elements.name: Using_custom_elements
custom-elements.summary: One of the key features of the Web Components standard is the ability to create custom elements that encapsulate your functionality on an HTML page, rather than having to make do with a long, nested batch of elements that together provide a custom page feature. This article introduces the use of the Custom Elements API.
custom-elements.title: Using custom elements

dnd.name: dnd#HTML_Drag_and_Drop_API
dnd.summary: HTML Drag and Drop interfaces enable applications to use drag-and-drop features in browsers.
dnd.title: HTML Drag and Drop API

dom-input-indeterminate.name: HTMLInputElement#indeterminate
dom-input-indeterminate.summary: The HTMLInputElement interface provides special properties and methods for manipulating the options, layout, and presentation of <input> elements.
dom-input-indeterminate.title: HTMLInputElement

downloading-resources.name: download
downloading-resources.summary: The HTMLAnchorElement.download property is a string indicating that the linked resource is intended to be downloaded rather than displayed in the browser. The value, if any, specifies the default file name for use in labeling the resource in a local file system. If the name is not a valid file name in the underlying OS, the browser will adjust it.
downloading-resources.title: HTMLAnchorElement: download property

drawing-text-to-the-bitmap.name: CanvasRenderingContext2D
drawing-text-to-the-bitmap.summary: The CanvasRenderingContext2D interface, part of the Canvas API, provides the 2D rendering context for the drawing surface of a <canvas> element. It is used for drawing shapes, text, images, and other objects.
drawing-text-to-the-bitmap.title: CanvasRenderingContext2D

event-handler-attributes.name: Event_handlers
event-handler-attributes.summary: Events are signals fired inside the browser window that notify of changes in the browser or operating system environment. Programmers can create event handler code that will run when an event fires, allowing web pages to respond appropriately to change.
event-handler-attributes.title: Event handling (overview)

fakepath-srsly.name: file
fakepath-srsly.summary: <input> elements with type="file" let the user choose one or more files from their device storage. Once chosen, the files can be uploaded to a server using form submission, or manipulated using JavaScript code and the File API.
fakepath-srsly.title: <input type="file">

forms.name: forms#Forms
forms.summary: This page lists all the HTML elements, which are created using tags.
forms.title: HTML elements reference

global-attributes.name: Global_attributes
global-attributes.summary: Global attributes are attributes common to all HTML elements; they can be used on all elements, though they may have no effect on some elements.
global-attributes.title: Global attributes

mathml.name: mathml#Inline_SVG_and_MathML_support
mathml.summary: To build websites, you should know about HTML  the fundamental technology used to define the structure of a webpage. HTML is used to specify whether your web content should be recognized as a paragraph, list, heading, link, image, multimedia player, form, or one of many other available elements or even a new element that you define.
mathml.title: Structuring the web with HTML

ping.name: a#attr-ping
ping.summary: The <a> HTML element (or anchor element), with its href attribute, creates a hyperlink to web pages, files, email addresses, locations in the same page, or anything else a URL can address.
ping.title: <a>: The Anchor element

rel-icon.name: Link_types#icon
rel-icon.summary: The rel attribute defines the relationship between a linked resource and the current document. Valid on <link>, <a>, <area>, and <form>, the supported values depend on the element on which the attribute is found.

chrome.notes: If both ICO and PNG are available, will use ICO over PNG if ICO has better matching sizes set. (Per caniuse.com.).

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 83, the crossorigin attribute is not supported for rel="icon".

opera.notes: In version 15 and later (Blink-based Opera), if both ICO and PNG are available, will use ICO over PNG if ICO has better matching sizes set. (Per caniuse.com.)

safari.notes: If both ICO and PNG are available, will ALWAYS use ICO file, regardless of sizes set. (Per caniuse.com.)

safari_ios.notes: Does not use favicons at all (but may have alternative for bookmarks, etc.). (Per caniuse.com.)

edge_blink.notes: If both ICO and PNG are available, will use ICO over PNG if ICO has better matching sizes set. (Per caniuse.com.).

rel-icon.title: HTML attribute: rel

pseudo-classes.name: Pseudo-classes
pseudo-classes.summary: A CSS pseudo-class is a keyword added to a selector that specifies a special state of the selected element(s). For example, the pseudo-class :hover can be used to select a button when a user's pointer hovers over the button and this selected button can then be styled.
pseudo-classes.title: Pseudo-classes

sections.name: Document_and_website_structure#HTML_for_structuring_content
sections.summary: At this point, you should have a better idea about how to structure a web page/site. In the last article of this module, we'll learn how to debug HTML.
sections.title: Document and website structure

server-sent-events.name: Server-sent_events
server-sent-events.summary: Traditionally, a web page has to send a request to the server to receive new data; that is, the page requests data from the server. With server-sent events, it's possible for a server to send new data to a web page at any time, by pushing messages to the web page. These incoming messages can be treated as Events + data inside the web page.
server-sent-events.title: Server-sent events

shared-workers-introduction.name: SharedWorker
shared-workers-introduction.summary: The SharedWorker interface represents a specific kind of worker that can be accessed from several browsing contexts, such as several windows, iframes or even workers. They implement an interface different than dedicated workers and have a different global scope, SharedWorkerGlobalScope.
shared-workers-introduction.title: SharedWorker

the-pattern-attribute.name: pattern
the-pattern-attribute.summary: The pattern attribute specifies a regular expression the form control's value should match. If a non-null value doesn't conform to the constraints set by the pattern value, the ValidityState object's read-only patternMismatch property will be true.
the-pattern-attribute.title: HTML attribute: pattern

the-xhtml-syntax.name: the-xhtml-syntax#XHTML
the-xhtml-syntax.summary: XHTML is a term that was historically used to describe HTML documents written to conform with XML syntax rules.

webstorage.summary: The Web Storage API provides mechanisms by which browsers can store key/value pairs, in a much more intuitive fashion than using cookies.

webstorage.summary: The Web Storage API provides mechanisms by which browsers can securely store key/value pairs.

workers.name: Web_Workers_API
workers.summary: Web Workers makes it possible to run a script operation in a background thread separate from the main execution thread of a web application. The advantage of this is that laborious processing can be performed in a separate thread, allowing the main (usually the UI) thread to run without being blocked/slowed down.

notes: Is a Node EventEmitter instead of DOM EventTarget.
Worker script environment expects CommonJS modules or ECMAScript modules.
Must be imported from the worker_threads module.

workers.title: Web Workers API

workers.name: Using_web_workers
workers.summary: Web Workers are a simple means for web content to run scripts in background threads. The worker thread can perform tasks without interfering with the user interface. In addition, they can perform I/O using XMLHttpRequest (although the responseXML and channel attributes are always null) or fetch (with no such restrictions). Once created, a worker can send messages to the JavaScript code that created it by posting messages to an event handler specified by that code (and vice versa).
workers.title: Using Web Workers
